<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia-Kidnap     07-01 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Kidnap,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leftist Guerrillas Kidnap U.S. Oil Executive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Friday they were still
searching for the manager of a U.S. oil company who was kidnapped
by leftist guerrillas this week for a $2 million ransom.
   Giacomo (Jake) Gambini, 42, an Italian-born U.S. citizen, was
abducted by leftist guerrillas Monday as he left his office in
Sabana de Torres, 200 miles north of Bogota, police in the
Department of Santander said.
   They said the rebels belonged to the pro-Cuban National
Liberation Army and were demanding $2 million in ransom.
   Gambini's hometown in the United States was not immmediately
available. In a telephone interview with The Associated Press
Friday night, Charles Gambini of Galveston, Texas, confirmed that
his brother Jake had been kidnapped in Colombia, but refused to
comment further.
   Police said Gambini worked for the Piper company, which
according to industry sources provides technical advice to
companies searching for oil in northeast Colombia.
   The National Liberation Army has attacked several oil pipelines
and abducted technicians in an attempt to pressure the Colombian
government to cancel contracts with foreign petroleum companies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
