<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 2352EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a BC-Jazz     07-01 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Jazz,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Buddy Rich Celebrated at Jazz Festival</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Buddy swung,'' singer Joe Williams said Friday
before opening the JVC Jazz Festival concert celebrating the music
of the late drummer and band leader Buddy Rich.
   ``He drummed the impossible drum,'' Mike Greene, president of
the National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences, said in giving
a citation of merit to Rich's daughter Cathy Rich, who produced the
concert.
   The evening at Carnegie Hall was a mixture of the classy and the
homey. Williams and Mel Torme sang impeccably and with warmth.
Louis Bellson played a couple of exciting and varied drum solos.
There were film clips of Rich in the late 1930s and early 1940s
with the Artie Shaw and Tommy Dorsey bands.
   Williams sang ``There Will Never Be Another You'' and
``Honeysuckle Rose'' in front of the Buddy Rich Big Band. Torme
included ``Here's That Rainy Day,'' which he said was Rich's
favorite from a 1978 album they made, ``Together Again for the
First Time.''
   Cathy Rich sang a song praising her father while slides from the
family scrapbook were shown. The last number was the lengthy ``Two
in One Suite,'' with Rich's drumming recorded in Las Vegas in 1968
and the band playing. Annie Ross and Dominick Allen, souding very
good, sang new, sometimes treacly lyrics in praise of Rich.
   Also appearing were saxophonist Stan Getz, who played Thad
Jones' ``Yours and Mine,'' which he and Rich once heard together at
the Village Vanguard, and singers Jon Hendricks and Company and
Marlena Shaw.
   Rich, who died in 1987 at age 69, was a self-taught drummer
credited with ``the fastest hands in the world.'' His career
spanned vaudeville, the Big Band era and decades on the road.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
