<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 0132EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-TheReagans     07-01 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-The Reagans,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagans Talk About Themselves On British TV</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ronald and Nancy Reagan recall the white lies they
told each other on their first date, and Reagan's daughter,
Maureen, remembers her surprise when a friend told her she found
the U.S. president sexy.
   These are a few of the tidbits of Reagan lore that British
television viewers will see on July 8, when the first of a
three-part series on the life of Reagan is broadcast.
   The film, shown to journalists Thursday, is filled with varied
assessments of Reagan.
   To Secretary of State George P. Shultz, the president is ``a
revolutionary and he's changed the agenda (in) the most sweeping
presidency in this country probably since Franklin Roosevelt.''
   Former budget director David Stockman calls Reagan's economic
policies ``the singular greatest episode of sustained economic
mismanagement in the 20th-century history of the United States.''
   But Mrs. Reagan says of her husband: ``I think he made people
feel good about themselves, good about the country. We now have a
strong economy, unemployment is down, interest rates are down. ...''
   The film traces Reagan to his Midwestern boyhood, interviewing
friends and schoolmates.
   Actress Olivia de Havilland recalls Reagan and the late actor
Errol Flynn lining up as soldiers so that Flynn's shoulder obscured
Reagan.
   She says Reagan quietly kicked the sand into a mound, ``higher
and higher, and finally, when the photographer said, `All right
everybody, let's smile,' the future president of the United States
stepped up on the mound and towered over Errol Flynn.''
   Interviewer Godfrey Hodgson asked Reagan why he spied for the
FBI on colleagues in the Screen Actors Guild of which he was
president.
   ``They (the FBI) came wanting some advice, some findings on
people that I had dealt with, and I got an insight into what was
happening to the motion picture business. It did give me a real
understanding of the communist menace,'' Reagan says.
   Mrs. Reagan recalls their first date when, mutually wary, they
both said they had ``early morning calls'' so that they could leave
early if they didn't like each other.
   They got home at 2:30 a.m, she says. ``I think by that time both
of us knew that neither one us of had an early morning call.''
   Maureen Reagan, Reagan's daughter by his first marriage to
actress Jane Wyman, says a friend who saw Reagan doing a TV ad
dressed as a cowboy exclaimed to her that ``he's so sexy.''
   ``I said, my father sexy? You must be kidding. `No no, he's
wonderful.' And he is wonderful,'' Miss Reagan says.
   During his 50-minute interview, Reagan describes his wife as ``a
helpmeet such as I think every man dreams of having, a relationship
that sort of matches your dreams of marriage when you were an
adolescent.''
   He laughs about claims that she interferes in policy-making.
   ``She doesn't go down and get involved in affairs like
disarmament or anything else. She advises me of what she thinks is
good for me, and I feel free to confide in her the things that are
going on.
   ``As a matter of fact she's a help just by my knowing that she's
up there when I go to meet her at the end of the day.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
