<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Smith     07-01 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Smith,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Challenger Widow Fears for Next Shuttle Crew</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow of space shuttle Challenger pilot
Michael Smith, who sued the makers of shuttle rockets blamed for
the Challenger explosion, says she will be praying for the safety
of the next shuttle crew.
   Shuttle Discovery _ which has undergone 210 modifications and
seven months of delay _ will be the first shuttle flight since
Challenger exploded in January 1986 killing all seven aboard. The
launch is scheduled for Sept. 4.
   ``I'll be saying my prayers for the crew and their families,''
Jane Smith told The Houston Post after giving a tearful deposition
on Wednesday to lawyers for U.S. government contractor Morton
Thiokol. ``I hope they'll be safe.''
   Mrs. Smith and her three children are the only relatives of the
Challegner crew who haven't settled a lawsuit with the government
or Thiokol. Last May, the 42-year-old widow filed a $1.5 billion
wrongful death suit against Thiokol, the government and the
director of NASA's solid rocket booster program.
   Since then, a Florida federal judge has denied two of her three
claims _ that Thiokol be banned from supplying booster rockets for
NASA shuttles and that the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration be named as a defendant in the lawsuit.
   Mrs. Smith's remaining claim _ which will be heard in a Virginia
federal court Sept. 12 _ is aimed at Thiokol's decision to
recommend the ill-fated launch.
   A leaking seal on one of the booster rockets was blamed for the
Challenger explosion.
</TEXT>
