<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua-Sentences     07-01 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua-Sentences,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Sentenced For Passing Secrets To U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three former government officials and
a Nicaraguan businessman have been sentenced for passing economic
secrets to the United States, news reports said.
   The pro-government Nuevo Diario newspaper said Thursday that
Nora Aldana Centeno, a former planning official, and Mario Jose
Alegria Castillo, an official of the Superior Council of Private
Enterprise, were sentenced Wednesday to 16 years for passing secret
economic documents to U.S. Embassy officials.
   They were arrested in late May and were accused of ``taking
documents with the classification `secret,''' the paper said.
   Alegria Castillo, director of the council's Institute of
Economic and Social Research, also was charged with organizing ``a
network of informants in some Nicaraguan state institutions,'' it
added.
   Pedro Su Olivas, a Central Bank official, and Adrian Espinales,
of the Commerce and Industry Ministry, each drew a three-year term
for providing the information to Algeria which then passed it to
the United States.
   The opposition newspaper La Prensa called the 16-year sentences
``barbaric'' and said lawyers for all four defendants planned to
appeal.
   It quoted lawyers for Aldana Centeno and Alegria Castillo as
saying their clients had been convicted of a non-existent crime
because Nicaragua has no laws about revealing secret documents.
</TEXT>
