<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 0154EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Children     07-01 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Children,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 1 Million Children Official Non-Entities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than one million children in China
officially do not exist because they were born outside state birth
control targets, rendering them unable to receive food rations,
schooling and job assignments, an official report said.
   The children, most of whom are under age 10, are commonly
referred to as ``black children.'' They are children whose parents
did not have their births registered or who were refused
registration by local authorities, the People's Daily reported
Thursday.
   Under China's one-child policy, officials in each county are
responsible for ensuring that each woman has only one child and
that the number of births in the county does not exceed the birth
target set by the state.
   Parents are penalized for having more than one child, and
officials are penalized if the county goes over the number of
births that it is allowed. Officials, however, are financially
rewarded if births stay within the target.
   Some parents did not register births of their second or
subsequent children to avoid paying the fine, the paper said. Fines
vary from region to region, but are generally $270 or more per year
for five years, a huge fine by Chinese standards.
   Some local officials, seeing their bonuses jeapordized by too
many births, simply refuse to register new babies, the paper said.
   In one city in southwestern China's Sichuan province, local
officials refused to register the births of 450 babies because the
birth target had already been reached, the report said.
   Without a residence permit, children are deprived of the rights
of a Chinese citizen. They do not receive their ration of rice and
edible oil, are unable to register for school and will not be able
to get a job, join the military or sit for college entrance exams
when they grow up, the newspaper said.
   The problem will become even greater when these children marry
and have children of their own, who also will be unable to get
residence permits, it said.
   The situation is most serious in the provinces of Hebei,
Shandong, Jiangxi and Guizhou. In each of these provinces, ``black
children'' number more than 70,000, the report said.
   State officials have called attention to the problem, saying
that the children are innocent victims, the newspaper reported.
   They said the situation not only hurts the children, it also
affects the nation's family planning and population control efforts
and creates social problems.
   China's birth rate hit 2 percent in 1986 and stayed there last
year. If the trend continues, China's population of 1.08 billion
will double by the year 2030, according to the United Nations Fund
for Population Activities.
   China has said that it must keep the birth rate at 1.5 percent
if it is to meet its goal of keeping the population under 1.2
billion by the year 2000.
   China will mark Asia's Three Billion Population Day today. In a
televised speech for the occasion Chinese Premier Li Peng said
Thursday, ``The country has listed family planning as one of its
basic national policies and taken the control of population growth
as a strategic task.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880701-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 0223EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NicaraguaPoll     07-01 0693</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua Poll,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaraguans Critical of Sandinistas, Appreciate Soviet Union,
Dislike U.S.</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Interamerican, 5th graf, is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many Nicaraguans are critical of their leftist
government and don't believe it is democratic, but they think
Soviet policies are better than those of the United States,
according to a private poll.
   A survey presented Thursday as the first independent poll of
Nicaraguan opinion under nine years of Sandinista rule indicates
strong support for President Daniel Ortega, 85 percent opposition
to U.S. Contra aid, and 68 percent disapproval of U.S. policies in
Central America.
   Asked what they most admire about the United States, 42 percent
of those polled said ``nothing,'' which was the most prevalent
answer.
   The Reagan administration for the past seven years has supported
rebels attempting to overthrow the Nicaraguan government.
   The poll of 1,129 adults in Nicaragua was sponsored by the
Catholic University in Managua and research groups in California
and Mexico.
   William Bollinger, director of the cosponsoring Interamerican
Research Center of Los Angeles, said the newly formed, private
Nicaraguan Institute of Public Opinion used accepted scientific
polling methods, employing students at Catholic University, which
he described as the nation's most politically neutral university.
The students interviewed 1,129 adults selected at random in five
types of Managua neighborhoods on June 4-5.
   Bollinger did not offer a margin of error for the poll but he
said at a news conference that several steps were taken to ensure
its integrity and objectivity.
   But he did note that many educated people who might have given
anti-Sandinista views have fled to the United States, with their
homes taken over by government officials and military officers. He
said about 27 percent of those polled worked for the government,
and they were the most supportive of the Sandinistas.
   Thirty-eight percent of the respondents believed the ruling
Sandinistas' management of the Nicaraguan economy has been either
bad or terrible, while 36 percent described it as fair, and only 22
percent said it was good or excellent.
   Seventy-four percent of those interviewed said they rated their
family's economic situation worse than a year ago, while only 7
percent said it was better.
   Forty-eight percent said they did not consider the Sandinista
government democratic while 40 percent said they did. But there was
general support for Sandinista peace efforts and the government's
foreign policies.
   A majority supported incorporation of the Contras into the
country's political life but most of those interviewed also said
they doubted the fighting would end soon.
   The overall results show the U.S. economic blockade of
Nicaragua, along with U.S. support for the Contra rebels, has
alienated even many anti-Sandinista Nicaraguans, Bollinger said.
   The Soviet Union received higher positive responses than the
United States among all income levels on several questions, with
higher-income groups being more pro-Soviet and pro-Sandinista than
poorer and less-educated Nicaraguans.
   Future polls _ the research group plans one of people in several
Latin American countries later this year _ will attempt to obtain
more detail about reaction to Soviet policies, said Bollinger.
   Only 1 percent of the respondents described U.S. Central
American policy as excellent, 7 percent called it good, 17 percent
said fair, 40 percent said bad and 28 percent called it terrible.
   Asked the same question about Soviet policy, 14 percent said it
was excellent, 43 percent good, 14 percent fair, 9 percent bad and
4 percent terrible.
   In evaluating Ortega's management of the government over the
last four years, 42 percent said it was good or excellent, 29
percent fair and 21 percent bad or terrible.
   Bollinger said this is a high rating in Latin American terms. He
said in a similar poll conducted in El Salvador, only 13 percent of
respondents gave President Jose Napoleon Duarte a good or excellent
rating.
   The poll showed that 28 percent of those interviewed claimed
affiliation with the ruling Sandinista party, 9 percent with
liberal or conservative opposition parties and 59 percent said they
belonged to no party.
   Bollinger said the Nicaraguan government did not interfere with
the survey even though laws apparently are still on the books
prohibiting independent polling in the country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
