<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ElectricBoat     07-01 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Electric Boat,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Electric Boat Employees Go On Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GROTON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 10,200 Electric Boat employees
went on strike at the company's shipyard here Friday after contract
talks with the submarine builder broke down.
   ``We expect the strike to be strong and well-supported,'' said
Robert Manning, a lawyer for the Metal Trades Council.
   Electric Boat, a division of General Dynamics Corp., is one of
only two shipyards making nuclear submarines for the Navy, and the
only manufacturer of subs capable of carrying the giant Trident
ballistic missile.
   Talks broke down at 11:20 p.m. Thursday after a three-hour
last-ditch effort, and the walkout began after midnight.
   No new talks were planned.
   Earlier in the day, the Navy awarded this year's third and final
SSN-688 fast-attack submarine contract to Electric Boat. The $347.4
million contract will go to EB's main shipyard in here and its
other plant, in North Kingstown, R.I.
   The strike does not affect the Rhode Island plant.
   In a letter to employees, shipyard General Manager Fritz G.
Tovar said a strike will not stop submarine construction at the
shipyard here. EB arranged to assign 3,000 salaried employees to
shipyard jobs in the event of a strike.
   The two sides stalemated over the union's demand for percentage
wage increases and the shipyard's insistence that it could afford
no more than cash bonuses to remain competitive in its pursuit of
Navy contracts.
   Union members voted earlier Thursday 4,921 to 3,140 to reject
the company's latest offer but returned to the bargaining table
with 4{ hours to go before the strike deadline in a last-ditch
effort to reach a settlement.
   Talks began in November to replace a three-year contract that
expired Friday. The last strike at the shipyard was in 1975, when
the union walked out for five months and the region's economy
sagged.
   In Hartford, state Labor Commissioner Betty Tianti said she
would meet on Friday with members of the state's congressional
delegation and others to see what could be done to lessen the
economic impact of the strike.
   The union wanted straight hourly wage increases of 5 percent, 4
percent and 4 percent over three years.
   Electric Boat's ``last, best and final offer,'' presented
Monday, calls for bonuses totaling $4,250 over three years for a
first-class mechanic making $12.02 an hour, said Thomas Sotir, vice
president of human resources.
   The company cited increased competition from the only other
submarine shipyard in the country, the Newport News Shipbuilding
and Drydock Co. of Virginia.
   Newport News, which pays its workers 60 cents an hour less than
Electric Boat, recently won two contracts for nuclear attack
submarines after it underbid Electric Boat.
   ``If the Navy wants to get into the cheapest subs around, why
don't they get Yugos?'' said Wes Lamphere, 27, of Griswold,
president of the foundry workers local. ``We don't want to make a
million bucks, we're not asking for the world. We just want to keep
up.''
</TEXT>
