<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 0231EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BlackBoxes-Commuters     07-01 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Black Boxes-Commuters,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commuter Planes to Have `Black Box' Recorders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Within three years all but the very smallest
commuter aircraft must be equipped with so-called ``black box''
recorders under a new regulation from the Federal Aviation
Administration.
   Large jetliners already are required to have the recorders which
provide information about an aircraft's performance and provide a
30-minute loop tape of conversation in the cockpit.
   The devices have been critical in finding the cause of many
airliner crashes over the years. The National Transportation Safety
Board recently cited several commuter accidents in which
investigations were hampered because adequate information was not
available.
   But commuter planes of less than 30 seats are not required to
have the devices.
   Under a final FAA rule announced Thursday, multi-engine, turbine
powered commuter planes carrying more than six passengers and flown
by two pilots will be required to have cockpit voice recorders.
   Slightly larger commuter planes carrying 20 or more passengers
will have to be equipped with digital flight data recorders that
store such information as air speed, altitude, aircraft pitch and
heading.
   Commuter airlines must have the black box recorders within three
years of the effective date of the rule, which is expected to be in
90 days.
   The cockpit voice recorders must be included in new aircraft and
retrofitted into planes already in service. The flight data
recorders must be in both new and in-service aircraft with 20 or
more seats. There is no retrofit requirement for flight data
recorders in the smaller commuter planes of less than 20 seats.
   ``Although the FDR and CVR do not enhance safety by themselves
they have proven to be invaluable accident investigation tools and
have led to numerous improvements in aviation safety,'' said FAA
Administrator Allan McArtor.
   Last year Congress directed the FAA to expand its requirements
for the ``black box'' recorders to include commuter airlines, which
last year carried about 32 million passengers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
