<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Savimbi     07-01 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Savimbi,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angolan Rebel Leader Says He's Finally Getting Support From U.S.
Blacks</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angolan rebel leader Jonas Savimbi says he has
been trying to get his message across to American blacks for seven
years and is finally making headway, even though his movement is
supported by South Africa.
   ``I can assure you here that we have made a very modest, small,
but firm start in talking to the black leaders,'' Savimbi said at
the National Press Club on Thursday.
   Before visiting Washington this week Savimbi went to Alabama and
Mississippi to seek support at black churches and from civil rights
leaders.
   He met with some success and appeared at the White House for a
meeting with President Reagan on Thursday accompanied by the Rev.
Ralph David Abernathy of the Southern Christian Leadership
Conference and a handful of other blacks.
   ``We have to do all that we can to see to Dr. Savimbi having the
support that is necessary,'' Abernathy said. ``I'm sure that he
needs our blessing and support and because of his location he is
facing many problems.''
   Savimbi has been treated as a pariah by American civil rights
leaders because his UNITA forces receive aid from South Africa in
their struggle against the Soviet-backed Angolan government.
   Opposition to him here has by no means disappeared. About 40
protesters shouting anti-Savimbi slogans demonstrated against him
in Fayette, Miss., last Saturday, and he said he encountered other
protests in the South.
   About 25 people demonstrated outside the National Press Building
during his appearance, and a man interrupted his speech from the
open door of the dining room to shout three times, ``Savimbi is a
murderer.''
   Savimbi says he first sought a meeting with the Congressional
Black Caucus in 1981 and again when he was here in 1986. He said
Thursday that he is still hoping for a meeting with the black
members of Congress this time.
   He said he wanted ``to explain the problems of UNITA in order
for the people to know, to listen and to judge. I think those are
the fundamentals of democracy.''
   Savimbi told the conservative Heritage Foundation that he saw
his first member of the caucus, Rep. Louis Stokes, D-Ohio, this
trip when Stokes chaired his meeting with the House Intelligence
Committee. He said Stokes treated him politely.
   The committee oversees U.S. aid to UNITA.
   To the criticism of his links with South Africa, Savimbi says he
opposes apartheid, but will take support from anyone willing to
give it. He says he is a Democrat who only wants freedom and
independence for his country.
   When he fought against Portuguese colonial rule of his African
homeland in the 1960s and 1970s, U.S. aid was unavailable to him
because the United States was allied with Portugal.
   So he turned to the Soviet Union, which rejected him, and then
to China, which gave him guerrilla training.
   UNITA lost to the Soviet-backed MPLA after the Portuguese left
Angola in 1975, so he retreated to the bush and sought support from
the only source available, South Africa.
   Congressional sources, who asked not to be identified, say he is
receiving an estimated $200 million to $300 million in direct South
African aid this year, plus the support of the South African
military in Angola and neighboring South-West Africa, or Namibia.
   U.S. conservatives favor his movement because of its opposition
to the Soviets. Conservatives succeeded in winning congressional
repeal of a law banning aid to UNITA and in 1986 Reagan announced
$15 million in military aid.
   While the details are classified, the aid continues and is
estimated to have climbed to between $30 million and $40 million
this year, including Stinger anti-aircraft missiles that Savimbi
credits with stopping air strikes against his headquarters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
