<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DefenseProbe-Congress     07-01 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe-Congress,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aspin Less Firm On Demand For Contract Freeze</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Les Aspin says he and Defense Secretary
Frank C. Carlucci ``are on the same wavelength'' although the
Defense Department sharply criticized Aspin's call for a freeze in
new contracts to companies mentioned in the Pentagon bribery
investigation.
   The Wisconson Democrat, chairman of the House Armed Services
Committee, said he and Carlucci spoke on the telephone late
Thursday, shortly after a Pentagon spokesman had sharply criticized
Aspin's proposal.
   ``I called him up and when he talked, we discovered that we're
on the same wavelength here,'' Aspin said. ``I don't think we're
that far apart in what we're thinking. My goal is to make sure the
contracts that are being let now, not the ones involved in the
investigation, are free of any taint. That's his goal, too.''
   Aspin had called Wednesday for a delay of six to eight weeks in
awarding contracts to firms mentioned in the 2-year-old
investigation of fraud and bribery in Pentagon weapons-buying. No
charges have yet been filed.
   But Aspin, in an interview with the Associated Press, said he's
not wedded to the six-to-eight-week time frame. ``That's just an
idea I threw out,'' he said.
   Aspin said he plans to write Carlucci a letter outlining Aspin's
proposals. ``I need to get these ideas down on paper and then he
said he'd respond.''
   But, said Aspin: ``Carlucci and I have the same goals. He said
he's got people working to come up with a way to make sure the
current contracts aren't tainted.''
   Aspin and other committee members attended a closed-door
briefing Thursday by the Naval Investigative Service about the
case. Two legislators said later they expect numerous indictments.
   Rep. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., said officials ``are very, very
sure of their case...It's pretty ironclad.''
   Rep. Larry Hopkins, R-Ky., said, ``many, many indictments will
be forthcoming.... I don't think it will be too long before the
first of them will be coming down.''
   Rear Adm. Ted Gordon, director of the NIS, detailed the case for
the legislators. He outlined a ``series of interlocking rings of
people, kind of like the Olympic flag,'' in which several groups
operated independently, according to one source, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Earlier, the Pentagon had rejected Aspin's call for a halt. A
freeze could raise weapon costs, force plant layoffs and hurt
military readiness, said spokesman Fred S. Hoffman.
   ``We would be glad to discuss with the Congress the question of
freezing awards of new contracts while the Justice Department is
investigating allegations of procurement fraud,'' Hoffman said.
``But at this point we feel it would be imprudent to apply such a
freeze or moratorium.''
   The investigation has also spawned its first two pieces of
reform legislation.
   One would overhaul and centralize the purchasing system while
the second would try to end to the so-called ``revolving door''
between the private sector and government.
   The first measure would create a single buying office, known as
the Defense Acquisition Agency, to replace the current mix of
purchasing agencies scattered throughout the Defense Department.
   The second would require Pentagon officials to wait two years
after they quit before working for a defense contractor.
</TEXT>
