<1ST_LINE>r w PM-GunControl     07-01 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gun Control,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Judiciary Committee Approves Handgun Waiting Period</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Rifle Association says it will
try to pluck a handgun waiting-period provision out of an anti-drug
bill when the measure comes up for a vote in the House.
   ``We'll work to break it out of the drug bill on the floor and
get an up-or-down vote on that issue only,'' said James Baker, the
NRA's chief lobbyist.
   On Thursday, the House Judiciary Committee tucked an amendment
into the drug bill that would require prospective purchasers of
handguns to wait seven days before taking possession, to allow for
background checks.
   ``We will be incapable of making substantial headway in our war
against drug trafficking unless we are also prepared to disarm drug
dealers and drug traffickers and drug users,'' said Rep. Edward
Feighan, D-Ohio, who offered the waiting-period amendment.
   The proposal withstood a challenge from Rep. Bill McCollum,
R-Fla., who attempted to substitute an amendment requiring that a
system be developed to identify felons who attempt to buy firearms.
The McCollum substitute was defeated 22-12, and the waiting period
was then approved by a voice vote.
   Feighan noted that Republicans on the committee did not ask for
a recorded vote, and said that is an indication that most members
do not want to be publicly reported as opposing ``such a sensible
gun-control measure.''
   ``The NRA is losing credibility in this institution and
nationally because they have opposed the most reasonable efforts at
gun control,'' said Feighan. ``Their insanity doesn't end.''
   The NRA contends that waiting periods don't work.
   ``We think that law-abiding citizens will be the only ones
affected and criminals will continue to evade the law,'' Baker said.
   During the waiting period, law enforcement agencies could try to
determine whether a prospective buyer has a criminal record or a
record of mental incompetency.
   The measure would exempt those who present dealers with
certificates from police stating that the purchasers' lives have
been threatened.
   Twenty-two states have some form of waiting periods, with
California having the longest at 15 days. The amendment would
supersede less stringent state waiting-period laws, but leave
stronger laws standing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
