<DOCNO> AP880701-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 0235EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Garbage     07-01 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Garbage,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britains in Tussle Over Proposed U.S. Garbage Shipments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government leaders are fretting over a plan to
import millions of tons of U.S. household trash to a dump in
northwest England.
   One lawmaker said in Thursday's debate in Parliament that the
United States should look into disposing its waste in its own
deserts rather than in Britain. Legislator Chris Taylor said he
feared creating the 130-foot-high dump on 390 acres in his home
constituency of Warrington could introduce U.S. crop diseases into
the area.
   ``Who would pick up the bill if the Colorado beetle infected the
Cheshire potato crop?,'' he asked.
   Americans should find a place ``in their deserts, perhaps, to
deal with their own garbage, rather than add to our own
environmental problems,'' said Taylor of Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher's governing Conservative Party.
   The garbage is to be shipped from the East Coast of the United
States at the rate of 1.5 million to 2 million tons a year for five
years by a British company, Power Water and Waste, according to
Environment Undersecretary Colin Moynihan.
   Several African nations have recently expressed outrage over
dumping of waste from Western countries, including the United
States, within their borders.
   In one case, the government of Guinea in West Africa said it
found 15,000 tons of toxic ash shipped from Philadelphia and dumped
on an island off its coast by a Norwegian company.
   Nigeria recently announced it was posting vigilantes around its
coast to block such dumping by foreign countries.
   Moynihan defended disposing of foreign waste in Britain as a
``legitimate trade.''
   But he said this particular plan ``gives grave cause for
concern.'' He said the waste ``is undoubtedly different in kind and
scale from the imports we have received so far.''
   He said U.S. household garbage contains garden and food waste,
so imports ``must involve the risk of pests and diseases being
carried with it,'' he said.
   The Cheshire County Council approved the plan, and Moynihan said
he would be holding talks later with that body.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
