<1ST_LINE>u a AM-StateEmployeesStrike     07-01 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-State Employees Strike,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Largest State Workers' Union Goes On Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE McGRAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A union representing 12,000 state
clerical workers and counselors went on strike at midnight
Thursday, its president said.
   Paul Krissel, president of the Pennsylvania Social Services
Union, said 56 percent of Pennsylvania's second-largest state
employees union voted to reject a three-year contract offer.
   Krissel said the strike would affect statewide operations in
welfare and unemployment offices, some bureaus under the Department
of Labor and Industry, and some counseling services in prisons and
mental institutions.
   He said the strike would become evident when offices opened in
the morning and picket lines went up outside. The bulk of the
membership is in Philadelphia and Pittsburgh and surrounding areas,
the union president said.
   John Taylor, a spokesman for Gov. Robert Casey, said supervisors
and non-striking employees will keep offices open.
   ``We're prepared to do whatever we have to do to maintain
services,'' the governor said at an afternoon briefing.
   PSSU struck for two days in 1985 and three weeks in 1975.
   At issue is the state's effort to institute a two-tier wage
scale and vacation package that the union said discriminates
against new employees and those at the lower end of the scale,
Krissel said.
   ``We seek a fair across-the-board wage increase for all workers,
as well as some added financial recognition for loyal, longer-term
employees,'' he said.
   Although 25 percent of the employees represented by the union
are not members, Krissel said he expected they would honor picket
lines. Union members in supervisory positions, about 2,000 people,
are barred from striking, he added.
   The state's largest union, the American Federation of State,
County and Municipal Employees, ratified a three-year contract with
the state last week.
</TEXT>
