<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--CrossBurning     07-01 0167</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Cross Burning,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vigilantes Try to Burn Man on Wooden Cross</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Slum dwellers tied a man accused of burglary
to a 40-foot wooden cross, whipped him and tried to burn him alive,
but police rescued him, a newspaper said.
   Residents of Hauscar, a shantytown outside Lima, bound
20-year-old Jorge Arce to a stake which they dubbed the ``cross of
justice,'' the government newspaper La Cronica said Thursday.
   The vigilantes held him there for six hours, beating and
whipping him. They also doused him with cold water and shaved part
of his head.
   Police saved the victim as residents placed kindling at his
feet, and he was not seriously hurt, the report said. Authorities
refused comment, and it was unknown if he had been charged with any
crimes.
   Arce had been caught robbing a home early Wednesday, the report
said.
   Local residents formed vigilante groups in their crime-plagued
area after police cut patrols, according to Jorge Salvador,
spokesman for the Hauscar Neighborhood Association.
</TEXT>
