<DOCNO> AP880701-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 0140EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-AMARdp 1stLd-Writethru a0683 07-01 0776</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AMA Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0683,0793</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AMA Approves AIDS Policies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with approval of policy to
violate confidentiality in some cases with AIDS patients. Picks up
5th graf, `Dr. Don...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Medical Association on Thursday
called on the states to trace the sexual partners of people
infected with the AIDS virus and urged prisons to test inmates for
exposure to the deadly disease.
   In addition, the AMA urged doctors, as a last resort, to breach
confidentiality rules and warn sexual partners of AIDS patients.
   The AMA approved the measures by voice vote along with a package
of other AIDS proposals before adjourning its annual policy-making
convention.
   ``I think that contact tracing (of sexual partners), at least in
the heterosexual community, has the potential to substantially
reduce the proliferation and spread of AIDS,'' said Dr. James
Sammons, executive vice president of the 295,000-member AMA.
   The AMA's 420-member House of Delegates also approved policies
aimed at prohibiting athletes from using steroids, posting health
warnings on tanning booths, urging airlines to ban smoking on all
domestic flights and evaluating whether health warnings should be
required on alcoholic beverages.
   The delegates passed an amendment that says doctors, as a last
resort, have an obligation to depart from their Hippocratic vow of
confidentiality to warn sexual partners of persons infected with
the AIDS virus.
   The policy says that doctors should try to persuade patients who
are infected with the virus to inform their sexual partners. If the
infected person refuses, the doctor should report the person to the
local public health department so the officials can warn the sexual
partners, under the policy.
   ``And if that fails, the doctor should tell the people who are
at risk directly,'' said Dr. M. Roy Schwarz, chairman of the AMA's
AIDS Task Force and the association's assistant executive vice
president for medical education and science.
   Dr. Don Chaplin, a delegate from Burlington, N.C., warned that
doctors must emphasize the need to protect the identities of AIDS
victims.
   ``I caution us to be very careful to do anything we can to
protect confidentiality and to fight any discrimination because it
would thwart our efforts to bring this disease under control,''
Chaplin said.
   The doctors' organization renewed its call for mandatory
AIDS-virus testing of all inmates because of the problems of
intravenous drug use and homosexuality in prisons, practices that
spread the disease.
   The AMA adopted a similar prison-testing proposal last year and
reapproved it Thursday despite objections from several doctors that
it would accomplish little.
   The doctors approved what Chaplin said would be ``broad
expansions on contact tracing'' of sexual partners to slow the
spread of AIDS among heterosexuals.
   Sammons said contact tracing had been effective in reducing such
other sexually transmitted diseases as syphilis and gonorrhea.
   The delegates also called on federal and state governments to
expand treatment programs for intravenous drug abusers because they
pose the most explosive potential for spreading AIDS into the
heterosexual population.
   By 1991, the nation likely will have 270,000 cases of acquired
immune deficiency syndrome, said an AMA progress report issued
during the convention. There is no known cure for the disease.
   Some of the other AIDS policies approved by the AMA call for
vigorous enforcement of existing anti-discrimination laws to
protect AIDS victims against bias in employment, housing and other
areas; and urge women to avoid breast feeding if they are infected
with the AIDS virus to reduce the chance of giving the disease to
their children.
   Another measure calls for the U.S. president to keep public
attention focused on the epidemic by creating a new national AIDS
commission, identical to the one that just finished its work.
   Such a panel would be a clearinghouse for AIDS research and
``provide the essential coordination between public and private
institutions that are addressing AIDS,'' the AMA said.
   In other action:
   _The rapid growth of the commercial tanning industry _ with an
estimated 17,500 parlors nationwide _ prompted the AMA to declare
that tanning booths ``pose potentially significant health risks.''
   Delegates voted to lobby the federal government to require
warnings in tanning parlors about the increased risks of skin
cancer caused by prolonged exposure to ultraviolet light in tanning
booths.
   _Delegates continued their longtime war on tobacco use, urging
commercial airlines to ban smoking on all domestic flights. Federal
regulations now prohibit smoking on flights of two hours or less.
   _The AMA urged state legislatures to prohibit athletes from
using steroids to enhance physical prowess. Improper use of
steroids poses dangerous risks such as impairment of a person's
sexual functions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
