<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 0317EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UPIVote     07-01 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UPI Vote,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wire Service Guild Ratifies One-Year Contract With UPI</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wire Service Guild members at
United Press International voted 95-31 to ratify a one-year
contract with UPI, Guild President Kevin Keane said.
   UPI President Paul Steinle said Thursday's vote ``signals the
beginning of an era of peace between the guild and management, and
it's one more message to the news industry that we are here for the
long haul.''
   The vote, which came after 15 months of negotiations, was
counted at the guild's office in New York and announced during the
55th annual convention of The Newspaper Guild, the parent union of
the wire service local.
   The contract, which runs through July 1, 1989, covers about 700
UPI editorial and other employees in the United States.
   The agreement was reached May 26 with a new guild negotiating
team that took over after another team quit May 9 in a dispute with
the guild's executive committee.
   The old contract expired in April 1987. The new pact replaces
work rules imposed by the company when it declared an impasse Nov.
1.
   Three months after that, operating control of the financially
troubled news wire service was transferred from Mexican publisher
Mario Vazquez Rana to WNW Group, a media investment company whose
chairman is Earl W. Brian and whose president is Steinle.
   Keane said that with a wage increase that took effect Nov. 1 and
another scheduled for Nov. 1, 1988, the top minimum pay under the
new contract will be $670 a week starting in the employee's eighth
year of service. Under the old contract, top scale was $585 a week,
starting in the sixth year.
   The new pact also improves pensions, restores job security and
union dues checkoffs, and continues a health insurance plan put in
effect after Nov. 1, Keane said.
   The guild loses its agency shop provision, under which employees
had to pay a fee to the union as a condition of employment, Keane
said.
   ``The executive committee and the negotiating committee were
certain this was the best contract available to UPI employees,''
Keane said.
   Charles Dale, president of the parent Newspaper Guild, called it
``a settlement about which I can't say I'm proud, but ... an
agreement that was necessary _ necessary for us to survive and
equally necessary for UPI to obtain the breathing space needed to
regain the viability that has been so sorely in question.''
   The company, which lost $20 million in 1987, announced March 30
it would seek to reach profitability by eliminating 150 jobs,
focusing on business news and embarking on joint electronic
ventures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
