<2ND_LINE>PM-Ex-President-Graft,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Arrest Of Ex-president Accused Of Corruption</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge ordered the
arrest of former President Salvador Jorge Blanco if he does not
return from the United States within 15 days to face corruption
charges.
   Judge Juan Maria Severino Tejada announced Wednesday that he
ordered any qualified Dominican authority to try to capture Jorge
Blanco if he does not return. The judge's order also stated that
Jorge Blanco will be tried in absentia if he does not appear in
court within 15 days.
   Dominican authorities allowed the former president, who
complained of a heart condition, to fly to Atlanta in May 1987 for
medical treatment.
   Jorge Blanco, who was president from 1982-86, is one of nearly
20 former government officials accused of widespread corruption
during the former president's administration. They are accused of
misusing government funds to buy military equipment at inflated
prices and embezzling money from a public food program.
   The corruption investigation was ordered by President Joaquin
Balaguer after he took office. Blanco has called the charges
``political persecution.''
   It was unknown whether the former president intended to heed the
judicial order or remain in exile.
