<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Australia-USBribes     07-01 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Australia-US Bribes,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Government Official Jailed For Taking Bribes from US Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Australian government
employee was sentenced today to 15 months in jail after he admitted
taking bribes from an American aviation company. The Australian
manager of the firm also was jailed.
   Melbourne County Court Judge Mervyn Kimm said Leonard Calder
Freeman took bribes of unknown value while working as a purchasing
officer at the Australian Federal Government Aircraft Factory in
Melbourne.
   Freeman, 60, on Thursday pleaded guilty to seven counts of
taking bribes between 1983 and 1986.
   The former Australian general manager of the North Hollywood,
Calif.-based Citicorp Aviation Industry Resources Inc., Werner
Gunther Becker, also pleaded guilty Thursday to seven counts of
paying the bribes. Becker, 30, was sentenced today to 12 months.
   The judge said Freeman was paid 5 percent of the value of orders
for aircraft parts placed with the U.S. firm.
   ``You were in a position of trust and responsibility and you
grossly failed in that trust and responsibility,'' Kimm told
Freeman. ``You admitted in a police interview that you knew what
you were doing was against the law, but nevertheless you
continued.''
   Kimm said Freeman had had a similar agreement with the firm's
previous general manager, who died in 1983.
   The previous general manager had worked for a firm that was
taken over by Citicorp Aviation Industry Resources.
   At the man's funeral, Freeman approached Becker to see if the
deal was to continue, the judge said.
   Testimony indicated Becker contacted superiors in the United
States who advised him to continue to pay Freeman.
   The judge said Freeman gave the firm details of quotes provided
by other firms, and in some cases was able to place smaller orders
directly with the U.S. firm.
   Kimm set a minimum non-parole term of nine months for Freeman
and six months for Becker.
</TEXT>
