<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Political Arm of Nation's Largest Teacher Union Backs Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The political action committee of the
National Education Association, the nation's largest teacher's
union, has given Democratic presidential hopeful Michael Dukakis
its backing for his party's nomination.
   The decision came Thursday during a closed-door meeting of NEA's
political action committee prior to the teacher group's annual
convention scheduled in New Orleans next week.
   Dukakis ``believes in and supports a view and a vision of
education policy consistent with our efforts to assure every child
a quality education,'' said NEA president Mary Hatwood Futrell.
   The endorsement, which applies only to the Democratic
nomination, won't become official until today, when the NEA board
of directors is scheduled to meet and is almost certainly to concur
with NEA-PAC's choice.
   NEA officials said the 1.9 million-member union plans to withold
a final presidential endorsement until Sept. 8, after both parties
have held their conventions.
   Dukakis picked up his first formal labor endorsement on
Wednesday from the 59,000-member National Treasury Employees Union,
a group that represents mostly federal Internal Revenue Service and
Customs Service workers.
