<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     07-01 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Hits High of Year, Stock Prices Plunge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar hit its highest levels of the year
against the Japanese yen in Tokyo during Friday morning trading,
continuing its recent advance. Stock prices took a plunge.
   The dollar opened at 133.57 yen, up a strong 1.37 yen from its
previous day closing, and rose rapidly to end the week at 134.50
yen, up 2.30 yen from Thursday's close.
   It was the dollar's highest level since reaching about 133.95
yen on Dec. 2.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, the market's main barometer, shed 265.87 points,
or 0.95 percent, to close at 27,503.53.
   An exchange dealer at a major commercial bank, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said the local market seemed to be testing
whether Japan's central bank would take any action to stem the
dollar's rise.
   Earlier this week, Japanese monetary authorities, including
Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa, said the Bank of Japan would step
into the market if necessary to brake the dollar's upswing.
   But dealers said the central bank had not yet intervened to prop
up the yen and said the currency might fall even further against
the dollar.
   ``We see the dollar rising to the 135-yen range,'' said Nikko
Securities' Yoshio Ogawa.
</TEXT>
