<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0464 07-01 0673</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0464,0688</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Extends Truce, Proposes New Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Shultz discussing economic
aid to Nicaragua during talks in Guatemala. PICKS up 5th graf,
`Contra commander ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega said Secretary
of State George P. Shultz's trip to Central America could reignite
Nicaragua's civil war and that Sandinista troops will be on guard
despite the renewal of a truce.
   Ortega said Thursday he was extending a unilateral cease-fire
until July 31. He also proposed new peace talks with the
U.S.-backed Contra rebels, which have been fighting the leftist
government since 1981.
   The rebels have not yet replied to his proposal for a new round
of talks in Managua July 27-29.
   In Guatemala City, Shultz and leaders of the Nicaraguan
Resistance on Thursday discussed reviving the talks and using a
carrot-and-stick approach with the Sandinistas.
   Contra leader Alfredo Cesar said they talked about offering U.S.
aid to the Sandinistas to induce them to enact promises of
democratic reforms. They also discussed renewed military aid to the
rebels if the Sandinista refused.
   Contra commander Enrique Bermudez, who met with Shultz, said the
cease-fire announcement was not important. He said the rebels have
said all along that they have no intention of resuming the fighting
but will defend themselves if attacked.
   The rebels rejected a similar invitation for June, saying the
Nicaraguan capital did not have an ``atmosphere'' conducive to
negotiations.
   In a pastoral letter issued earlier this week, Nicaragua's
bishops pleaded with the combatants to resurrect the stalled talks
and heed the Nicaraguan people's ``heartbreaking clamor'' for peace.
   Ortega said Shultz had come to Central American bearing ``a
message loaded with hate for the people of Nicaragua, directed at
seeking how to isolate it and seek more resources in Congress to
continue the war against Nicaragua.''
   Shultz has criticized Nicaragua as a ``totalitarian society''
during his three-day trip and compared it unfavorably to the
region's four U.S.-backed democracies: Costa Rica, El Salvador,
Honduras and Guatemala.
   Ortega said ``many dramatic things can occur in the coming days
or weeks because something must come of this trip by Shultz _ a
military escalation.''
   In Washington, administration officials have said President
Reagan may ask Congress to renew military aid to the Contras.
   The United States has been funding the Nicaraguan rebels since
1981, but military aid to the Contras ran out shortly before the
peace talks began.
   Ortega spoke Thursday before 1,200 military officers and
announced the truce renewal shortly after returning from an
official visit to Cuba. His announcement came just hours before the
latest in a series of truces with the Contras was to run out.
   In Cuba, Ortega signed a $150 million assistance agreement under
which Cuba will pardon a $50 million debt and give economically
crippled Nicaragua oil, food and technical assistance with sugar
refineries and an industrial plant.
   Ortega said the pact shows ``the willingness of the Cuban people
and government to cooperate with the people and government of
Nicaragua to better face the critical situation that North American
aggression is imposing on us.
   ``While Cuba makes these decisions, the American government acts
in a contrary line,'' he said.
   The United States regards Cuba and Nicaragua as the hemisphere's
prime communist threats and has trade embargoes against both
nations.
   Ortega called his decision to extend the truce a ``demonstration
of common sense and responsibility because we don't want to give up
the possibility of a negotiated solution.''
   ``But this does not mean that we are going to let down our guard
... because we know that they (the Contras) are not going to keep
their word and are infiltrating forces from Honduras.''
   The Contras and the Sandinistas agreed to a 60-day truce and
peace talks on March 23. Ortega later renewed the cease-fire and
the Contras agreed to go along. Since then, talks between the two
sides have broken down and each has accused the other of violating
the truce.
</TEXT>
