<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NorthernIreland     07-01 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northern Ireland,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Taxi Driver Severely Injured In Police-Guerrilla Cross Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas attacked a police
station with guns and rocket-propelled grenades early today, and a
taxi driver was wounded in the crossfire.
   Police said the guerrillas made a getaway in a car. The
guerrillas and police were not injured and the police station was
not badly damaged.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility, but suspicion fell
on the Irish Republican Army.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA is fighting to end British rule in
Northern Ireland and unite the predominantly Protestant province
with the overwhelmingly Catholic Irish Republic under socialist
rule.
   The 46-year-old cab driver was taken to a hospital and received
emergency surgery, a police spokesman said on condition of
anonymity.
   The spokesman did not say whether the cab driver was hit by
police shooting or by shooting by the guerrillas. The victim
appeared to have driven into the crossfire by accident.
   The British Broadcasting Corp. reported that a woman passenger
in the cab at the time was not injured.
   Police said they recovered a Soviet-made rocket-propelled
grenade-launcher, a grenade, two radios and ammunition from the
scene.
   On Tuesday, an IRA bomb exploded in a school bus carrying 12
girls, seriously injuring one of them.
   Police said the bomb was intended for the driver of the bus, a
part-time soldier. He was cut in the face and eyes. The IRA claimed
responsibility for the attack and said it regretted injuring the
14-year-old girl.
</TEXT>
