<1ST_LINE>r i PM-KoreansKilled     07-01 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koreans Killed,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korean Construction Workers Killed In Iraqi Raid On Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iraqi raid on a gas plant
construction site in Iran has left 13 South Korean construction
workers dead and 37 others injured, Daelim Industrial Co. reported
today.
   The South Korean contractor said the raid occurred Thursday in
Kangan, a town on the coast of the Persian Gulf about 550 miles
south of Iran's capital, Tehran.
   Officials said that eight Iraqi Air Force planes bombed the area
Thursday morning, firing six rockets and strafing the area with
machine gun fire, according to reports from Daelim's construction
manager in Kangan.
   The injured workers have been evacuated to hospitals on the
nearby coastal city of Bushehr, the officials said.
   Tehran's official Islamic Republic New Agency, monitored in
Nicosia, Cyprus, said Iraqi jets bombed ``an industrial-labor
complex'' on Iran's southern gulf coast, killing or wounding an
unspecified number of workers and causing some damage.
   Daelim has been building the gas plant under a $180-million
contract with Iran. Officials in South Korea said it was not known
yet how much damage was inflicted upon the plant under
construction. About 400 Korean workers reportedly were on the
project.
   South Korean Foreign Minister Choi Kwang-soo said South Korea
would take ``necessary diplomatic steps'' against Iraq as soon as
detailed information was obtained on the incident.
</TEXT>
