<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 0455EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WoodstoveParty     07-01 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Woodstove Party,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vermont Castings Retires Its Answer to the Model T</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANDOLPH, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's largest maker of woodstoves
threw a party to mark the demise of its popular Defiant model, the
victim of environmental regulations effective today that require
new stoves to burn more cleanly.
   ``The Defiant is a symbol of the end of an era,'' Vermont
Castings Inc. Chairman Duncan Syme said Thursday, calling the
woodstove his company's answer to the Model T.
   Syme decided to forego the gnashing of teeth and complaints
about government regulation. Instead, his company designed some new
stoves and threw a big party for the company's retiring mainstay.
   Born in 1975 of the energy crisis, a back-to-the-land ethic and
a desire by many to thumb their noses at OPEC and the big oil
companies, the Defiant quickly became a symbol of a lifestyle. More
than 130,000 stoves have been sold.
   Syme was an architect who was trying in the early '70s to
integrate woodstoves into some of his designs. ``We looked around
and didn't see any good ones,'' he said.
   He got together with his now deceased brother-in-law Murray
Howell, a Wall Street investment banker.
   ``We sensed that there was a consumer need for a good-looking
stove (on which) you could open the doors and celebrate this thing
of bringing flame into your livingroom,'' Syme said.
   They caught the market's wave just before it swelled and the
company became an overnight success. Sales have declined since the
heyday, but Syme said the company has settled into a comfortable
niche marketing colorful new stoves, often to upscale city dwellers
and suburbanites who want a livingroom showpiece.
   Thanks to the Defiant, Vermont Castings grew to become the
nation's largest woodstove manufacturer and now employs about 400
people, most of them at plants in Randolph and nearby Bethel.
   Responding to environmental concerns over woodsmoke pollution
and the new regulations, the company has introduced two new models
designed to cut down on particulates and some of the gasses in
woodsmoke.
   The new EPA rules require stove makers to cut particulates in
smoke by 77 percent effective today, and by 81 percent from the
pre-1988 standard in 1990. Vermont Castings officials, wary of a
patchwork of regulations in states concerned about winter haze,
helped the EPA devise the new rules, said David Kimbell, the
company's vice president for marketing.
   The new stoves meet the standards by burning wood more
efficiently, Kimbell said, adding that the company has been working
with a catalytic combuster designed to burn most of the woodsmoke.
   Syme, 50, who wore a straw hat and bow tie Thursday as he
addressed the crowd of Vermont dignitaries, company employees and
dealers who milled about among balloons, ale and other props under
yellow-and-white-striped party tents.
   ``This is like a commencement,'' he said. ``It's as if we've had
a fun time together these last four years in the ivy halls ... and
I think we're on the threshold of a new and exciting future.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
