<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel OKs Bill on Sale of Cable Programming</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rural satellite dish owners moved one step
closer to legally receiving cable television programming with a
House subcommittee vote approving a bill giving independent
distributors rights to sell the scrambled programming.
   The bill was approved Thursday by a narrow 13-11 vote of the
House Energy and Commerce telecommunications subcommittee, with
many supporters saying they would prefer the industry work out its
own solution.
   ``We are not convinced there is a true marketplace at work,''
said committee chairman Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass.
   Under the bill, approved 13-11, any cable programmer that sells
its programming to at least one distributor other than a cable
operator would have to make that programming available to all other
distributors.
   Congress has been concerned that some cable programmers have
been unwilling to sell their programming to third-party
distributors, thus shutting out potential competitors.
   But ``the fate of this legislation rests as much in the hand of
the affected industries as it does in the hand of Congress,''
Markey said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Voice of America Writer Sues To Publish Article Without Agency
Review</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A writer for the Voice of America says that
she should not be required to obtain prior approval from the
government to publish an article accusing the Reagan administration
of politicizing agency broadcasts.
   Carolyn Weaver on Thursday filed suit challenging federal
regulations that require Voice of America employees to get
government approval to publish articles or make speeches about U.S.
foreign policy or the agency's operation.
   Weaver's suit, the first court challenge to the rules, charges
that the clearance requirement is a form of prior restraint
prohibited by the First Amendment, according to her attorney,
Stephen M. Kohn.
   The regulations give the government the right to delete passages
or stop publication of publication of material it considers
``inaccurate, inconsistent with current foreign policy, or can
reasonably be expected to affect adversely U.S. foreign relations.''
   Employees must submit all books or manuscripts ``of official
concern'' for clearance by the U.S. Information Agency, which
operates the Voice of America. The regulation also covers employees
of the State Department and the Agency for International
Development.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Common Cause Assails Proposed Tax Break On Lawmakers' Homes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government watchdog group says members of
Congress should not be given a bigger tax deduction on their homes.
   ``We strongly urge you to resist any efforts to repeal or
increase the deduction for living expenses for members of
Congress,'' said Fred Wertheimer, president of Common Cause, in a
letter sent Thursday to a House tax-writing committee.
   ``This action would ... enhance preferential tax treatment for
members of Congress that is available to no other taxpayer,''
Wertheimer added.
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowsk, D-Ill., has proposed a repeal of the
$3,000 limit on deductibility for members' Washington living
expenses as part of a plan to allow higher congressional salaries
in exchange for banning acceptance of speaking fees.
