<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Revival of Private Vietnam Aid Program Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oxfam America, a nonprofit agency engaged in
relief, development and other humanitarian activity overseas, has
announced it will receive a U.S. government license to revive
private aid operations in Vietnam, ending a four-year ban.
   ``The action taken today by the U.S. government seems to
represent a significant step toward improved relations with
Vietnam,'' said today's announcement by Oxfam executive director
John Hammock. ``Vietnam's war with America may be over, but its war
with poverty is not.''
   The announcement said the group would provide $112,000 for three
programs in Vietnam to improve agricultural production and the
quality of rural life: $57,700 to support the Cantho University
agricultural research center in the Mekong Delta, $19,140 to
provide a generator and tools for the Van To Agricultural Tools
Workshop in Hai Hung Province and $35,065 to equip an irrigation
system in Thuong Kiet village in Hai Hung province to water 778
acres of rice land and to drain 1383 acres.
