<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Dukakis-Budget     07-01 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Budget,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Massachusetts' Fiscal Year Ends With No Budget _ Or Governor _ In
Sight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Republicans criticized Gov. Michael
S. Dukakis for campaigning for president out of state the day the
state's fiscal year ended with a nearly $400 million deficit and no
new budget in sight.
   The Dukakis administration has acknowledged that the state
government was technically $397 million short of funds for fiscal
1988, which ended Thursday, due to an unexpected slowdown in tax
payments and the cost of court-ordered corporate tax abatements.
   The shortfall comes at an awkward time for Dukakis, the probable
Democratic presidential nominee, who has stressed his managerial
skills on the campaign trail. For the last several years
Massachusetts has had only budget surpluses.
   To address the problem, the governor filed a supplemental budget
with the Legislature containing a 20-point plan to tap cash
reserves and make bookkeeping adjustments to close the $397 million
gap.
   But House Minority Leader Steven Pierce charged Thursday that it
was ``inconceivable'' that the Democratic governor would be out of
state campaigning with the budget crisis unresolved.
   Dukakis spokesman Steve Crawford said the governor would be
working in his office today, Saturday and possibly Monday.
   ``He is in constant contact with his office. His chief of staff
and his secretary of administration and finance are regularly
discussing the budget process with legislative leaders,'' Crawford
said.
   In recent years, the state government has often gone several
days or even weeks into a new fiscal year without a budget, which
must be balanced under the state constitution.
   Administration and Finance Secretary Frank Keefe said the
government could keep functioning without a budget through
Wednesday, when millions of dollars in checks must be issued to
cover the state payroll, welfare payments and other obligations.
   Lawmakers are nearing final approval of a series of tax bills
and fee-raising measures that would help pay for expanded state
spending projected for fiscal 1989.
   Meanwhile Thursday, the state Revenue Department was busy
opening envelopes in a drive to collect every possible tax dollar
that can be attributed to fiscal 1988 to help cover the $397
million deficit.
   For the coming year, the House and Senate have endorsed separate
budgets that call for spending approximately $11.8 billion, or
about 8 percent more than fiscal 1988. But the two versions differ
in details, and a team of negotiators plans to work through Tuesday
on a compromise.
   Dukakis and the Democratic legislative leaders have agreed on a
spending target of $11.8 billion next year, and they have embarked
on a program of at least $200 million in higher taxes, fines and
fees to support the higher spending.
   Dukakis already has signed a $40 million cigarette tax measure.
The House passed and sent to the Senate three more revenue bills
that would raise another $163 million by bringing the state income
tax back into conformance with federal rules, by closing a
corporate tax ``loophole,'' raising fines for traffic violations,
increasing wetlands filing fees and claiming unclaimed soft drink
and beer bottle deposits.
   Republicans have charged that Dukakis is knowingly
overestimating state revenues in order to claim that the budget is
in balance.
</TEXT>
