<DOCNO> AP880701-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 0506EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDS-HealthWorkers     07-01 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS-Health Workers,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Researchers Studying Use Of AZT By Health Care Workers Exposed To
AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some doctors and other health workers
exposed to the AIDS virus are taking the drug AZT as a preventive
measure, despite potentially serious side effects associated with
the anti-AIDS medication.
   AZT _ the only federally approved anti-AIDS drug _ can cause
muscle aches, nausea, headaches and severe anemia. Additionally,
medical experts have mixed opinions about using AZT, now known as
zidovudine, to prevent infection after exposure.
   Dr. Julie Gerberding of San Francisco General Hospital said she
is often asked whether the side effects of AZT outweigh the chances
of infection after a health worker is pricked with an AIDS-tainted
needle.
   ``I've been bombarded with calls from health care workers around
the country,'' said Gerberding, who is directing a study on the
risk of AIDS infection among health workers.
   Researchers believe AZT may keep the AIDS virus from installing
itself on the genetic material of cells if the drug is taken soon
after exposure, thus preventing AIDS infection. However, the
medical community is split over whether the drug should be
administered before a patient develops AIDS symptoms.
   Dr. Paul Volberding, an AIDS authority at San Francisco General,
said the odds of AIDS infection in a health care worker with a deep
cut who comes in contact with the virus may run as high as one in
100. He said 22 health workers worldwide have become accidentally
infected.
   Last month, Burroughs Wellcome Co., the only maker of AZT, began
a nationwide study of health workers accidentally exposed to the
virus.
   Karen Collins, a spokeswoman for the drug company, said workers
are required to enroll within five days of exposure. Half will
receive a six-week supply of the drug free of charge and half will
get a placebo, she said.
   Researchers at the National Institutes of Health in Bethesda,
Md., said Thursday they are seeking approval from the federal Food
and Drug Administration for a similar study that could start within
a month. The NIH study, which would concentrate on workers facing
``massive exposures'' to the virus, would not use placebos, said
Debbie Katz, who is coordinating the project.
   Gerberding said she knew two workers at her hospital who took
AZT after being exposed to the AIDS virus through tainted blood.
   William Owen, a doctor in private practice who treats AIDS
patients, said he prescribed the drug to a surgeon who cut his hand
with a scalpel while operating on a patient with acquired immune
deficiency syndrome.
   Since patients may acquire AZT through their personal
physicians, the number of people taking the drug as a preventive
measure is not known.
   ``Like everything else with AIDS, it's quasi-underground,'' said
Dr. June Fisher, who runs the city's Center of Municipal
Occupational Safety and Health, a health clinic.
   Volberding said he has enough faith in the drug's efficacy that
he could not in good conscience advise AIDS-exposed workers to
enroll in the Burroughs Wellcome study because he'd be afraid they
would get the placebo.
   However, Dr. Martin Hirsch of Massachusetts General Hospital
said if he was accidentally exposed to the virus he probably would
enroll in the Burroughs Wellcome study rather than take the drug on
his own.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880701-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 0508EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-KidnappedChild     07-01 0735</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kidnapped Child,0755</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Abducted Child Returns Home with Parents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN LEHMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 2-year-old who was kidnapped as a
baby and adopted by an Israeli couple returned home clutching her
Brazilian parents and a teddy bear.
   Her mother said she would someday allow her child to decide if
she wants to meet her adoptive parents in Israel, even though her
lawyer said the Tel Aviv couple knew something was amiss in the
adoption.
   Bruna Vasconcelos arrived Thursday at Sao Paulo's international
airport with her parents, Rosilda and Luis Vasconcelos, on a flight
from London. They had stopped there en route from Tel Aviv.
   ``I feel as if Bruna and I never had been separated, that she
was never kidnapped,'' the child's mother told reporters while the
brown-haired girl played with their tape recorders and microphones.
The child also smiled and waved.
   The Vasconcelos' two-year ordeal started Oct. 13, 1986, when
their child, then 4 months old, was abducted from their home in the
southern city of Curitiba. One year later, the child was located in
Israel, and the couple regained custody after a court battle with
her adoptive parents.
   Asked if she would one day allow Bruna to visit her former
adoptive parents, Mrs. Vasconcelos said: ``When she is older, I
will tell her the whole story of what happened to her. Then she
will be able to decide on her own whether or not she wants to see
them again.''
   Shortly after arriving back in Brazil, the child, dressed in a
green jump suit, romped through the baggage-claim area, rode the
conveyor belt and wheeled around a pushcart. Occasionally, she
interrupted her play to embrace her parents.
   The family later boarded a plane for Curitiba, where Parana
state authorities planned a big reception and meeting with Gov.
Alvaro Dias.
   At a brief news conference held in the airport's press room,
Mrs. Vasconcelos, looking tired but composed, held Bruna on her lap
and said, ``I never doubted I would be reunited with my daughter.
It's a marvelous feeling having her back, and I owe it all to my
faith in God, luck, persistence and the many people who helped me.''
   Police say Bruna's kidnapping was the work of one of many
baby-trafficking rings that abduct or buy infants from mothers in
poor areas and sell them for hefty profits to childless foreign
couples.
   Adoption by foreigners is legal in Brazil, but it is a
time-consuming bureaucratic process that sometimes takes several
years. With phony or even legitimate papers obtained through
corrupt officials, the baby-trafficking rings can arrange an
adoption within weeks, police say.
   The Israeli couple who adopted Bruna, Yaacov and Simone
Turgeman, paid $25,000 to intermediaries but said they acted in
good faith, believing the high fee and documents were legal.
   But Shimon Schuber, the Israeli lawyer who helped the Brazilian
couple get their daughter back, said: ``The Turgemans may not have
known Bruna had been kidnapped, but they certainly knew something
was fishy. They knew the documents were phony.''
   Schuber, who accompanied Bruna back to Brazil, said: ``They had
to know something was illegal about the whole thing. No one goes to
Paraguay to adopt a Brazilian child and thinks it's all legal.''
   Almost immediately after her abduction, Bruna was taken across
the border to neighboring Paraguay, where she was handed over to
the Turgemans.
   About one year afterward, Bruna was located near Tel Aviv. Her
parents contacted Brazilian authorities for help in getting her
back, and earlier this month, the Israeli Supreme Court decided she
should be returned to her parents in Brazil.
   Mrs. Vasconcelos said that at first her relationship with the
Turgemans ``was just fine. They seemed understanding and were
willing to cooperate. But later the relationship deteriorated.''
She declined to say why.
   Olavo de Souza, a Curitiba radio reporter who covered the story
in Israel for more than a month, said the relationship soured when
the Israeli couple ``tried to convince the Vasconceloses to abandon
the idea of taking Bruna home.''
   ``When they saw the Vasconceloses would not consider such a
proposition, they filed an appeal in the Supreme Court to postpone
Bruna's return. But the court turned them down,'' Souza said.
   Mrs. Vasconcelos said the Turgemans treated her daughter well.
``But the way they raised her was nothing special,'' she said.
``They didn't do anything I would not do.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
