<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NunAbducted     07-01 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nun Abducted,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nun Remains In Hiding After Interview With Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A novice nun abducted by her family from a
renegade Catholic convent says she wasn't kidnapped and doesn't
want to press charges, but a convent official accused the woman's
parents of ``brainwashing'' her.
   Mary Susan Greve, 22, also known as Sister Mary Cecilia,
voluntarily appeared at the Hamilton County Sheriff's Department
Thursday with her parents, James and Susan, and the family's lawyer.
   ``She expressed to us that she has no animosity or any bad
feeling toward members of her family or anyone else, and that she
is where she is (with her parents) because she wants to be where
she is,'' said Raymond Hulgin, chief of detectives.
   Misdemeanor charges have been filed in New York state against
four of her relatives for the alleged abduction Sunday. Police did
not arrest the family members because the charges are misdemeanors
from another state.
   Ms. Greve, a novice at St. Joseph Novitiate Convent for 20
months, was allegedly pushed into a waiting car by her brother
David as she walked with two nuns on a street near the convent in
Roundtop, N.Y.
   Hulgin said the parents told police they took their daughter
because they were upset by a lack of communication with the
convent, which calls itself a traditionalist Roman Catholic
convent. The sect holds services in Latin and rejects the liberal
teachings of the Second Vatican Council of the 1960s.
   The sect, called the Society of St. Pius V, split from the
recognized Catholic traditionalist Society of St. Pius X in 1983
over philosophical differences. The sect is not recognized by the
Roman Catholic Church.
   A tape of the local police interview with Ms. Greve has been
mailed to New York State Police, who will use it to decide whether
to drop charges, Hulgin said.
   Ms. Greve appeared to be clear-headed and comfortable during the
interview, Hulgin said.
   ``She seemed to be in total control of herself. She had no
reservations about speaking to us,'' he said. ``She was very
cooperative. She gave us no firm commitment as to what her future
intentions were.''
   Despite Ms. Greve's statement to police, the convent's spiritual
adviser, the Rev. Clarence Kelly, said Thursday he was not
convinced she was acting on her own.
   ``I would like to talk to her without her parents present to
determine in fact that she is acting according to her own free
will,'' Kelly said.
   ``There was no question about the force used in her abduction.
Now she is being held in captivity for a number of days. I'm afraid
they've subjected her to some type of brainwashing,'' he said.
   In April, the family took Ms. Greve from the convent for a
medical check-up, but a nun was waiting for them in Cincinnati and
persuaded Ms. Greve to return to the convent, said her brother John.
</TEXT>
