<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     07-01 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Dive, Dollar Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices took a plunge today as the dollar
continued its climb against the Japanese yen in Tokyo.
   The dollar opened at 133.57 yen, up a strong 1.37 yen from the
previous day's closing. It rose rapidly to end the week at 134.50
yen, up 2.30 from Thursday's finish.
   The dollar closed today at its highest level since Nov. 27, when
it finished at 134.75 yen.
   It ranged between 133.55 and 134.60 yen today, with spot volume
estimated at $9.8 billion.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, the market's main barometer, shed 265.87 points,
or 0.95 percent, closing at 27,503.53.
   The loss came after a rally of 371.31 points over the previous
two trading days.
   ``Share prices fell because the stock market was adjusting
itself to the weaker yen,'' said a broker with a major securities
firm who spoke on condition of anonymity. But he noted that
activity was very heavy, with 2.6 billion shares traded in the
first section.
   Volume was up from 2.5 billion shares traded on the first
section Thursday. Among the issues posting sharp losses were
steels, heavy industrials and electricals, the trader said. Also
losing ground were constructions, nonferrous metals and textiles.
   Low-priced issues, including trading houses and shippings, held
on to earlier gains, traders said.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the Tokyo market seemed to be
testing whether Japan's central bank would take any action to stem
the dollar's rise.
   ``Right now it is unclear how far the government is willing to
let the dollar go,'' said an exchange dealer with a major
commercial bank. ``But it is rumored that Finance Minister (Kiichi)
Miyazawa sees the 138-yen level as acceptable.''
   The trader, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said he did not
believe the Bank of Japan had stepped into the market today to stem
the yen's slide. The central bank does not comment officially on
its market interventions.
   Earlier this week, Japanese monetary authorities, including
Miyazawa, said the central bank would use market intervention if
necessary to brake the dollar's upswing.
</TEXT>
