<1ST_LINE>r i PM-ChinesePaintings     07-01 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chinese Paintings,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Classical Paintings Exhibit To Tour United States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighty classical Chinese paintings dating back to
the 14th century will be exhibited in five U.S. cities next year to
mark the 10th anniversary of Sino-American diplomatic ties, an
official report said today.
   The English-language China Daily called the selection of
paintings the finest ever allowed to leave China. It said the works
are from China's last two dynasties, the Ming and Qing, which ruled
from 1368 until a republic was established in 1911.
   The paper said the paintings, borrowed from the Palace Museum in
Beijing's former imperial palace, will be shown first in January at
the Honolulu Academy of Arts in Hawaii.
   From there they will move to the High Museum of Art in Atlanta,
Georgia= the Cleveland Museum of Art in Cleveland, Ohio, the
Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York City and a fifth undecided
city.
   The International Arts Council of the United States began
negotiations with the Palace Museum two years ago to hold the
exhibit, the paper said.
   The United States and People's Republic of China established
diplomatic relations on Jan. 1, 1979, ending 30 years of
estrangement.
</TEXT>
