<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BullFlap     07-01 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bull Flap,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Damages Awarded for Loss of Bull Semen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLFAX, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owners of Blitz, a prize bull, should
not be compensated for the bull's death or the loss of his valuable
semen, a jury has decided.
   Alvene and Emily Leinweber had sued Ed and Karen Hinnenkamp for
$150,000, claiming Blitz was fatally wounded in 1983 while
defending his herd against a trespassing Hereford owned by the
defendants.
   The Leinwebers claimed Blitz was the foundation of their
breeding business, Palouse Pinzgauer Breeders, 11 miles north of
Colfax. They said Blitz had to be put to sleep months after the
alleged fight, since he couldn't stand up long enough to have his
semen extracted.
   Blitz's semen cost about $20 a sample and was sold throughout
the United States, the Leinwebers said.
   The Hinnenkamps acknowledged their bull broke out of its pasture
and flirted with Blitz's cows, but denied it attacked Blitz.
   After an eight-day civil trial in Whitman County Superior Court,
jurors decided Wednesday the Hinnenkamps were not liable for their
Hereford's rambling, nor were they negligent for not preventing the
bull's activity.
   The decision came despite an earlier plea from the Leinwebers'
attorney, Linda Schauble-Ruff, to award damages.
   ``The Leinwebers are approaching their golden years and were
looking forward to the (financial) comfort Blitz could have given
them,'' she told jurors. ``But that can't happen now. They've got
only 800 units of semen left to hoard.''
   Gary Libey, the Hinnenkamp's attorney, said Blitz could have
died from accidents other than a fight. He suggested Blitz may have
simply over-exerted himself while mating, injuring both hind legs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
