<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 0603EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vietnam-Cambodia     07-01 0729</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-Cambodia,0752</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Officer Describes Guerrilla Attacks in Cambodia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HO CHI MINH CITY, Vietnam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Khmer Rouge guerrillas planted
explosives that injured 33 people in Cambodia's capital last year
and tried to blow up a strategic bridge there in 1984, a Vietnamese
army officer said today.
   Col. Dinh Nhu Ninh, commander of an elite unit assigned to
protect Phnom Penh, provided a rare disclosure of guerrilla
infiltrations.
   But he said the capital has been very secure since Vietnam
invaded Cambodia in late 1978 and set up a pro-Vietnamese
government. He dismissed the Khmer Rouge, the main guerrilla
infiltrators, as ``leftovers of an army that was beaten up and
became bandits.''
   Ninh said the last members of his unit, 1,200 men, returned home
on June 6 as part of Vietnam's plan to withdraw 50,000 troops, or
half its force in Cambodia, by the end of the year.
   Vietnam says its military command and all military advisers
returned home on Thursday, turning responsibility for the war over
to Cambodian officers.
   About 50,000 Cambodians, according to official count, turned out
on the streets of their capital as about 300 Vietnamese commanders
left Phnom Penh and flew to Ho Chi Minh City, formerly Saigon.
   Hanoi acknowledged it lost 25,000 men in the war, but most of
the fighting was away from the capital. Ninh said that no
Vietnamese soldiers had been killed in Phnom Penh since he took up
his post in January 1979. There were no major attacks on the city
and most intrusions were on its outskirts, he said.
   Vietnam's army rarely provides details of operations. The only
reports of guerrilla infiltration into Phnom Penh have come from
highly exaggerated Khmer Rouge claims or sketchy accounts from a
few Western aid officials.
   Fanatic Khmer Rouge communists killed millions of people when
they ruled Cambodia from 1975 until the Vietnamese invasion.
   Ninh spoke with foreign journalists invited to cover the
Vietnamese pullout.
   He said the worst period was from March 23 to July 20 last year
when Khmer Rouge agents planted 44 Chinese-made explosives on the
outskirts of the city. The plastic-covered bombs, about 4 inches in
diameter and 1{ inches wide, exploded when touched, he said.
   ``The intention was to scare people,'' he said. ``They laid the
explosives in the people's water tanks, bus terminals, staircases
of people's houses, or on the road.''
   Ninh said 33 people, all civilians, were wounded, including six
Vietnamese living in Cambodia.
   The leader of the saboteurs, a Khmer Rouge battalion commander,
was sentenced to death and another suspect, a Khmer Rouge
underground activist, sentenced to life imprisonment, Ninh said.
   Authorities also captured 15 others whom the Khmer Rouge had
paid $500 for each bomb they placed, he said. They received shorter
jail terms or were put in political ``re-education'' camps.
   He said the second most serious attack was the firing of two
H-12 rockets into the city on Dec. 27, 1986. Both crashed into
paddy fields, causing no injuries, and a Khmer Rouge operative who
launched the rockets was captured, he said.
   Ninh also said six Khmer Rouge operatives were caught in an
abortive plot to blow up the Son Ngoc bridge, the capital's
biggest, which links its eastern and western sectors. The plot was
organized in 1983 and explosives were to be planted in early 1984,
he said.
   Ninh said the chief plotter, Mon Ly, was sentenced to death and
the five others were given prison terms or probation.
   While Ninh said guerrilla-related incidents in Phnom Penh were
declining, he did not discount claims by diplomats that the Khmer
Rouge was lying low to prepare for attacks in 1990, when Vietnam
says its last soldiers will leave Cambodia.
   He said some Cambodians in Phnom Penh reacted to this year's
pullout with apprehension about the return of the Khmer Rouge.
   Ninh said guerrillas also conduct limited psychological warfare
in Phnom Penh, distributing handwritten leaflets saying ``that
Khmer (Cambodians) should not fight Khmer. The Khmer should fight
the Vietnamese.''
   The Vietnamese colonel said military intelligence indicated the
Khmer Rouge exaggerated its strength in referring to ``Division
18,'' the unit that was behind the 1986 rocket attack and the 1987
explosions.
   ``A division should have about 10,000 soldiers,'' he said. ``But
they have only 250 people and call themselves a division. Nonsense.
They don't have any strategy or tactics.''
</TEXT>
