<2ND_LINE>PM-Portugal-US, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0520,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Says US Naval Attache Expelled For Photographing Iranian
Ship</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with embassy comment. PICKS up
6th graf, `He later ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Portugal has expelled the U.S. naval
attache to Portugal for photographing an Iranian ship loading cargo
in a Portuguese port, a published report said today. The U.S.
Embassy denied the report.
   The weekly Independent newspaper quoted unidentified sources as
saying the attache, Capt. William Barney, left Lisbon on Wednesday.
   But U.S. Embassy spokeswoman My Chau Bui-Griffin said Barney
left Lisbon in early May following routine transfer orders from
Washington.
   She said he had served as naval attache in Lisbon since March
1985.
   Mrs. Bui-Griffin declined to comment on the allegations reported
by the Independent. She said it was not U.S. Embassy policy to
comment on individual newspaper reports.
   The Portuguese Foreign Ministry and the prime minister's office
said no one was immediately available to comment.
   The paper said the attache at first said he was a journalist
when challenged by port authorities as he allegedly photographed
the Iranian ship at Setubal, south of Lisbon.
   Photographing state-owned installations is an offense in
Portugal in some circumstances.
   He later admitted he was a diplomat after being taken to a
Portuguese naval base for questioning, according to the report.
   It said Barney was recognized by several Portuguese naval
officers at the base.
   Portuguese state-owned companies sell arms to both Iran and its
enemy Iraq, and the weapons are loaded at the port of Setubal. The
newspaper did not say whether the cargo Barney reportedly
photographed included arms.
   The Indepdendent said Barney left Lisbon after Foreign Minister
Joao de Deus Pinheiro summoned U.S. ambassador Edward Rowell and
informed him of the Lisbon government decision to expel the
diplomat.
   The report gave no further details.
</TEXT>
