<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 0623EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AMA-At-A-Glance     07-01 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AMA-At-A-Glance,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Summary Of Day's Events At AMA House of Delegates Meeting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-AMA Rdp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a summary of the major issues considered
Thursday by the American Medical Association's 420-member House of
Delegates. The AMA is the nation's largest group of doctors
representing 295,000 physicians. The convention ended Thursday.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>____</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AIDS POLICIES</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The delegates approved a package of policies for battling the
nation's AIDS epidemic. One proposal calls on states to trace the
sexual partners of people infected with the AIDS virus as a
strategy for slowing the deadly disease's spread into the
heterosexual population.
   Another says physicians, as a last resort, have the obligation
to stop the spread of AIDS by departing from their rule of
confidentiality and warning the sexual partners of anyone infected
with the virus.
   The other policies adopted included a recommendation that
prisons test inmates for exposure to the AIDS virus, a call for
expanded treatment programs for intravenous drug abusers and a
proposal that the president form a new AIDS commission to
coordinate public policies.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>TANNING PARLORS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The delegates, alarmed by the rapid growth of the commercial
tanning industry, declared that tanning booths ``pose potentially
significant health risks.''
   They voted to lobby the federal government to require that
warnings be posted in tanning parlors about the increased risks of
skin cancer caused by prolonged exposure to ultraviolet light from
tanning booths.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>TOBACCO</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The delegates took additional steps in their fight for a
smoke-free society, urging commercial airlines to ban smoking on
all domestic flights. Federal regulations now prohibit smoking on
flights of two hours or less.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>STEROIDS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The delegates also called on state legislatures to prohibit
athletes from using steroids to enhance their physical prowess.
Improper use of steroids poses dangerous risks such as impairment
of a person's sexual functions.
</TEXT>
