<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     07-01 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in early European trading today
after reaching a seven-month high in earlier trading in Tokyo. Gold
prices rose slightly.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 2.30 yen to close the week at 134.50 yen, the
dollar's highest level since Nov. 27 when it closed at 134.75 yen.
Later, in London, it was quoted at 134.05 yen.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the Tokyo market seemed to be
testing whether the Bank of Japan central bank would intervene to
stop the dollar's rise.
   ``Right now it is unclear how far the government is willing to
let the dollar go,'' said an exchange dealer with a major
commercial bank in Japan.
   ``But it is rumored that Finance Minister (Kiichi) Miyazawa sees
the 138-yen level as acceptable.''
   In Europe, the dollar slipped from its Asian peaks amid reported
dollar sales by the West German central bank, but was still above
its late Thursday level.
   In London, the British pound slid to its lowest level against
the dollar this year, trading as low as $1.69. At midmorning it was
quoted at $1.7023, the lowest level since last September, and
cheaper than $1.7085 Thursday.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Thursday:
   _1.8210 West German marks, up from 1.8170
   _1.5120 Swiss francs, up from 1.5060
   _6.1347 French francs, up from 6.1250
   _2.0555 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0530
   _1,351.25 Italian lire, up from 1,350.38
   _1.2172 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2126
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $435.90 an ounce, little
changed from late Thursday's $436.40. At midmorning, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $436.50.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $436.75, compared with $436.50 late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 82 cents to close at a bid
$440.00.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.68 a troy
ounce, up from Thursday's $6.66.
</TEXT>
