<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CemeteryStrike     07-01 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cemetery Strike,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Cemetery Workers End Strike; Others Continue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers at eight cemeteries ratified a
new contract, ending a monthlong strike that forced funeral parlors
to store hundreds of bodies awaiting burial, but a strike continued
at nine other cemeteries.
   The 71 Eastbay members of Cemetery Workers and Greens Attendants
Local 265 approved the pact Thursday and were scheduled to return
to work today, union officials said.
   The settlement does not affect a strike by workers at nine
cemeteries on the San Francisco Peninsula who also walked off the
job May 30. There are no talks scheduled in that dispute, which
involves about 87 workers.
   No details of the Eastbay settlement were immediately available.
The major issue that prompted the strike was the cemetery owners'
use of contract workers to do jobs that Local 265 officials said
should be performed by union members.
   The striking workers included gravediggers, gardeners and
maintenance personnel.
   Cemetery owners attorney John Cantwell said he was unsure how
many burials have been delayed by the strike. In 1985, a six-week
strike by the same union local resulted in more than 800 bodies
going unburied during the walkout.
</TEXT>
