<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 0710EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Protest     07-01 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Protest,0607</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Deny Police Killed Pollution Protesters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLENE L. FU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials today denied Western reports that
police killed several peasants and brutally beat others who tried
to stop the release of polluted water from a reservoir near Beijing.
   The official Xinhua News Agency late Thursday issued the first
official report of the June 21 protest during which peasants tried
to stop a petrochemical company from releasing contaminated waste
water from a reservoir into a local stream.
   The peasants said the water would poison their wells and crops.
Officials said the water level in the reservoir had risen too high
and that there was danger of flooding.
   Wang Zuoseng, local Communist Party secretary, criticized
foreign reporting of the protest and accused Western reporters of
violating government regulations this week when they visited the
reservoir in Guce village.
   Authorities there turned away some Western reporters this week
and confiscated film and audio tapes.
   Guce, which is under the Beijing municipal administration, is 37
miles southwest of the city center.
   Wang cited the same regulation that was used last October to
expel 14 Western reporters from Tibet following violent
pro-independence, anti-Chinese riots by Tibetans in Lhasa.
   The regulation requires foreign reporters to apply for
permission when traveling to report in areas open to foreigners.
Reporters previously had interpreted it to apply to places outside
Beijing, and officials have never before invoked it in greater
Beijing.
   The new interpretation would significantly widen the scope of
the regulation and severely limit foreign reporting in China.
   At today's news conference, Wang said the July 21 protest was
much smaller than peasant witnesses have said. He denied witness
accounts that thousands of armed police were brought in and scores
of peasants were badly hurt.
   Villagers told The Associated Press on Thursday that more than
1,500 farmers clashed with at least 2,000 armed police, and 60 to
70 protestors were seriously injured when police beat them with
nightsticks and used electric cattle prods.
   Some villagers told Western reporters that three people were
killed, but those who spoke to the AP said they could not confirm
any deaths.
   ``What you're talking about is what a small number of people are
saying. I was at the site. I can assure you that there were no more
than 500 farmers,'' Wang said. He said about 200 unarmed local
police were at the scene.
   He denied that anyone was killed or seriously injured, but said
some people might have been slightly hurt during the scuffle.
   Villagers also said 150 people were arrested the day of the
protest, and that 10 remained in custody, but Wang said only five
people were being interrogated. He said they have not been formally
arrested or charged.
   He did not say if others had been detained and released.
   The waste stored in the Niukou Reservoir came from the
state-owned Yanshan Petrochemical Co. Wang said it was produced
after the plant dismantled its old waste treatment equipment and
before it had installed new equipment.
   Wang said he did not know what chemicals were in the water or
what affect they could have on human health and crops.
   By mid-June, the water in the reservoir had risen to a dangerous
level and had to be released to avoid flooding, he said. Beijing is
having its annual rainy season.
   Wang said the petrochemical company will compensate the farmers
for all losses they suffer in their summer wheat harvest and for 60
percent of losses of their autumn grain crop.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
