<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BusCrashSettlement     07-01 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bus Crash Settlement,0622</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Ford Offers Settlement In Fatal Church Bus Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. has offered out-of-court
settlements of less than $1 million to each of the families of the
24 children killed in a fiery May 14 church bus crash, a newspaper
reported today.
   Ford, which made the bus chassis, also offered payments to the
estates of the three adults who died in the accident near
Carrollton, and to the 40 survivors, based on the severity of their
injuries, The Courier-Journal reported today, attributing the
information to unidentified lawyers.
   Ford spokesman Robert Waite told the newspaper that ``delicate''
negotiations were under way, but would not comment on whether a
settlement had been offered.
   Lawyer Michael Hance, who represents the families of two of the
dead children, said a settlement was being offered by Ford and all
manufacturers responsible for producing the bus, including Sheller
Globe Corp. of Toledo, Ohio, which assembled it.
   Hance declined to disclose the size of the offers, but described
them as ``attractive financially'' to the families and also a good
deal for Ford.
   Sheller Globe's spokesman did not return phone calls seeking
comment, the newspaper reported.
   Lawyer Don Skeeters, a spokesman for the Radcliff firm of
Skeeters & Bennett, which is representing most of the remaining
plaintiffs, refused to confirm or deny that an offer had been made.
   Lawyers who have handled similar cases told the Courier-Journal
it would be highly unusual, if not unprecedented, for such a major
case to be settled so quickly, before lawsuits were even filed.
   Washington lawyer John Coale, who represents one family and has
been active in several air-disaster cases, said it would be
``unconscionable'' to settle so quickly without exploring whether
Ford might be liable for punitive damages. He predicted the cases
might be worth as much as $120 million.
   Coale, who represents the parents of Shannon Fair, who was
killed in the crash, said his client intended to take Ford to trial
even if all other plaintiffs settle out of court, although he
acknowledged it would be difficult for one client to finance such a
battle.
   Hance said he would present the bus makers' proposal today to
his clients, the parents of Patty Nunnallee and Sandy Brewer. In
Hance's view, the families must decide between accepting the
offers, which he called ``a sure thing,'' or the ``reality of
fighting one of the largest corporations in the nation for four or
five years.''
   While he described the offers as attractive, he said Ford might
be forced to pay $60 million to $70 million for compensatory
damages alone if the case is tried. The total value of the proposed
settlement offer is ``nowhere close to that,'' he said.
   Hance also said his clients, whom he described as more
interested in bus-safety reforms than money, also might refuse to
accept Ford's stipulation that settlement values be kept secret.
   The converted school bus, owned by the Radcliff First Assembly
of God Church, was returning 67 people _ mostly children _ to the
church after a day at the Kings Island amusement park near
Cincinnati. Police say the accident was caused by a drunken driver
traveling the wrong way on Interstate 71.
   However, investigators have said other factors combined to
increase the loss of life, including the bus' lone rear exit door
and crowded conditions inside.
   Authorities also cited the bus' gas tank, which ruptured and
burst into flames. The resulting smoke was blamed for all 27 deaths.
   The bus was apparently one of the last manufactured in 1977
before a new federal rule required bus fuel tanks be sheathed in
protective cages.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
