<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CDC-AIDSNotification     07-01 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CDC-AIDS Notification,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Partner-Notification Plans Exist In All States, CDC Finds</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AMA-AIDS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Procedures to warn the sex or drug-sharing
partners of people infected with AIDS virus are now under way in
every state, according to a new report from the national Centers
for Disease Control.
   The CDC reported Thursday that all 50 states encourage partner
notification, through programs by which infected people are urged
to inform partners with whom they have had sex or shared needles.
   Forty-eight states have in place ``referral on request''
programs to inform partners when an AIDS-infected patient asks them
to. The other two _ Georgia and Nebraska _ have programs to inform
partners in certain case, such as women of childbearing age or rape
victims.
   In addition, a Georgia law going into effect today specifies
that health authorities may contact spouses, sex partners or other
parties for disclosure purposes after first trying to inform the
patient that they plan to do so.
   AIDS, caused by a virus, is transmitted chiefly through sex or
contaminated drug needles. Partner notification, the CDC noted, has
been a key part of efforts to fight sexually transmitted diseases
since the advent of penicillin to treat syphilis in the 1940s.
   The CDC recommends that AIDS-infected people ``should be
instructed in how to notify their partners and to refer them for
counseling and testing.'' The agency also recommends that if
infected people cannot or will not get their partners to seek
counseling, ``physicians or health department personnel should use
confidential procedures to assure that the partners are notified.''
   ``All the states are giving counseling to patients about the
need to inform their sex partners and needle-sharing partners,''
said Dr. Kathleen Toomey, a CDC researcher.
   Having a third party notify people at risk ``has been shown to
be effective, but costly,'' the CDC said in its weekly report.
Because of limits on money and other resources, having patients
inform their own partners ``has played an increasingly important
role.''
   In four of the states offering outside notification of sex or
drug partners _ Colorado, Idaho, South Carolina and Virginia _ the
percentage of partners identified through the programs who agreed
to AIDS tests and showed signs of infection ranged from 14 to 39
percent, Ms. Toomey said.
   ``By identifying such individuals, the partner-notification
process can target risk-reduction messages to those at greatest
risk of acquiring or transmitting infection,'' the CDC said.
   More than 65,000 AIDS cases have been reported in the United
States; 88 percent have occurred among homosexual males or
injectible drug abusers, according to the CDC. More than 37,000
patients have already died.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
