<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 0812EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-KidnapTrial     07-01 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kidnap Trial,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspected Kidnapper Says He Planned Abduction For Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAARLEM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The suspect in the country's only
known fatal kidnap case said today he picked his victim, a Dutch
tycoon, at random and then spent two months planning the abduction.
   Ferdi Elsas, 45, said at his trial here that he began mapping
out the abduction of grocery baron Gerrit-Jan Heijn in July 1987.
Heijn was kidnapped Sept. 9, and his body was found April 4.
   Elsas said he chose his victim at random. His lawyer, Johannes
Weermeijer, told The Associated Press that Elsas ``knew Mr. Heijn
from the telephone directory.''
   There was no immediate word on the motive for the abduction.
Heijn's relatives paid $8 million ransom.
   The only other testimony scheduled to be given was that of a
forensic psychiatrist who has examined the suspect extensively.
Under Dutch trial practice, the hearing of witnesses is unusual.
   Elsas has confessed that he abducted and killed Heijn. If found
guilty, he could be sentenced to life in prison.
   Local press reports indicated that the psychiatric report
claimed that at the time of the abduction, Elsas bore only
``limited responsibility'' for his deeds.
   If the court accepted that claim, it could impose a limited jail
sentence followed by confinement in an institution for the
criminally insane.
   The soft-spoken Elsas is an unemployed business consultant with
an engineering degree from a Dutch university.
   Elsas told court president Ms. C.A. Terwee-Van Holten that he
shot and killed Heijn on the day of his kidnapping in a forest near
Renkum, in the eastern Netherlands.
   Heijn, vice president of the multimillion-dollar Ahold retail
concern, was abducted from his sprawling villa in Bloemendaal, one
of Haarlem's affluent suburbs, while on his way to a dental
appointment.
   On April 4, Heijn's body was dug up from a forest in the eastern
Netherlands after police arrested Elsas.
   Their arrest came after a bank employee discovered a 250-gilder
note from the ransom payment.
</TEXT>
