<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0537,0659</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab Woman Dies Six Weeks After Israel Raid</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with Arab death; picks up 13th
graf pvs: `The school...;</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian woman died today from a bullet
wound she sustained six weeks ago when Israeli soldiers raided her
village in the occupied West Bank, hospital officials said.
   Fatima Kassem, 24, was shot in the head during a May 18 army
raid on the mountain village of Abwein, officials at Jerusalem's
Mukassad Hospital said.
   Her death brought to 214 the number of Palestinians killed since
the Arab uprising began Dec. 8. Four Israelis also have been killed.
   Also today, Arab hospital officials rejected army claims that
Mohammed Shabello, a 36-year-old street vendor from the West Bank
city of Nablus, died of a heart attack unrelated to a clash with
troops.
   Hospital officials said Shabello died minutes after inhaling
tear gas hurled by troops to subdue stone-throwing demonstrators in
Nablus on Thursday.
   Shabello's death, which was not included in the fatality count,
touched off a violent protest at the man's funeral Thursday, and
Israeli troops wounded one Arab during the clashes.
   Palestinian protesters are challenging Israel's rule in the
occupied territories and Arab east Jerusalem, which the Israelis
seized in the 1967 Middle East War.
   Israel's Supreme Court, in a ruling published today, said
procedures for detaining Palestinians without trial for up to six
months must be formalized. Human rights activists have deplored
current policy under which about 2,500 Palestinians are detained.
   A Jerusalem Post report today blamed the uprising for diplomatic
setbacks in relations with Poland, Greece, Ireland and Portugal.
   The newspaper said Poland had canceled plans to raise the level
of relations with Tel Aviv and Greece reneged on a promise to open
an embassy in Tel Aviv and upgrade Israeli representation in Athens.
   Israel's deteriorating image also prompted Portugal not to open
an embassy in Tel Aviv and Ireland to refuse to host a resident
Israeli ambassador in Dublin, the Post said, quoting sources in
Jerusalem.
   An Israeli Foreign Ministry official confirmed Greece said
several months ago it would not open an embassy because of the
uprising. But he said it was unclear whether the other countries
were acting because of the Arab rebellion. He spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   In other developments, police closed the Dar El Aytam boys'
school inside the walled Old City on Thursday after students from
the school stoned a police patrol. Two youths were detained, Israel
radio said.
   The school closing came as violence has been on the increase in
Jerusalem after four months of relative calm. In a leaflet issued
last week, underground leaders of the uprising called on Arabs to
make Jerusalem the focus of their disturbances.
   The army has also confirmed that 38 schools were closed in the
West Bank in an effort to quell the protests, mostly involving
young Palestinians.
   On Thursday, police fired tear gas at dozens of Palestinians who
gathered near a key highway in Arab east Jerusalem to stone Israeli
cars, capping a day of violence in the city, Israel radio reported.
   It said police used tear gas after the Arab youths stoned
Israeli cars on a highway linking the occupied West Bank settlement
of Maaleh Adumim, home to over 15,000 Jews, with Jerusalem.
   The radio did not say whether police made any arrests. Police
spokesman Rafi Levy could not be reached at his home or office for
comment on the report.
   Also Thursday, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir accused Arab states
of encouraging Palestinians in the occupied lands to keep up their
``destructive and futile'' actions. He vowed that the uprising
would fail.
   In a speech to leaders of the quasi-governmental Jewish Agency,
Shamir rejected the view that the recent Arab summit in Algiers
adopted moderate resolutions toward Israel.
</TEXT>
