<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--VailBears     07-01 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Vail Bears,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bear Traps Set in Vail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VAIL, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colorado wildlife officials have set traps
around this posh ski resort to catch up to eight bears that have
been enjoying the city's lifestyle.
   The bears have been feasting on trash bins, said Bill Andree, a
state wildlife official. One of the sows even may have taught her
cubs to expect handouts from residents.
   Earlier this spring, officials believed there was only one bear
rambling around town, but recent sightings indicate there could be
as many as eight living in a 20-mile stretch from Vail to Beaver
Creek.
   The bears have become more aggressive, Andree said. Last
weekend, a bear chased a 14-year-old boy after he photographed the
animal.
   Residents have been warned not to camp or sleep out in backyards
or near food sources.
   Bears older than 3 years will be killed, Andree said. Younger
bears will be marked and released near Radium, 20 miles northeast
of here.
   State wildlife officials believe younger bears, if put in the
proper habitat, may learn to eat without bothering people.
</TEXT>
