<DOCNO> AP880701-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 0858EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-MissileInspectors     07-01 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Missile Inspectors,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First U.S. Missile Inspectors Under Treaty Going to Soviet Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first American inspectors
assigned to verify Soviet compliance with the treaty to eliminate
intermediate-range nuclear weapons left for Moscow today.
   Their Soviet counterparts arrive in San Francisco tonight.
   The two U.S. inspection teams, each comprised of 10 experts,
traveled from Frankfurt's Rhein-Main Air Base.
   They were led by U.S. Army Brig. Gen. Roland Lojoie, director of
the On-Site Inspection Agency, which was formed Jan. 15, 1988 after
President Reagan and Mikhail S. Gorbachev signed the Intermediate
Nuclear Forces treaty in Washington. That accord eliminated
ground-based short- and medium-range missiles.
   ``We all feel this is a historic mission,'' Lajoie told
reporters before boarding a U.S. Air Force jet for Moscow. ``Its
impact on international relations cannot be underestimated. We are
proud to be a part of this important moment in history.''
   Lajoie said one team would travel to the Soviet city of
Votkinsk, the site of a plant that formerly built the Soviets'
SS-20 missiles. The SS-20s are covered by the treaty, along with
U.S.-built Pershing 2 missiles and cruise missiles based in western
Europe.
   The other U.S. team must tell the Soviets within 48 hours after
arrival where it intends to begin conducting inspections, Lajoie
said. He did not disclose which site that would be.
   ``We're going in with the attitude `Trust everybody, but always
cut the cards,''' Lajoie said.
   The general said that although there are 1,800 missiles whose
destruction must be checked, other related items _ including
storage and transport missile containers and special hauling
vehicles _ bring the actual number of items to be inspected to at
least 5,000.
   The inspection teams will be checking for numbers of missiles,
and individual components will be measured and weighed under the
inspection process agreed upon with the Soviets, said Lajoie.
   In the next two months, the inspectors will visit 126 sites in
the Soviet Union, including 33 in eastern Siberia, Lajoie said.
   The Soviets will inspect 26 sites in the United States and
western Europe, including 11 in the continental United States,
according to On-Site Inspection Agency officials.
   The U.S. teams include linguists and specialists in nuclear
missiles.
   Although the inspection teams are comprised of members of all
branches of the U.S. military and civilian government employees,
the inspection agreement calls for all of them to wear civilian
clothes during their stay in the Soviet Union.
   In London, NATO commander Gen. John R. Galvin said he was
confident the verification arrangements would work. He said he had
been surprised at the openness the Soviets have shown in the visits
to U.S. elimination sites so far.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
