<DOCNO> AP880701-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 0903EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica     07-01 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Proposes Bill To Strengthen Residential Segregation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government proposed
legislation today that would strengthen residential segregation but
also would allow creation of the first legal multi-racial
neighborhoods.
   Government opponents condemned the three proposed measures,
saying they would force the evictions of thousands of blacks now
living peacefully but illegally in ``whites only'' areas.
   ``The government indicates once again its absolute obsession
with skin color as a norm on which to base South Africa's
political, social and economic life,'' said the anti-apartheid
Independent Party.
   Tian van der Merwe, member of Parliament for the anti-apartheid
Progressive Federal Party, called the measures ``so harsh and so
brutal'' that up to 200,000 blacks could be evicted on short notice.
   Under the Group Areas Act, all residential areas are segregated
by race. However, thousands of non-whites are living illegally in
neighborhoods designated for whites in Johannesburg, Cape Town and
other urban areas.
   One of the proposed measures, the Group Areas Amendment Bill,
would make it easier to confiscate property and to evict and
prosecute people living in areas not designated for their race
group.
   The maximum fine for a person living outside his group area
would be increased from $175 to $4,300. The maximum prison sentence
would be increased from two years to five years.
   The government has not strictly enforced the 35-year-old Group
Areas Act in recent years, angering conservative whites opposed to
integrated neighborhoods. The proposed bill is widely seen as an
accommodation to right-wing whites prior to nationwide municipal
elections in October.
   President P.W. Botha's governing National Party favors gradual
race reform but says it is committed to preserving white ``group
rights'' such as segregated schools and neighborhoods.
   The National Party has dominated South African politics for 40
years but has been losing ground to the extreme-right Conservative
Party, which opposes all concessions to the nation's 26 million
black majority. Under South Africa's system of apartheid, blacks
have no vote in national affairs.
   A second proposed bill, the Free Settlement Areas Bill, would
allow creation of residential areas open to all races. But before
such areas could be established, a government committee would check
``the necessity or desirability'' of an area being opened to all
races.
   A third bill would set up guidelines for multi-racial political
participation by residents in ``open areas.''
   The three bills are to be debated in the next session of
Parliament in August.
</TEXT>
