<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 0903EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StarWars-Test     07-01 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Star Wars-Test,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Small `Star Wars' Rocket Engine Successfully Tested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aerospace experts developing ``Star Wars''
technology have successfully tested a tiny, 2-ounce rocket engine
designed to power satellite-based missile killers.
   The engine tested at Rocketdyne's Santa Susana Field Laboratory
on Thursday is slated for use as a directional thruster for a
space-based interceptor in the Strategic Defense Initiative program.
   The goal is to neutralize incoming enemy nuclear missiles before
they re-enter the atmosphere by using lasers and interceptor
rockets.
   The new engine, dubbed by designers as the most efficient in the
free world, would guide the interceptor from its base on a
satellite toward an approaching nuclear missile. The missile would
be destroyed on impact.
   Officials from the Air Force Space Division, Rockwell
International and Rocketdyne called the test successful, praising
the engine's weight-to-thrust ratio, a measure of its power and
efficiency. Thrust is the forward force produced in reaction to
gases escaping rearward from the engine.
   ``The engines we were running with around five years ago were
1-to-20,'' said Ernie Bunch, a Rocketdyne engineer in the
space-based interceptor, or SABIR, program.
   The tiny engine tested has a weight-to-thrust ratio of
1-to-1,200, said Frank Patota, engineer in charge of the test area.
   The engine was fired, or pulsed, for five milliseconds and then
was shut off for 1@10 of a second. This cycle was repeated dozens
of times during each of the three testings. The result sounded like
machine gun fire.
   The interceptor rockets would be equipped with four of the
tested engines and four smaller thrusters.
</TEXT>
