<2ND_LINE>PM-Spain-Crash,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rescue Crews Find Five Bodies Of Victims of Helicopter Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescue workers today found the bodies of
five people, including one of Spain's top transportation officials,
whose helicopter crashed in a storm north of Madrid, a Civil Guard
spokesman said.
   The official said the bodies of Highway Traffic Chief Rosa de
Lima Manzano and four men were found near near the wreckage on a
4,800-foot-high peak near La Cabrera, a town 45 miles north of the
Spanish capital.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the dead
included Miss de Lima Manzano, art critic Santiago Amon, Socialist
Deputy Alberto Alcitores Balbas, and Civil Guard pilots Manuel
Moratillo and Santiago Aizpurua.
   The official said the bodies had been severely burned.
   About 1,800 people, including members of the paramilitary Civil
Guard, the army and the civil defense had taken part in the search
in the Somosierra mountain range, the official said.
   Officials gave no cause for the accident but said a storm and
poor visibility may have been partly responsible.
   Before serving as the Interior Ministry's highway traffic chief,
Miss de Lima Manzano had been civil governor of the northern
province of Palencia, a post comparable to sheriff.
   The helicopter left Madrid on Thursday for Aguilar de Campo, 160
miles north of Madrid.
</TEXT>
