<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TelephoneTaps     07-01 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Telephone Taps,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says National Security Agency Bugging Satellite Phone Calls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Intelligence Committee is
investigating allegations that the National Security Agency engaged
in electronic eavesdropping of Congressmen and American citizens,
The Plain Dealer reported today.
   The alleged telephone bugging was accomplished through
interception of satellite signals, the newspaper said.
   It said the allegations surfaced during secret testimony earlier
this year by Margaret A. Newsham, 45, a former employee at Lockheed
Missiles and Space Co. in Sunnyvale, Calif.
   Maj. Alan Freitag, public affairs duty officer for the Defense
Department in Washington, said Thursday night he was not familiar
with Ms. Newsham or her allegations and could not comment on the
report.
   Ms. Newsham, a former software configuration management analyst
for space projects at Lockheed, handled classified assignments
overseas and possessed NSA special access clearances.
   She lost her top secret access after becoming a
``whistleblower'' on waste in a government program and making
accusations that she was sexually harassed, according to The Plain
Dealer, which said she was fired from Lockheed for alleged
time-card violations.
   Ms. Newsham told Rep. Louis Stokes, D-Ohio, chairman of the
Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence, that the monitoring was
being done with the cooperation of British authorities and from
English soil, the newspaper said.
   While NSA eavesdropping on ordinary telephone calls is barred in
the United States, loopholes in the law allow the agency to do it
by monitoring microwave frequencies outside U.S. borders, said
James Bamford, author of ``Puzzle Palace,'' a book on the NSA.
   Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., who is said to have been among
those whose personal calls were monitored by the Pentagon security
agency, said he looked into the allegations after being informed of
them by The Plain Dealer. He said he does not believe they are true.
   Ms. Newsham was among sources confirming the existence of her
top-secret session with Stokes and two committee staffers, the
newspaper said.
   Asked about the allegations, Ms. Newsham's credibility or why
other members of the committee were not involved in the meeting,
Stokes said, ``I don't discuss intelligence business.''
   The military watchdog group Project on Military Procurement has
been working with Stokes on the probe, The Plain Dealer said.
</TEXT>
