<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 0955EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Circus     07-01 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Circus,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Circus A Success in Japan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Dinny in 4th graf is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES W. HATTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAPPORO, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Greatest Show On Earth'' met one of
the world's most polite audiences today, and the American brand of
unbridled circus won some new fans.
   The Ringling Bros. and Barnum & Bailey Combined Shows made its
debut in Japan in a huge tent in this city on the northern island
of Hokkaido. The audience was the first in Japan to see an American
circus.
   A near-capacity matinee crowd of about 4,000 attended the debut
and clapped enthusiastically for the 200-member troupe, after a
little encouragement from the clowns.
   ``We had been prepared for a reserved, quiet crowd. This is not
Texas,'' ringmaster Dinny McGuire told The Associated Press after
the performance. ``But they clapped fervently. ... I did not expect
them to be as overwhelmingly demonstrative.''
   Ringling Brothers has brought a version of the 118-year-old show
to Japan as an experiment. It will give 44 performances in Sapporo,
then 96 shows in Tokyo in August and September.
   The Japan Educational Association, the local promoter of the
tour, wanted a production as big as the two Ringling troupes
touring the United States, said publicist Joe Gold.
   The $40 ticket price for adults _ about four times the average
price in the United States _ still is considered reasonably priced
entertainment in Japan.
   To help audiences understand the acts, ringmaster McGuire
learned his introductions in Japanese. Also, Japanese characters
were put on many of the clown costumes to identify them to children.
   Finally, ``we brought in 120 kids last week'' for a dry run,
Gold said.
   Ringling owner-producer Ken Feld said the production will cost
$10 million plus incidentals _ such as the $8 million tent.
   At the matinee, viewers first smiled instead of laughing and
clapped politely instead of loudly. But the clowns went into the
stands for direct contact with youngsters, then staged elaborate
stunts and broke the ice with a comedy high-wire act called the
``Mount Fuji Aerial Adventure.''
   ``Slapstick always plays well,'' said Glen Little, the head
clown, wearing a blue wig.
   Sachiko Okawara said she liked the performance ``very much.''
``The performancers, the animals, the costumes, the lights _ and
the band. The band was beautiful,'' she said.
   For 5-year-old Miku Kusakabo, the list of favorites was shorter:
``The elephants,'' she said through an interpreter, and nodded
vigorously when asked if she wanted to come back.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
