<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 1012EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SharpevilleSix     07-01 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sharpeville Six,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecution Witness Writes Botha To Recant Testimony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecution witness has
written President P.W. Botha to seek clemency for six black people
whose death sentences have sparked international outrage, a
newspaper reported today.
   Joseph Manete, who said that police tortured him so he would
give false testimony, reportedly described his police interrogation
and pleaded for the release of the so-called Sharpeville Six.
   ``I am writing this letter in order to tell you the truth ...
What I have told the court was not my words,'' according to a text
of the letter published today by City Press, the largest
circulation newspaper for blacks.
   Botha refused to intervene in the case, despite appeals from
many foreign governments to halt the hanging of the five black men
and one woman convicted of the mob killing of a black town
councillor.
   A day before they were due to hang in March, attorneys obtained
a stay of execution from the trial judge, Willem Human, on the
basis of a statement that Manete had given his lawyer.
   The lawyers said Manete wrote an affidavit saying police coerced
him into falsely identifying two of the defendants as being part of
the crowd that stoned and burned ouncilor Jacob Dlamini in
September 1984.
   During a hearing last month, Human said he had not relied on
Manete's testimony and had not been shown the affidavit. Human said
reopening the case to investigate interrogation of other
prosecution witnesses would be ``absurd.''
   Human gave the defendants until July 19 to seek a stay of
execution from the chief justice of the Appellate Court, P.J. Rabie.
   In the letter printed today, Manete described his interrogation,
saying that from the outset he told police he didn't know the names
of Dlamini's killers.
   ``They threatened and pressurized me,'' he wrote. ``One of the
white policemen pushed my head against the wall and I was clapped
several times on the face.''
   He said a policeman read him the names of the six defendants and
told him he would be imprisoned ``and tortured daily'' if he did
not name two of them as having been present at the killing.
Finally, Manete said, ``I agreed with them.''
   ``During the interrogation I was afraid that very soon I will
reach the point of no return _ that is death,'' he said.
   The six defendants are Mohalefa Sefatsa, Reid Mokoena, Oupa
Diniso, Theresa Ramashomola, Duma Khumalo and Francis Mokgesi.
   Manete said he was told to identify Khumalo and Mokgesi. He told
Botha other prosecution witnesses also were unhappy about
statements they had given under police interrogation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
