<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Explosion 3rdLd-Writethru   07-01 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Explosion, 3rd Ld - Writethru,a0569,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car Bombs Explode In Lebanon; One Dead, 52 Hurt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with second car bomb; 52 reported injured.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two cars rigged with explosives blew up
today in separate parts of Lebanon, killing at least one person and
injuring 52, police said.
   The first explosion occurred on west Beirut's busiest street. A
police spokesman said the bomb went off on Hamra Street at about
11:50 a.m. (4:50 a.m. EDT) near the Grand Hotel in the
Syrian-policed neighborhood.
   The spokesman, who could not be identified in line with standing
regulations, could not immediately confirm a state radio report
that a man killed in the blast was the driver of the automobile.
   Thirty-two people were injured in that bombing.
   Later, a Mercedes Benz loaded with explosives blew up in eastern
Lebanon's Bekaa valley near a Syrian army checkpoint, police said.
They said 20 people, including two Syrian soldiers, were injured.
   The car, parked about 15 yards from a checkpoint in the town of
Bar Elias, exploded at 12:25 p.m. and set four other cars on fire,
police said.
   After the Beirut bombing, black smoke billowed from the southern
edge of Hamra Street as motorists, honking their horns, sped away
in panic.
   The street is lined with boutiques, cafes and other shops. Its
high-rise buildings house offices and banks. The explosion occurred
near the plush Versailles Cinema, which was closed because of
damage sustained in civil war fighting.
   Witnesses said Syrian soldiers fired automatic rifles in the air
to make way for fleeing cars.
   Lebanese policemen blocked traffic along the 1.5-mile-long
street to allow ambulances and fire engines to reach the scene.
   Today's blasts came nine days after a car bomb exploded in east
Beirut's Christian district of Karantina, wounding 19 people.
   There have been nine car bombings in Lebanon this year.
Ninety-four people were killed and 251 wounded in the previous
blasts.
</TEXT>
