<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CanePickers     07-01 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cane Pickers,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Gives Sugar Cane Workers Opportunity to Qualify for Resident
Status</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has given thousands of foreign
sugar cane workers an opportunity to qualify for permanent U.S.
resident status under a program for seasonal farm workers.
   U.S. District Judge Thomas F. Hogan ordered the Immigration and
Naturalization Service to accept applications from sugar cane
workers to obtain legal resident status under streamlined
procedures to accommodate a Nov. 1 deadline.
   Under the 1986 Immigration Reform and Control Act, seasonal
workers have that date to file applications to qualify for the
program.
   Hogan also ordered INS to grant work authorization papers to the
applicants and barred the agency from initiating deportation
proceedings against those individuals.
   ``Equity demands that these sugar cane workers be afforded an
opportunity to stay in the country pending the final outcome
regarding the status of sugar cane'' in the program for seasonal
workers, Hogan said Wednesday.
   Hogan, who ruled in April that the Agriculture Department had
not justified excluding sugar cane harvesters from the program,
chided USDA for the continuing delay in drafting new regulations.
   He gave USDA until July 11 to propose the new regulations and
set an August 19 deadline for issuing the final rule.
   USDA could still issue regulations that exclude sugar cane
harvesters from the program, but the agency would have to give
Hogan further justification for its decision.
   USDA had sought to issue its new regulations in September, but
Hogan said further delays would not give the workers enough time to
qualify for legal status if the department ultimately decided they
could participate in the program.
   ``The court views with skepticism ... (USDA's) claims that,
despite at least three drafts which have been rejected, the agency
still is grappling with the drafting of the regulation,'' Hogan
said.
</TEXT>
