<HEAD>Physician, Village Official Killed Near U.S. Air Base</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with more dead</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen killed a physician, two
government officials, a former political candidate and a
12-year-old bystander in a series of attacks throughout the
country, military reports said today.
   A communist rebel also was killed when guerrillas and government
troops fought in a town called Mexico north of Manila, the reports
said. Four government militiamen and a soldier were wounded.
   Official reports from Angeles city, 50 miles north of Manila,
said two unidentified men barged into the clinic of Dr. Patricio
Santiago on Thursday night and fatally shot him as his wife watched.
   In a separate incident also Thursday in Angeles, two gunmen
killed district council member Almario Quiambao as he walked with
his wife on a street, the reports said.
   The slayings brought to 35 the number of people killed during
the past two months in Angeles, home of the United States'
sprawling Clark Air Base. Most of the killings have been attributed
to leftist and right-wing extremists.
   In Mexico town, 10 miles from Angeles, communist guerrillas
aboard a truck overtook a government patrol jeep and fired on the
troops, a military report said. The soldiers fired back and killed
one rebel, the report said, adding that a 12-year-old boy on a
bicycle nearby died in the crossfire.
   Thursday's two other slayings were in the village of Pandanon on
the central Philippine island of Negros, the Philippine News Agency
reported.
   It quoted a police report as saying that six men shot to death
Alfredo Magdato, a defeated vice mayoralty candidate in nearby
Murcia town. The gunmen then opened fire on village council member
Reynaldo Conlu, who was nearby and rushed to investigate, the
agency added.
