<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DroughtRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0533 07-01 0673</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0533,0685</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Helps Plains Farmers, Floods Some Fields</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites throughout to update with rain amounts today,
Wisconsin legislature, record low temps, Iowa rain.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Drought-Good Harvest, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rain soaked the central Plains today, bringing new life to
wilting crops and flooding parts of Kansas, but some farmers
complained that the wet weather was too little, too late.
   ``It's too late for this corn even if it does rain,'' said
Oklahoma farmer Ronald Limon, edging into chest-high stalks that
should be 3 feet higher by now. The struggling ears were pale; the
kernels were widely spaced.
   ``You can hear it rattle when the wind blows. And that's a bad
sign,'' Limon said Thursday hours before scattered rain fell on the
state. ``But we're thankful. It could be no ears at all.''
   A bill to guarantee up to $35 million in loans to help farmers
suffering through the drought was passed Thursday by the Wisconsin
Legislature and sent to the governor. It would provide about 3,500
potential loans to farmers whose debts totaled 40 percent of their
assets. Maximum loans would be $10,000 for up to three years at 6
percent interest.
   Widespread rain fell Thursday night and early today from New
Mexico to Missouri and from Mississippi to South Dakota. Chanute,
Kan., got 2.14 inches in the six hours up to 7 a.m. and 2.02 inches
fell at Joplin, Mo.
   But forecasters cautioned that the drought continues.
   ``The indications are that this is a temporary interlude,'' said
Lonnie Nine of the National Weather Service in Springfield, Mo.,
where 3.72 inches fell Wednesday and early Thursday. That city got
an additional 1.83 inches today. ``Over the long haul, we expect to
return to the dry, hot weather. Ten days from now, people will be
needing water again.''
   The rain came too late to help the wheat crop, said Paul
Nordquist, crop production specialist for the University of
Nebraska-Lincoln West Central Research and Extension Center in
North Platte.
   One example of the shortfall in precipitation is Iowa. Harry
Hillaker, acting state climatologist, said final statistics for the
first six months of the year are expected to show average state
rainfall came to 7.45 inches, driest on record, including more than
2 inches earlier this week in some areas. Normal rainfall in that
period is 15.72 inches.
   For some it was not only too late, but too much. Fields, roads
and bridges in northeastern Kansas were under up to 5 feet of water
Thursday. The heaviest rain reported was 12 inches in Douglas
County, Kan., south of Topeka.
   About 20 Douglas County residents had to be evacuated _ some by
boat _ because of flooding, county authorities said.
   ``I knew it was raining when I went to sleep, and when I woke up
water was rushing in the front door,'' said resident Steve Silvers.
``I panicked and grabbed everything I could and started yelling at
my neighbor across the street to see if she was OK.''
   The water washed away large chunks of asphalt from county roads
and uprooted fields of crops made fragile by the heat and drought.
Residents were allowed back in their homes Thursday.
   Thunderstorms brought cooler temperatures to the Plains and a
cold front pushed temperatures to record lows today around the
Great Lakes and from New England to North Carolina. Elkins, W.Va.,
got down to a brisk 32 degrees.
   But the heat wave that had gripped the Midwest claimed another
victim Thursday. An 80-year-old Oklahoma man died of dehydration
three days after he and his wife were found in a wheat field.
   Harry Archer died at a Cordell, Okla., hospital after attempts
to rehydrate him failed, said Washita County undersheriff Ron
Mazureka. His wife, Rhoda, 77, died earlier after collapsing of
heat exhaustion last weekend.
   In Alabama, an autopsy Thursday on a 77-year-old woman found
dead in her home revealed she died of heatstroke. The body of
Thelma Lane was found Wednesday as temperatures in Mobile hovered
in the 90s.
</TEXT>
