<1ST_LINE>u i PM-BerlinShowdown     07-01 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Berlin Showdown,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Move On Disputed Land Squatters, Communist Guards Help Them
Over Wall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Berlin police today chased nearly 200
squatters from a disputed piece of land near the Berlin Wall after
a monthlong struggle that pitted environmentalists against city
developers.
   When the removal order came, the squatters found an unusual
escape route _ over the Berlin Wall into the city's Communist side.
   East German border guards helped them over the barrier, which
divides the city of Berlin into Allied and Communist sectors.
   Most of the estimated 186 environmentalists who fled to East
Berlin had returned to West Berlin by noon. Nine protesters were
arrested in the raid. Eight have since been released, police said.
   The demonstrators were protesting plans to build a highway
through a park nearby.
   When more than 900 West Berlin police moved in to clear the
area, nearly 200 protesters were already sitting on the
13-foot-high wall.
   They earlier declared that they would seek ``political asylum''
in East Berlin if West German police tried to rout them.
   East German guards backed trucks up to the eastern side of the
wall to make it easier for the environmentalists to jump down and
escape the West Berlin police.
   One smiling East German guard even helped one of the protesters
by pulling his bicycle over the wall.
   The action to clear the squatters from the 10-acre piece of
property known as the ``Lenne Triangle'' occurred after it formally
came under West Berlin's control one minute after midnight.
   It was handed over under the terms of a deal worked out with
East Berlin this year.
   The protesters occupied the area on May 26 and quickly set up a
shantytown and erected barriers to protect them from police charges.
   The property has been the scene of frequent violent skirmishes
between police and demonstrators. Protesters often attacked police
with bottles, stones and Molotov cocktails, and officers responded
with tear gas and water cannons.
   Police could not legally enter the property until it came under
West Berlin control.
</TEXT>
