<HEAD>Hungary's Parliament Condemns Romanian Resettlement Plan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 9th graf: `Official media...,' to UDPATE with border
official saying no official ban. Pick up 10th graf pvs: `The
parliamentary...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Romania-Hungary, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament today condemned a Romanian
plan to resettle ethnic Hungarians and called on Bucharest to
reconsider the move.
   The resolution made no reference to Romania's decision this week
to close a Hungarian consulate and expell its staff. It also didn't
mention the order to close a Hungarian cultural center in the
Romanian capital.
   Matyas Szueroes, head of the foreign relations committee that
drafted the document, appealed to Hungarians ``not to yield to
emotions'' regarding the ``disquieting developments reported from
Romania.''
   Hungary maintains the program of moving residents of 7,000
villages to new agricultural-industrial centers would destroy
ethnic Hungarian culture and tradition in Romania. Romania says it
would help villagers by providing services now enjoyed only in
cities.
   Romania's treatment of its 1.7 million Hungarian residents has
long been a sticky issue between the two Warsaw Pact allies.
   Hungary claims the Hungarian minority is discriminated against.
Bucharest says Hungary's criticism is interference in Romania's
internal affairs.
   Romania on Tuesday closed Hungary's consulate in Cluj in
Transylvania, home to most of Romania's ethnic Hungarians, to
protest a demonstration by 50,000 people in Budapest against the
resettlement program.
   Bucharest also insisted that the Hungarian Embassy move out of
rooms rented for a cultural center.
   Official media in Hungary reported that Romanian authorities
also were sending back some Hungarian travelers without giving any
reason for the move. A Hungarian border official, who spoke on
condition he not be identified, said today there was no official
ban.
   The parliamentary document, which is to be sent to the Romanian
legislature, said the beginning of the Romanian program would
further weaken Hungarian-Romanian relations.
   The document said Hungary hoped Romania ``would reexamine its
... plans and will refrain from their implementation.''
   ``This would remove an important obstacle to the rapprochement
between the Hungarian and Romanian people,'' the document said.
   On Thursday, Communist Party chief Karoly Grosz appealed for
dialogue with Romania.
   Grosz, who is also premier, said the tension was temporary and
warned against drawing long-term conclusions.
   He told Western journalists he would go ahead with a planned
visit to Romania because ``if we don't talk to each other we cannot
understand each other.''
   No date for the trip has been announced, but it is believed
Grosz will go to Bucharest after visits in July to Moscow, Warsaw
and Washington.
   On Thursday, a Hungarian diplomat in Bucharest said Romania had
declared Hungary's cultural center in the Romanian capital closed
and ordered the embassy to vacate the building.
   The cultural center was never issued a permit to start operation
and has been used as a storage for the embassy in recent years.
</TEXT>
