<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Austria-Waldheim 1stLd-Writethru   07-01 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Austria-Waldheim, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0600,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Austrian President Withdraws Lawsuit Against WJC President Bronfman
^Eds: SUBS 3rd graf: `First, the...,' to CORRECT attribution to
Christian. Pick up 4th graf pvs: `Second, the...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Kurt Waldheim today withdrew a
slander suit filed against Edgar Bronfman, president of the World
Jewish Congress, a spokesman said. Bronfman last year called
Waldheim ``part and parcel of the Nazi killing machine.''
   Spokesman Gerold Christian, told The Associated Press that
Waldheim cited three reasons for the move in a letter sent to the
Vienna prosecutor's office.
   ``First, the U.S. Justice Department has refused legal
assistance, which is in contrast to international legal norms,''
and this ruled out a quick court action, Christian said.
   ``Second, the (international) commission of historians, private
undertakings as well as international historians have determined
Waldheim's personal innocence.
   ``Third, there is an endeavor (on the part of the president) to
contribute to calming down and reconciliation,'' he said.
   The U.S. Justice Department said in December 1987 that it has
evidence of Waldheim's complicity in the transfer of civilian
prisoners to the Nazi SS for exploitation in labor camps during
World War II, the deportations of Jews from Greek islands to
concentration or death camps, the execution of Allied prisoners and
the execution of hostages and other civilians.
   Waldheim has denied wrongdoing.
   Christian said Waldheim stopped the suit also ``to calm things
down for Austria, because the country always has priority over
personal matters.''
   It was believed that Waldheim decided to stop legal proceedings
against Bronfman because there was virtually no chance for the
court action ever to take place in Austria, and even less chance
that it would take place in the United States.
   With the Justice Department unwilling to cooperate by having
Bronfman testify in a U.S. court, and with Bronfman refusing to
appear in an Austrian court, the lawsuit might never have been
resolved.
   A report issued by an international commission of historians in
February did not say if Waldheim was involved in wartime atrocities
but it made clear that as an intelligence officer in the German
army, he was aware of them and did nothing to prevent them.
   The document seriousl questioned Waldheim's integrity and led to
widespread calls for his resignation, but the Austrian head of
state refused to comply, insisting that the historians had cleared
him of all charges.
   Waldheim called on the Vienna prosecutor's office to sue
Bronfman on May 7, 1987, two days after the World Jewish Congress
president said he was ``part and parcel of the Nazi killing
machine'' while serving in the Balkans during the war.
   According to a presidential statement issued at the time, the
lawsuit was also based on a comment by Bronfman who reportedly said
if Waldheim ``has any patriotism in his soul whatsoever, his
doctors would find reasons for him to resign his post.''
   The third Bronfman comment cited by the president said
Waldheim's ``misdeeds and his lying about his past'' were so
obvious that it would be ``almost a crime against humanity to have
very much to do with this man.''
</TEXT>
