<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DysonFundraiser     07-01 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dyson Fundraiser,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Probe Target Staged Fundraiser For Rep. Dyson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Unisys Co. official whose home was searched
by the FBI in connection with the Pentagon procurement
investigation staged a campaign fund-raiser for U.S. Rep. Roy P.
Dyson, The Sun reported today.
   Dyson aide Katie Tucker told The Sun on Thursday that Dennis
Mitchell organized a cocktail party held July 9, 1987, at a
Manhattan hotel.
   Mitchell at the time was an assistant to Charles F. Gardner, a
former Unisys vice president who is currently a consultant to the
company. Mitchell is now marketing manager for the defense
electronics plant.
   Dyson's relationship with Unisys was first publicly noted on May
1 when the Maryland Democrat's top aide, Thomas M. Pappas,
apparently jumped to his death from his 24th floor New York City
hotel room. Dyson, Pappas and another aide were in Manhattan for a
$4,000 weekend paid for, in large part, by Unisys.
   The FBI searched Gardner's office on June 14 and Mitchell's home
the following week. Neither man responded to requests for
interviews by The Sun.
   Ms. Tucker said her boss remembered seeing Gardner at the party
but that he couldn't remember the names of any other guests.
   ``We have no idea who they are,'' she told The Sun. ``They
attended this fund-raiser that was put together by Unisys. That was
the one and only time we have had any contact with them.''
   William J. Beckham Jr., spokesman for Unisys, said his company
did not ``quote unquote arrange the fund-raiser,'' adding that if
Mitchell staged the event, he did so on his own. ``It was not a
company-sponsored, nor a company-supported activity,'' Beckham said.
   The newspaper also reported that on the same day as the
fund-raiser, Dyson received $1,000 campaign donations from three
other people whose offices or businesses have been searched by the
FBI.
   Federal Elections Commission records show that Dyson collected a
total of $16,000 in political contributions that day, the newspaper
reported.
</TEXT>
