<1ST_LINE>r a PM-InmateReporter     07-01 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Inmate Reporter,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inmate-Journalist Transferred After Story Critical of Warden</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOMPOC, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An inmate has been transferred from a
federal prison for violating a ban on working as a reporter, and
the prisoner's editor called the move punishment for criticizing
the warden in print.
   Dannie M. Martin, 48, whose June 19 article on conditions at
Lompoc Federal Penitentiary appeared in the San Francisco
Chronicle-Examiner, was moved Thursday to another facility, said
Lompoc Associate Warden Paul Hofer.
   ``I feel Dannie has been transferred as a punitive response to
material the Chronicle chose to print in order to keep its readers
informed on important issues,'' said Peter Sussman, editor of the
Sunday feature section that has published 20 articles by Martin in
the past two years.
   ``Convicts have the right to communicate with news media under
special mail rights and the paper had a First Amendment right to
publish,'' he added.
   Hofer said in a statement that Martin was transferred for
violating prison regulations against inmates working as journalists.
   Sussman said he could not discuss whether Martin was paid for
his articles.
   Martin, serving time for bank robbery, was put in an isolation
ward for 24 hours last week by Warden Richard Rison after a story
by Martin accused Rison of turning the prison into ``a caldron of
fear, hatred and violence.''
   The headline over the story read ``Gulag Mentality.''
   Among other things, Martin criticized Rison's policy of keeping
the recreation yard closed until noon. ``Those of us who work on
night jobs and ran and exercised in the mornings now sit in gloomy
cell blocks watching the sun shine through the window bars,'' he
wrote.
   Rison said that he put Martin in confinement to protect him from
other inmates angered by the article. He said a reference to
possible riots at the maximum-security prison could spark a
demonstration.
   Martin was returned to the general prison population after an
investigation determined he was under no threat.
   Hofer said Martin's intention to continue writing for the
newspaper ``jeopardizes the safe and orderly operation of the
institution and cannot be tolerated.''
   Martin's destination could not be released until he arrived
there, prison officials said.
   Martin's next article will appear Sunday and describes his stay
in confinement, said Sussman. Martin talks about his fear of
transfer in the report.
   The two San Francisco papers produce a joint edition on Sunday,
with the Examiner handling news and the Chronicle handling features.
</TEXT>
