<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Shultz 1stLd-Writethru a0490 07-01 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0490,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede GUATEMALA CITY</HEAD>
<HEAD>Shultz Arrives in Costa Rica After Talks With Rebel Leaders</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES thruout with Shultz meeting with Arias. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE , Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz
met today with President Oscar Arias after discussing with
Nicaraguan rebels possible ways of making Arias' regional peace
plan succeed.
   Hundreds of flag-waving Costa Rican children greeted Shultz
after he flew here following visits to Guatemala, Honduras and El
Salvador.
   Shultz is on the last stop of his three-day Central American
tour. He spent Thursday night in Guatemala City. Adolfo Calero, a
leader of the Nicaraguan rebels, said today in Guatemala that the
administration and pro-rebel members of Congress are considering a
$30 million aid package for the rebels over a six-month period.
   A portion of the money, perhaps $7 million, would be placed in
an escrow account and released as military aid for the Contras if
Nicaragua's government does not meet democratic reforms mandated in
Arias' peace plan, Calero said.
   There was no immediate word on what Shultz and Arias discussed.
Administration officials said Shultz and rebel leaders only touched
briefly on the Contra issue.
   Arias won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1987 for drawing up a plan
that calls for cease-fires in Central America's wars, democratic
reforms, and an end to outside aid to insurgents.
   Shultz met with the rebel leadership after visiting El Salvador
and Honduras for talks with top officials Thursday. He began his
Central American tour in Guatemala Wednesday.
   Shultz said Thursday in Tegucigalpa, Honduras, that he has
shared ideas with Central American leaders on a diplomatic solution
to the Nicaraguan problem, but he gave no details.
   He said he planned to discuss these ideas with President Reagan
and members of Congress after his return to Washington.
   Contra supporters in the Congress have been discussing the
possibility of seeking approval for new military aid for the rebels
to be placed in an escrow account.
   The Contras have received no military aid since Feb. 29, and
congressional approval of a new package of lethal assistance
without conditions is thought to have scant support among lawmakers.
   Congress approved a $17 million humanitarian aid package in late
March after the rebels and the Sandinista government agreed on an
interim cease-fire.
   Efforts by the Sandinistas and the Contras to reach agreement on
a permanent cease-fire broke down June 9 and no new talks have been
scheduled.
   The Contras have said the Sandinistas backed away from their
earlier promises to enact democratic reforms. The Sandinistas have
said the Contras were just using the talks as a pretext to get more
U.S. military aid.
   A senior U.S. official who briefed reporters after Shultz'
meeting with the Contras said the possibility of resuming
negotiations was discussed.
   So far, the administration has said only that it plans to seek
renewed aid for the Contras, but no final decision on a package was
to be made until after Shultz's trip.
   The administration, by weighing the possibility of offering U.S.
assistance to the Sandinistas, appears to believe that Nicaragua
may be receptive to a proposal that would benefit it economically.
   Despite massive support from the Soviet bloc, the Nicaraguan
economy has continued to unravel, crippled by the civil war.
   On several occasions during his Central America trip, Shultz has
quoted Sandinista officials as saying Nicaragua's inflation rate
this year is running at 20,000 percent.
   Economic aid would be a sharp reversal of Reagan administration
policy. In addition to funding the Contras, the administration has
a trade embargo against Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
