<2ND_LINE>PM-Stabbing Deaths, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0562,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four People Found Dead in Duplex</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates thruout with more detail, quotes from uncle</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four members of the same family were
stabbed to death and a fifth was wounded in an attack at two homes,
and police said they arrested a relative about a block from the
scene.
   Joselito C. Camangian, 23, an amusement park worker, was booked
today on four counts of investigation of homicide, said police
Detective Pat Kolstad said.
   The survivor, Candida Camangian, 26, was in serious condition at
Santa Clara Valley Medical Center after the Thursday night attack,
said nursing supervisor Carrie Wickware.
   Candida Camangian is the suspect's sister. Her twin sister, a
brother, a cousin and 15-year-old niece died.
   The supect was a native of the Philippines who came to Santa
Clara about five months ago, police said.
   ``We don't know the motive yet,'' said Kolstad. He added that
Camangian offered no resistance when he was arrested.
   An uncle, Elmer Gale, said he was preparing for his night job
when he heard a pounding at his door.
   ``I heard Candida (Camangian) yelling, `Uncle, uncle, please
open the door. My brother is stabbing my sister','' Gale said
today, adding that she then flung herself on him and sobbed, ``Lito
is stabbing my brother, too.''
   Gale said he slipped out a rear door and ran to a gas station to
telephone police. As he was calling, he said, Joselito Camangian
walked up.
   ``I was astonished, he was calm,'' a weary, shaking Gale
recalled. ``Then he tells me, `Uncle, I don't know what I did. Call
the police. I don't know what I did.'''
</TEXT>
