<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-Ships     07-01 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Ships,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mine-damaged US Frigate Leaves for Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. missile frigate Samuel B.
Roberts headed for home Friday, riding out of the Persian Gulf on
the back of another ship 11 weeks after an Iranian mine nearly sank
it.
   The 3,600-ton warship rode in a special cradle atop the Mighty
Servant 2, a heavy-lift cargo vessel the Navy chartered from a
Dutch salvage firm for $1.3 million.
   Emergency repairs to the frigate's badly ripped hull were made
at Dubai. Its early morning departure from the emirate in the
southern gulf was a surprise because U.S. military officials had
indicated earlier the Roberts would pass through the narrow Strait
of Hormuz at night for security reasons.
   As the Mighty Servant 2 and its piggyback cargo approached the
strait, the The U.S. missile cruiser Vincennes fired an artillery
salute. The Vincennes was on patrol near Hormuz, where Iran has
threatened shipping with gunboats and missile batteries since early
in its 8-year-old war with Iraq.
   About 30 of its crew members are accompanying the Roberts to
Newport, R.I., on a trip expected to take about 40 days. U.S.
officials said the frigate would be rebuilt at the shipyard in
Bath, Maine, where it was launched in 1986.
   Officials have denied reports the $400 million ship would be
scrapped, but hull damage from the April 14 mine explosion was so
extensive that salvage experts advised against trying to tow it
across the stormy Atlantic.
   Departure of the ``Sammy B.,'' as crewmen called their ship,
came 11 weeks to the day after it sailed inadvertently into what
U.S. officers said was a newly laid Iranian minefield and collided
with a submerged mine while trying to back out.
   Ten crewmen were wounded in the explosion, which wrecked the
engine room, broke the keel of the 453-foot vessel and started
fires and flooding.
   U.S. forces retaliated with attacks on two Iranian oil platforms
April 18 that led to a day of confrontation in the southern gulf in
which six Iranian naval craft were sunk or disabled.
   The Mighty Servant 2 is a ``semi-submersible'' ship, described
as one of only two in the world capable of carrying the Samuel B.
Roberts home. Both are owned by the the Dutch salvage firm
Wijsmuller Transport.
   Earlier in the week, the frigate was towed out of Dubai and
floated over the submerged deck of the cargo vessel, which was then
raised to normal level, leaving the Roberts high and dry.
</TEXT>
