<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail Baryshnikov, artistic director of
American Ballet Theater, announced Friday that choreographer Twyla
Tharp will join the company as artistic associate.
   Baryshnikov said Tharp and several dancers in her company will
join at the next rehearsal period, which starts Aug. 22. She will
choreograph a new work for Ballet Theater next season and will
teach several of her creations to the company during the next two
years.
   Tharp has directed her own modern-dance company since 1965 and
has choreographed more than 80 works. She choreographed ``Push
Comes to Shove'' for Baryshnikov and American Ballet Theater in
1976 and has done three other ballets for the company.
   She did choreography for four movies, ``Hair,'' ``Ragtime,''
``Amadeus'' and ``White Nights'' and has choreographed extensively
for television.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wolfman Jack has stopped howling about the
golden oldies on Southern California's airwaves, but the madman of
the radio can hardly be called muzzled.
   Thursday was the 49-year-old disc jockey's last day spinning the
platters that matter weekday afternoons on XTRA-AM because the
station adopted an all-talk format beginning Friday.
   ``It's nothing personal nor are there any bad feelings,'' said
the Wolfman, who has broadcast with XTRA-AM since September 1987.
``They've been paying me a lot of money, so I sure wouldn't leave
if it wasn't the right thing all the way around.''
   Fans of the nifty '50s need not fear. Wolfman Jack Productions
is developing a new late-night national radio show. And the
Wolfman, whose real name is Bob Smith, can also be seen on The
Nashville Network as host of the weekly ``The Rock 'N' Roll
Palace.''
   XTRA-AM is a 50,000-watt station in Tijuana, Mexico, near the
California border. Wolfman Jack performed his show from his studio
at his Beverly Hills home and fed it via satellite to the station.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Lamar Alexander, whose name
has cropped up in discussions of possible presidential and vice
presidential contenders, has taken on a smaller presidency.
   The two-term Republican governor took office Friday as president
of the University of Tennessee.
   ``This is a university on its way to being real good
academically. That excites me,'' Alexander, 47, said. He succeeds
Edward J. Boling, who retired after nearly 18 years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Motown Museum announced Friday that Michael
Jackson will donate the proceeds of his Oct. 24 concert in Detroit
to the Motown Museum Historical Foundation.
   Jackson got his show business start, at age 9, at Motown
Records. In 1987 the studio and offices, known as ``Hitsville
U.S.A.,'' was proclaimed a historical site by Gov. James Blanchard.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opera director Gerard Mortier, who
brought the Monnaie opera company to international attention in the
1980s, said Friday he has agreed to head the restructured Flemish
Opera.
   Mortier, 43, will be director of the opera company in northern
Belgium for three years while keeping his post as head of the
Brussels Monnaie.
   The Flemish Opera in the Dutch-speaking part of Belgium was
recently reorganized to try to brighten its financial future and
add creative impetus.
   Mortier said while the Monnaie has an international scope, the
Flemish opera would be to give young Flemish talents experience
before moving on to larger companies.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Auto heir John Francis Dodge is
again behind bars, completing a one-year sentence handed down for
violating a probation term set in January on a previous drug
conviction.
   Dodge, 34, was allowed to delay serving his time until April 4
to give him time to settle a custody dispute over his 6-year-old
son. He was released after 56 days by prison officials who
mistakenly started the clock on his jail time on Jan. 6, the day he
was sentenced.
   When the mistake was uncovered, Dodge was ordered to return to
the Loxahatchee Road Prison by June 30. He turned himself in on
Thursday.
   Prison officials on Thursday said they had not calculated a
release date for Dodge, youngest grandson of auto tycoon Horace
Dodge Sr.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Bhumibol Adulyadej on Saturday
becomes the longest-reigning monarch in Thailand's 750-year history.
   The king will have been on the throne for 42 years and 23 days.
The longest previous reign was that of King Chulalongkorn, who
ruled 1868-1910.
   King Bhumibol, 60, will preside over Buddhist rites in the Grand
Palace, pay homage to the relics of Chulalongkorn and travel with
Queen Sirikit to the ancient capital of Ayuthaya during four days
of ceremonies. Bangkok's buildings have already been festooned with
lights and special logos.
   The constitutional monarch, born while his father studied
medicine in Boston, assumed the throne upon the mysterious death of
his brother in 1946. He is widely regarded as a source of stability
in this rapidly developing nation.
</TEXT>
