<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Gromyko     07-01 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Gromyko,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gromyko Honored at Conference Day After He Criticized</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Party, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Andrei A. Gromyko was honored
with the chairmanship of a session of the national Communist Party
conference on Friday, one day after he was criticized for
contributing to the country's stagnation.
   Soviet television showed Gromyko, 78, standing at a lectern in
the Kremlin's Palace of Congress as he opened the morning session.
   On Thursday, Vladimir I. Melnikov, party boss in the Russian
republic's region of Komi, told the conference that Soviets want
high officials who served under Leonid I. Brezhnev removed.
   ``Those who in the past actively promoted the policy of
stagnation may not serve and work on the central party and
government bodies now,'' Melnikov said.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev interrupted to ask who
Melnikov had in mind, and among those the Komi official listed was
Gromyko.
   The official news agency Tass said a delegate later sent a note
to the conference organizers saying Gromyko, who spent 28 years as
foreign minister, had devoted his life to communism.
   But it added: ``We have worked him too hard. And comrade Gromyko
today has fallen behind the times.''
   When Gromyko was named to the largely ceremonial post of
president in 1985, observers believed this was a graceful way to
move the elder statesman out of the mainstream of Soviet
policy-making. The criticism of him at the conference might
indicate he will be eased out of the leadership entirely.
   The chairmanship of the conference is also largely ceremonial
and was rotated among most of the 13 members of the party's ruling
Politburo. Another of Melnikov's targets, Mikhail S. Solomentsev,
74, head of the party's Control Commission, chaired Friday's
afternoon session.
</TEXT>
