<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--LibraryName     07-01 0156</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Library Name,0160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Library Board Approves Controversial Name</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAFTON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new library will be named after a U.S.
Navy spy ship that Israel attacked in 1967, despite complaints the
action might be viewed as anti-Semitic.
   The Library Board on Thursday approved calling the building the
USS Liberty Memorial Public Library. Industrialist Benjamin Grob
and his brother, Theodore, said the name would have to be used when
they donated $250,000 toward the $1.1 million library.
   Thirty-four American sailors died in the attack on the Liberty
during the Six Day War. Israel officially apologized and paid
reparations.
   Critics said the Liberty had been used to generate hatred
against Jews and Israel.
   ``It is unfortunate they made a selection that will make a large
group of people in metropolitan Milwaukee very uncomfortable,''
said Howard Schoenfeld, president of the Milwaukee Jewish Council.
   Library board officials insisted the name was meant to honor the
sailors who died.
</TEXT>
