<1ST_LINE>u i PM-ToxicTanker 1stLd-Writethru a0623 07-01 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Toxic Tanker, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0623,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede IJMUIDEN, Netherlands</HEAD>
<HEAD>Salvage Workers Try Again To Raise Sunken Ship</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES thruout with latest developments. Corrects spelling
of acrylonitrile.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salvage workers today resumed
efforts to raise a sunken tanker after toxic chemicals began
leaking from the ship, Dutch television reported.
   Television reports said workers sawed the Dutch chemical tanker
Anna Broere into two pieces and planned to hoist the parts from the
floor of the North Sea. It said none of the highly poisonous
acrylonitrile stored in tanks escaped during the operation.
   On Thursday, salvage crews had to flee when an acrylonitrile
tank suddenly sprang a leak during efforts to lift the ship, a
coast guard spokesman said. No injuries were reported.
   Workers used a 16-ton chain to separate the ship's back section,
which contains the engine room, from the front part where the tanks
are located, the television report said.
   Crews have been trying to salvage the ship and its dangerous
cargo since May 27, when the Anna Broere sank after a collision
with a freighter off the Netherlands' west coast. It was carrying
1,600 tons of acrylonitrile, a highly carcinogenic and inflammable
agent used by the plastics industry.
   The two sections were expected to lifted to the surface during
the weekend, the report said.
   Water samples taken during Thursday's salvage attempt showed a
sudden increase in the levels of acrylonitrile in the water at the
site, according to a coast guard official, who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
   He said that at about 9.30 p.m. Thursday, those levels rose to
more than seven times the amount considered safe by the Dutch
environment ministry.
   The divers immediately boarded small boats kept nearby for
emergencies after the release of the toxic chemicals, the spokesman
said.
   A first attempt to salvage the Anna Broere failed when two of
the four steel cables holding the vessel broke, causing the ship to
disappear in the waves again.
</TEXT>
