<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--LawsuitsSettled     07-01 0137</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Lawsuits Settled,0140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Continental Crash Lawsuits Settled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three more lawsuits stemming from the November
1987 crash of Continental Airlines Flight 1713 have been settled
out of court, a federal judge said Friday.
   Eleven federal cases concerning the crash now have been settled
without trial. The terms of the latest settlements weren't filed
with the court, Chief U.S. District Judge Sherman G. Finesilver
said.
   About 40 federal lawsuits have been filed against Continental
and its parent corporation, Texas Air, since the Nov. 15 crash that
killed 28 people and injured 54 at Denver's Stapleton International
Airport. Some of the lawsuits also name McDonnell-Douglas Corp.,
manufacturer of the DC-9.
   All the cases filed in U.S. District Courts were transferred to
Finesilver for discovery proceedings.
   Finesilver said he may hold further settlement conferences this
summer.
</TEXT>
