<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 1432EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Drought-Insects Bjt   07-01 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Insects, Bjt,0636</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Insects Attack Drought-Plagued Crops; Wildlife Also Endangered</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAULA FROKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grasshoppers and other insects left hungry by
the drought are wreaking havoc on what remains in farm fields,
while young trees are depending on young people scooping buckets of
water from city lakes to sustain them.
   The good news is a low mosquito population this summer _ but
``I'd rather have the moisture on my grass,'' says Ross Green of
the Metropolitan Mosquito Control District in St. Paul.
   Yellowjackets and wasps may take the place of mosquitoes and be
more aggressive at picnics and near garbage cans as they search for
food, said University of Minnesota entomologist Jeffrey Hahn.
   ``It could be that they just die from a lack of food. But it
also could be that they will be driven to interact with people when
they might not normally do that,'' he said.
   Other insects also are taking a toll.
   ``We've definitely seen more treatment for grasshoppers than at
any time I remember,'' said Carlyle Holen, area extension agent in
crop pest management in northwestern Minnesota's Crookston office.
   ``Many thousands of acres have been treated over the past month,
and there still are fields that need treatment that perhaps the
farmers haven't even discovered yet,'' he said.
   Wheat-stem maggots, normally found in 1 percent of the fields in
the Red River Valley, are showing up this summer in 30 percent to
40 percent of the fields, Holen said. The maggots sever wheat and
barley stems.
   Dry weather appears to be responsible for a large drop in the
number of European corn borers that feed on corn plant leaves and
later bore into the stem.
   Record dryness coupled with near-record heat during the past few
months has stressed young trees and forced wildlife to change their
habits.
   Young trees planted in Minneapolis over the past several years
to replace those ravaged by Dutch elm disease are facing the dual
threat of insufficient moisture and hungry insects such as aphids
and bark beetles, said Hahn.
   The Minneapolis Park Board this week recruited 260 inner-city
young people to dip buckets into the city's lakes and pour the
water on young trees nearby. The lakes, highly popular for sailing,
swimming and picnicking, are down slightly.
   The city already maintains its 160,000 young trees planted in
the past 10 years with 23 water trucks. But the concern now is to
spread the word via the bucket brigade to homeowners.
   ``We thought that if people down at the lakes saw all the kids
down there watering the trees that are starting to wilt and dry,
people will catch on to the news that many of the small trees are
wilting and severely stressed and that they all should be out there
watering,'' said Parks Board special projects director Paul Domholt.
   Minneapolis, which draws all its water from the depleted
Mississippi River, has instituted limited lawn sprinkling
restrictions; adjacent St. Paul is seeking voluntary conservation.
Both cities have agreed to take stronger measures if the river
falls below a certain point.
   Duck-hunters face a shortened waterfowl season this year as the
birds move to regions with more moisture in search of nesting
sites, said Tim Bremicker, resource manager for the Minnesota
Department of Natural Resources.
   ``The drought quickly deteriorated a lot of the good breeding
wetlands,'' Bremicker said. ``The ducks then delay nesting or they
don't nest at all. They move into the northern parklands in
Minnesota, where we still have a lot of water _ comparatively.''
   Biologists also are concerned about other game.
   ``Any animal has a preferred climate, and when you move outside
that preferred climate birds or mammals become stressed,''
Bremicker said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
