<DOCNO> AP880701-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 1641EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lefebvre     07-01 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lefebvre,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Traditionalist Bishop Says Fight Just Beginning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of a traditionalist Roman Catholic
seminary in Connecticut, who was excommunicated as soon as he
became a bishop, said Friday he feels ``some sorrow'' for Pope John
Paul II and the fight has just begun.
   Bishop Richard Williamson also said history will prove
Archbishop Marcel Lefebvre, who consecrated four bishops Thursday
in defiance of the pope, is right in opposing modernism in the
church. The Vatican excommunicated all five men after the ceremony
in Econe, Switzerland.
   Williamson, a Briton who converted from the Anglican Church,
recalled that the early Christian theologian Athanasius was
excommunicated in the 4th century but eventually made a saint.
Athanasius was a champion of orthodoxy in the 4th century intrigues
over what became known as the Arian heresy.
   ``It was proved that Athanasius was right all along,'' he told
The Associated Press in a telephone interview from Econe, the site
of Lefebvre's Swiss seminary.
   The schism created by the consecrations and resulting
excommunications was the first major split in the church since the
so-called Old Catholics broke with Rome in 1870 after the doctrine
of papal infallibility was proclaimed.
   When asked what practical consequences he expected the Vatican
sanction to bring, Williamson said:
   ``The fight has just started. I hope that the issues begin to
clear and we will come out of this dreamland in which the devil has
got vast numbers of people asleep, completely unaware there is a
problem. The archbishop said today that he hopes this event will
lance the abscess of modernist Rome.''
   Williamson shrugged off a statement by Vatican spokesman Joaquin
Navarro, who predicted 80 percent of Lefebvre's followers will
leave him after the excommunication.
   ``Poor Father Navarro,'' he said. ``He lives in a different
world than from the world I live in.''
   He was asked whether followers might be shocked by a sentence in
Lefebvre's letter to the four new bishops that mentioned
``antichrists occupying the chair of Peter and the posts of
authority in Rome.''
   In response, he said Christians believe there are ``many
antichrists'' doing the work of ``the Antichrist, the one who is
coming at the end of the world.''
   ``Any enemy of the church is an antichrist,'' he said. ``It is
strong language but you have to remember what the church was 30
years ago and see it today. There is no comparison. There has been
a tremendous work of destruction since the Second Vatican Council.''
   His reference was to the 1962-65 council that produced reforms
Lefebvre says are spreading the ``cancer of liberalism'' in the
church.
   Williamson said he was ``not sorry that the archbishop refused
to enter into any compromise with those who do not understand
tradition.''
   To a question about whether the traditionalists were in schism,
he replied that church documents prove Lefbvre is on the ``side of
the absolute truth and Rome is not. Therefore it is obviously not
the archbishop who can be in schism.''
   Williamson, 48, said he did not know of the traditionalist
movement when he converted to Catholicism in 1971. When asked why
he went to Lefebvre's seminary, he said:
   ``I was sent there by a mainstream priest who did not agree with
the archbishop. He is an Irishman who said, `If you keep on opening
your big mouth there is only one place for you and that's Econe'.''
   He said he planned to return on July 7 to his own seminary in
Ridgefield, Conn., which he said has 38 students.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
