<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AbductedNun     07-01 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abducted Nun,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Abducted Nun Back With Her Family</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nun abducted from a New York convent is
relaxed and well and unwilling to press charges against her family,
police said Friday.
   ``She told us that she was not injured, and that she was not
being held against her will,'' said Ray Hulgin, chief of
detectives. ``She was relaxed and smiling. ... We feel comfortable
that she is in total control of her situation.''
   Mary Sue Greve, 22, abducted Sunday by her family from the
Roundtop, N.Y., convent where she was a novice nun, was interviewed
Thursday by sheriff's investigators.
   Police in New York and Ohio have been looking for the woman,
also known as Sister Mary Cecelia, since her father, James, and
brothers Dave, Mark and John pushed her into a waiting car Sunday
as she walked with two nuns on a street near St. Joseph Novitiate
Convent in the Catskill Mountains.
   Dave Greve has said that the abduction took place so the family
could raise objections with Miss Greve about the convent and its
priest, the Rev. Clarence Kelly.
   The convent is operated by a group of conservative Catholics
associated with Archbishop Marcel Lefebvre, the French prelate who
was excommunicated Thursday after a long dispute with the Vatican.
The sect has rebuffed modernist reforms instituted after the Second
Vatican Council of the 1960s and follows traditional practices,
including conducting Mass in Latin.
   Dave Greve said his sister still wants to become a nun and that
the family is searching for a convent for her to join.
   The family, through attorney James Condit, contacted Hamilton
County authorities Thursday afternoon. New York State Police have
misdemeanor arrest warrants for Miss Greve's father and brothers.
   Hulgin said the investigators' conversation with Miss Greve was
tape-recorded and mailed to New York authorities.
   Sgt. John Vansteenburg of the New York State Police said
Thursday that the warrants against the family would ``most
definitely'' be dropped once the tape was received and the reports
from Hamilton County confirmed.
   Hulgin said investigators did not delve into the particulars of
the kidnapping or what had transpired since Sunday.
   ``Our concern was that she was not a victim,'' Hulgin said.
   Miss Greve and her parents ``won't be around for a while,'' Dave
Greve said Thursday. ``This has been tough on all of us. Mary Sue
is very upset, and I'm a nervous wreck. But (Mary Sue) looks great
to me.''
</TEXT>
