<DOCNO> AP880701-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 1809EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-Drought     07-01 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Drought,0640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northwest Drought `Worst in 50 Years'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A severe drought in Mexico's
northwestern grainbelt is rapidly depleting wells and irrigation
dams, leaving farmers with little more to do than ``stare at the
sky.''
   Vital cropland sits idle, cattle are dying and the government is
wondering how it will pay for all the food it will have to import.
   ``We've got 15,000 tractors and 2,000 harvesting machines doing
nothing,'' said Nicolas de los Rios, research chief for the
Confederation of Agriculture Associations in the northwestern
Pacific coastal state of Sinaloa.
   Recent rains in other important agricultural areas prevented a
national catastrophe, although wheat yields are down about 15
percent and other crops are expected to be off due to late planting
and low soil moisture.
   But farmers and cattle ranchers in the northwest are facing what
some have said is the worst drought in nearly half a century.
   Most affected are Sinaloa and the northwestern border state of
Sonora. They have been dry for nearly a year.
   ``Sinaloa is experiencing its worst drought in memory,'' Rios
said in a telephone interview.
   More than 20,000 head of cattle have died in Sonora alone,
Arturo Ortega, president of the state Cattle Ranchers Union, told
the Mexico City newspaper El Universal.
   Insufficient moisture in Baja California and Chihuahua still
threatens non-irrigated fields and pastureland.
   Cattle losses in Chihuahua, Mexico's largest state bordering
Texas and New Mexico, are into the thousands and large parts of the
state bypassed the corn-planting season due to parched cropland.
   Chihuahua began importing cattle from the United States last
week.
   ``In other years farmers would be working intensely right now,''
said Kenneth Shwedel, an agriculture economist in Mexico City for
the National Bank of Mexico.
   Instead, said Shwedel, ``They're staring at the sky.''
   It has rained in the northeastern border state of Nuevo Leon,
whose capital is Monterrey. But the state government in this
semi-arid industrial center announced this week a plan to seed
clouds so to raise dam-water levels.
   De los Rios said 970,000 acres of cropland have been left
barren, meaning production of soybean, rice, sorghum and corn will
drop by 1.1 million tons in Sinaloa alone.
   ``We're talking about a loss of 15 billion pesos ($6.5 million)
in direct salaries to workers,'' he said.
   Agriculture production on the northwestern desert lands depends
largely on irrigation, but low water levels in the dams forced the
cancellation of the spring planting season in some areas.
   All of Mexico's soybeans, half the sorghum and most of the corn,
beans and rice are planted during the spring cycle.
   De los Rios said the water supply in Sinaloa's seven dams has
fallen to 8 percent to 10 percent of total capacity.
   Sonora's 17 irrigation dams are down to about 25 percent of
capacity, and the supply is dropping, said Hector Roman de Vega,
president of the state Confederation of Agriculture Organizations.
   ``Cultivations of soybean and sesame have been restricted to
almost zero in the entire Yaqui and Mayo valleys,'' de Vega said.
The two valleys total nearly 775,000 acres.
   Shwedel said the federal government's inflation-fighting program
will face some tough challenges because of the drought.
   ``We're walking on a tightrope,'' he said.
   Under a plan to reduce inflation that hit a record 159 percent
last year, the government has pledged to reduce spending and froze
wages and prices of dozens of basic consumer goods.
   Although many crops have been salvaged, Mexico still is faced
with spending $100 million to $700 million more than it did last
year on imported food and feed, according to Shwedel. In 1987,
Mexico spent $1.3 billion, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
