<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon     07-01 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Car Bombs Rock Lebanon</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Mar Elias in 10th graf and Bar Elias in 11th graf are cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cars packed with explosives blew up
Friday on a busy block in west Beirut and near a Syrian army
checkpoint in the Bekaa valley, killing one person and injuring 52,
police said.
   A spokesman for a PLO splinter group, the Fatah-Uprising, blamed
supporters of Palestine Liberation Organizaton leader Yasser Arafat
for the two blasts, which occurred 30 minutes apart.
   The first explosion sent flames shooting across west Beirut's
crowded Hamra Street, killing one person and injuring 32, a police
spokesman said. The street is west Beirut's main commercial strip.
   The spokesman said a green Renault 12 rigged with 22 pounds of
explosives went off at about 11:55 a.m. (4:55 a.m. EDT) in front of
the downtown Grand Hotel. The explosion shattered windows in the
hotel and nearby buildings.
   Police could not confirm a state radio report that the person
killed was the automobile's driver.
   They said most of the injured were treated at hospitals for
wounds caused by flying glass and later released.
   Syrian soldiers fired their AK-47 automatic rifles in the air to
make way for ambulances and fire engines and to disperse onlookers,
many of them worried about family members who happened to be in the
area.
   ``My 17-year-old son was in a nearby barber's shop. Was anyone
hurt there?'' a frenzied woman asked a member of the local Red
Cross.
   Syrian soldiers and intelligence agents also harassed
journalists, hitting reporters with rifle butts, slapping
photographers and confiscating cameras.
   Police earlier had defused a bomb found in a Mercedes Benz that
had been parked near the Helou police barracks in West Beirut's
busy Mar Elias street, they said.
   In the second blast, police said a Mercedes Benz exploded 15
feet from a Syrian army checkpoint in the Bekaa valley town of Bar
Elias. Two Syrian soldiers were among the 20 wounded.
   Police said the car was packed with about 44 pounds of TNT and
blew up about 12:25 p.m. (5:25 a.m. EDT). The explosion set four
other cars on fire, police said.
   The explosions, the seventh and eighth car bombings in Lebanon
this year, came nine days after a similar explosion killed one
person and wounded 18 others in East Beirut's Christian district of
Karantina.
   By police count, the previous six car bombings killed 94 people
and wounded 251. There have been no claims of responsibility for
any of the bombings.
   In Damascus, the spokesman for the Syria-backed Fatah-Uprising
blamed the car bombings on Arafat's Fatah guerrillas.
   ``Such criminal acts are directed against the Syrian army and
its national role in Lebanon,'' Col. Abdul Hadi al-Nashnash said in
a statement, and were designed to ``create tension in other areas
of Lebanon.''
   Earlier, the leader of Fatah-Uprising was quoted as saying that
all Fatah guerrillas would be driven from Lebanon. Col. Saeed Mousa
charged that Arafat was trying to create an independent province in
the southern port city of Sidon.
   Arafat troops evacuated the Chatilla refugee camp in Beirut on
Tuesday and went to Sidon after Mousa's followers overran the
devastated area Monday. Fatah-Uprising is besieging the shantytown
of Bourj el-Barajneh on the city's southern edge.
   ``Arafat is currently seeking to concentrate his forces in Sidon
to create a canton ... but he will fail there as he had failed in
Beirut,'' Mousa was quoted as saying in an interview published
Friday in the Beirut daily Ad-Diyar.
   Mousa broke away from Arafat's Fatah, the largest PLO faction,
in 1983 and set up headquarters for Fatah-Uprising in Damascus, the
Syrian capital.
   By police count 127 people have been killed and 527 wounded
since the latest round of fighting for control ofr two Beirut camps
broke out May 1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880701-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 1509EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-NATO-Woerner     07-01 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NATO-Woerner,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woerner Replaces Carrington As Top NATO Official</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manfred Woerner became NATO's top
political official Friday and warned that the West still remains
under military threat from the East bloc despite Soviet efforts at
reform.
   The former West German defense minister spoke to reporters
shortly after taking over from Britain's Lord Carrington as the
alliance's secretary-general. Woerner, 53, is the first West German
to hold the post since the alliance was formed in 1949.
   ``We face a Soviet policy that inspires many hopes but has not
given any tangible indication that its military effort will
slacken,'' he said.
   Woerner called on the Soviets and their East European allies to
follow what he called the North Atlantic Treaty Organization's
example of maintaining only the military forces needed for
defensive purposes.
   ``That would be a decisive new turn for the foreign and security
policy of the Soviet Union and conclusive evidence of the
well-publicized `new thinking in the Soviet Union and Warsaw
Pact,''' he said.
   His comments echoed those of Gen. John Galvin, NATO's supreme
military commander in Europe, who warned the West not to be lulled
into a false sense of security by Gorbachev's reforms.
   Galvin, speaking to a group of American reporters today in
London, said Moscow has shown no change in military policy.
   ``I see a lot of wishful thinking, a lot of romanticism, about
the way things are going,'' Galvin said. ``On the military side ..
. I can find nothing really that has changed.''
   The two spoke as American and Soviet inspectors traveled to each
other's countries to begin the task of verifying compliance with
the superpower intermediate-range nuclear missile treaty signed in
December.
   Woerner is the seventh NATO secretary-general. The appointment
holds no fixed term.
   Fluent in English and French, he holds a doctorate in
international law and served as a conservative Christian Democratic
Union member of the Bundestag, or West German parliament, for 23
years before resigning this year to take the Brussels appointment.
   Woerner was Bonn's defense minister for nearly six years.
   As NATO secretary-general, Woerner is chairman of the main
decision-making bodies, including the North Atlantic Council and
the Defense Planning Committee, which coordinate the members'
national policies. The secretary-general also heads an
international staff of 1,500.
   On Wednesday, Woerner will travel to Norway for his first
official visit to a member country. Last fall, after Carrington
announced his plans to retire, Woerner and former Norwegian prime
minister Kaare Willoch engaged in a rare public contest for the
NATO appointment.
   It ended when Oslo withdrew Willoch's nomination and on Dec. 10,
the alliance foreign ministers approved Woerner's appointment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880701-0163 </DOCNO>
