<HEAD>Governor Files to Run Against Sen. Hecht</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Restores state in dateline.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Dick Bryan has filed as a
Democratic candidate for U.S. Senate, saying that incumbent
Republican Sen. Chic Hecht has become ``a captive of the ideology
of the far right.''
   Bryan, 50, also said Thursday he has collected $1.8 million of
his anticipated $3 million campaign warchest.
   The governor, halfway through his second four-year term, said he
was sure that despite the intense campaign schedule planned for the
next several months he could complete work on a proposed state
budget that must be ready for submission to the 1989 Legislature
next January.
   He also said Democratic Lt. Gov. Bob Miller was getting briefed
on the budget proposal so that he could take over smoothly as
governor in January should Bryan defeat Hecht.
   Bryan criticized Hecht's support of increased defense spending
and said Hecht repeatedly has voted against federal funding for
education and to oppose nuclear arms treaties. Hecht is completing
his first term.
