<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0664 07-01 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0664,0715</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top Likud Candidate Calls For Mass Deportations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts 1st graf to clarify that it should be policy to
deport and open fire; SUBS grafs 12-13 ``He said ...'' to ADD
background.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who may become the nation's foreign
minister said Friday it should be Israel's policy to deport
Palestinian activists and to open fire on rioters to crush the
7-month-old rebellion in the occupied lands.
   A Palestinian woman died of gunshot wounds to the head suffered
in an army raid on her village May 18, said officials at Mukassad
Hospital in Jerusalem.
   Only a harsh crackdown can restore Israel's ability to deter
revolt among the 1.5 million Palestinians of the West Bank and Gaza
Strip, said Benyamin Netanyahu, a former ambassador to the United
Nations and a leading candidate in the November parliamentary
election.
   Netanyahu could be the next foreign minister if his right-wing
Likud bloc wins the election. Likud and the rival center-left Labor
Party share a tenuous ``national unity'' coalition and recent polls
show them running even in the election campaign.
   Soldiers shot Fatima Kassem, 24, during a raid on Abwein, an
isolated West Bank mountain village, and killed another villager,
the hospital officials said.
   Her death brought to 214 the number of Palestinians killed since
violence began Dec. 8 in the West Bank and Gaza, which Israel
captured from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 war. Four Israelis also
have been slain.
   Netanyahu told The Associated Press on Friday that Israel should
``expel the main core of inciters who plan, organize and execute
the riots. ... We are talking about hundreds of people.''
   Thousands of Arab activists have been arrested in the past seven
months, but Netanyahu said prison terms no longer serve as a
deterrent. Local leaders are replaced as soon as they are arrested,
he said.
   Israel's expulsion of 21 Arabs has brought condemnation from
abroad, including criticism by U.S. officials who say the action
violates international law and human rights conventions.
   Netanyahu told Israeli reporters Thursday the United Nations
spent several minutes censuring Israel when four Arabs were
expelled earlier this year, and said the censure would last only a
few minutes more if Israel depoarted hundreds. He resigned as
ambassador four months ago to become a candidate.
   The former ambassador told the AP on Friday authorities must let
soldiers and Israeli civilians shoot with ``intent to neutralize''
Arabs throwing stones and firebombs.
   He said it should be Israel's declared policy to open fire on
Arabs throwing firebombs and rocks. ``If a rioter throws a
firebomb, he should know he could be shot to death,'' Netanyahu
declared. ``The vast majority of the Israeli voters favors much
tougher measures, and this cuts across the political spectrum.''
   Netanyahu said the policy must be valid for Israeli soldiers and
Jewish settlers alike. ``Settlers should be allowed to use force to
protect their lives,'' he said.
   He also demanded more restrictions on television camera crews,
contending that their presence feeds the violence, but said the
restrictions should not apply to print and radio reporters.
   Israel already puts severe limits on media access, frequently
declaring sites of violence to be closed military areas.
   The Labor Party, led by Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, has said
the violence must stop before peace talks can begin, but also
favors trading occupied territory for peace. Likud opposes
territorial concessions.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, head of the Likud bloc, said
Friday the rebellion's aim goes beyond ending the occupation to a
``confrontation over everything: our existence, our independence.''
He said domestic debates over territorial compromise weaken
Israel's negotiating position.
   A report in the Jerusalem Post said the Arab revolt had caused
several diplomatic setbacks for Israel.
   Quoting sources in Jerusalem, it said Poland and Greece
retreated from plans to raise the level of relations, Portugal
decided not to open an embassy in Israel and Ireland refused to
accept a resident Israeli ambassador.
   A Foreign Ministry official confirmed Greece had decided not to
open an embassy because of the uprising, but said he did not know
if that was the reason for decisions by the other countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
