<HEAD>Four Construction Vehicles Burned In Attack Near Airport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attackers believed to be opposed to the expansion
of New Tokyo International Airport burned five construction trucks
and three buses in two separate incidents Friday, police said.
   No injuries were reported in the arson attacks. Police found
time-ignition devices in both areas and were investigating whether
the same people may have been behind both attacks.
   In Narita, 40 miles northeast of Tokyo and four miles northwest
of the airport, attackers burned four construction trucks and
damaged the office walls of Tsurushima Kenki Co., which leased the
equipment, police said.
   In Sekishiro, 63 miles northeast of Tokyo, four buses and a
four-ton truck were destroyed in a parking lot, police said.
   Friday's attacks raised to seven the number of sabotage
incidents this year suspected to have been conducted against
companies involved in the expansion of the airport.
   Farmers and radical opponents have clashes with police over the
years to protest the airport and more recently the construction of
two new runways.
