<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--HongKong     07-01 0142</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Hong Kong,0144</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain And China Set Up Permanent Base For Liaison Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British-Chinese liaison team on Hong Kong set
up a permanent base in the colony Friday, nine years to the day
before Britain is scheduled to hand the territory back to China.
   The Joint Liaison Group is a forum for China and Britain to
discuss arrangements for the transfer of the colony to Chinese
sovereignty in 1997. The group has discussed issues such as the
territory's defense and participation in international
organizations.
   Established under the 1984 British-Chinese agreement on Hong
Kong's future, the liaison group has met three times annually for
three years, rotating between Beijing, London and the colony.
   The group established a permanent base in Hong Kong because the
two sides will need closer cooperation in the final years before
the turnover.
