<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 1518EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-ConventionDesign     07-01 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Convention Design,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Want High-Tech Look, Down to Balloons and Bunting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even the balloons and bunting are supposed to
have a high-tech look at this month's Democratic National
Convention.
   ``We want the people to see this thing as an organized, unified
convention _ people who've got their act together,'' Dan Lee,
deputy chief executive officer for the July 18-21 event, said in an
interview Friday.
   Bold tones of red, white and blue will be replaced by ``soft
blues, soft reds and gray tones'' on the podium. Lee said this
``more futuristic look'' will be used around The Omni and, to some
degree, will replace traditional bunting.
   ``It's not exactly bunting,'' Lee said of the decorations
planned for the skyboxes for VIPs. But he promised plenty of color
using paint, bunting and flags.
   Balloons in some entry areas will take the form of ``air
tubes,'' thick air-filled creations ``that will be intertwined in
some of the architectural structures,'' Lee said.
   Although Michael Dukakis' campaign has yet to set final plans
for the demonstration following his acceptance speech, Lee
suggested balloons won't simply drop from nets.
   ``There are a lot of different ways to use balloons these days _
balloon structures, different ways of releasing them,'' he said.
   Still, Lee promised the celebration of the nominee will include
``lots of flags, confetti, balloons, noisemakers, lots of
traditional things.''
   Less dramatic moments in the convention are being planned with
an eye toward projecting a calm, uncluttered image, a main goal of
the podium design.
   In past conventions, Lee said, ``there were always a lot of
people walking behind the speaker and everything. We just wanted to
eliminate a lot of that.''
   So only a handful of convention officials will have seats on the
main speakers' platform, and they will not be in the line of prime
camera angles. Party staffers will be seated with reporters beside
the platform.
   Above, two giant screens will project closed-circuit views of
the speaker, promotional films or graphics illustrating speeches,
Lee said.
   For the first time, the party will broadcast floor proceedings
and interviews with various officials over a satellite feed, making
it available to anyone with a satellite dish.
   Don Fowler, the convention's chief executive officer, has said
previously the convention's futuristic look will be enhanced by the
computer terminals which will be used to record and count many
preliminary votes.
   The traditional roll calls for the presidential and vice
presidential candidates still will be held, however.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
