<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     07-01 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTAGE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There are post-mortems, and then there are
postal mortems. Just ask H. Sam Ansell Jr.
   Ansell, owner of the Truesdale Funeral Home here, recently
received a $100 check from an Alletta DeMuir Rue for embalming her
mother and a letter praising the staff for its efforts.
   The letter bore a 2-cent stamp postmarked Nov. 17, 1930, in
Detroit. It also thanked founder George P. Truesdale for extending
credit for the work done on her mother, who apparently died in the
Kalamazoo area and was buried elsewhere.
   ``You have been most kind in letting us have this time to pay
and we sincerely thank you,'' wrote Rue, who listed a return
address in Detroit.
   The check was dated April 4, 1930, and issued by the Bank of
Detroit. But that name had been crossed out and subsituted in
handwriting with that of Jackson Park National Bank in Chicago.
   ``I rather doubt I can present that for payment to a bank,''
Ansell said.
   David Mastervich, an account representative at the post office
in nearby Kalamazoo, said the letter probably encountered a fate
common to long-delayed mail.
   ``We probably moved some equipment that's been there 50 years
and they found a letter under it,'' he said. ``At least no one can
say it didn't get delivered.''
   The Kalamazoo-Portage telephone directory listed two people
named Rue. One number had been disconnected, and a woman who
answered the phone Friday at the second listing said no one named
Rue lived there.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CURTIS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This tiny Upper Peninsula community is
preparing for its annual crawl of fame: the self-styled world
championship turtle races.
   The charity event, sponsored by the Curtis Lions Club, is
expected to draw at least 3,000 fans Sunday to the resort town on
Lake Manistique. Visitors can enter their own turtles for $3, but
the same fee can be used to rent reptiles drafted for the day from
the nearby Seney National Wildlife Refuge.
   ``It is sort of a rent-a-turtle affair,'' said Dick Nunemaker, a
Lions Club member who co-founded the event nine years ago.
   The turtles race, if that is the proper word, down a 12-lane,
12-foot-long raised wooden track. The course record is about five
minutes, Nunemaker said, adding, ``I have to talk very slowly in
announcing the races.''
   Although only one winner is named, the also-crawls are tended
carefully. Les Walstron, a retired conservation officer who gathers
the four- to eight-inch mud turtles from the Seney refuge, feeds
them all the minnows they can eat before returning them to their
usual surroundings.
</TEXT>
