<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Gulf-Roberts     07-01 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Roberts,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mine-Damaged U.S. Warship En Route From Persian Gulf to Newport,
R.I.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. warship severely damaged by an
Iranian mine on April 14 slipped quietly out of the Persian Gulf on
Friday aboard a larger vessel and headed for repairs in the United
States, the Pentagon said.
   The missile frigate USS Samuel B. Roberts was being carried
aboard the Dutch heavy lift ship, Mighty Servant II, a 25,743-ton
semi-submersible cargo vessel that was to take 30 days to carry the
Roberts to its home port of Newport, R.I.
   For security reasons, the Pentagon would not say when the ship
departed Dubai and when it passed through the Strait of Hormuz at
the mouth of the gulf.
   Before the Roberts was hit, it was on duty in the gulf escorting
merchant shipping which has been a target of attacks in the 8-year
Iran-Iraq war.
   The commander of U.S. forces in the region, Gen. George B.
Crist, declined during a meeting with reporters on Thursday to
discuss the Roberts' movements, but he warned Iran against trying
to attack the stricken vessel.
   ``Let them just try,'' he said.
   The Roberts hit a submerged mine on April 14 after stumbling
into what Crist said was a newly laid minefield 50 miles northeast
of Qatar. U.S. officials said Iran had sewn the mines.
   The blast wounded 10 U.S. sailors and ripped a 25-foot gash in
the hull of the 445-foot long, 3,600-ton frigate.
   U.S. forces retaliated by attacking two Iranian oil platforms
April 18, starting a day of fighting in which six Iranian naval
craft were sunk or damaged.
   Crist said Iranian attacks against merchant shipping in the gulf
had dropped off after April 18. However, he said the Iranians were
continuing work on a permanent bunker for Silkwork anti-ship
missiles at Kuhe-Stak, which overlooks the narrow Strait of Hormuz.
   The frigate USS Vincennes, equipped with advanced Aegis radar
and anti-missile missiles, has been posted near the strait with
orders to protect merchant ships from attacks by the Chinese-made
Silkworms.
   About 30 of the Roberts' sailors were accompanying the ship
home. About 140 other crewmen returned to the United States last
week.
</TEXT>
