<1ST_LINE>r w AM-GrainPayments     07-01 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Grain Payments,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Final Wheat, Barley Support Payments for 1987 Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat and barley farmers this month will get
about $190 million as final settlement for participating in last
year's federal price support programs, the Agriculture Department
said Friday.
   The subsidies are ``emergency compensation'' or so-called
Findley payments under the USDA's price support apparatus. The
payments will be in cash and will be issued ``as soon as possible''
through local offices of the department's Agricultural
Stabilization and Conservation Service, said Milton Hertz, head of
the agency.
   Wheat farmers will get about $170 million and barley producers
about $20 million. The final wheat payments are based on a rate of
9\ cents per bushel, and barley at 5 cents per bushel.
   Last January wheat farmers collected $335 million in advance
Findley payments, which are the the result of an amendment by
former Rep. Paul Findley, R-Ill. There were no advances for barley
producers.
   In all, farmers have collected about $3.2 billion under the 1987
wheat program and around $294 million in total barley payments,
according to USDA estimates.
</TEXT>
