<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 2102EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AlienSmuggling     07-01 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Alien Smuggling,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Allows Sanctuary Defense</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former governor's declaration of New
Mexico as a sanctuary state was vague enough to be construed as
carrying the weight of law, and a journalist and minister can use
it as a defense against alien smuggling charges, a judge has ruled.
   Then-Gov. Toney Anaya declared New Mexico a sanctuary in 1986, a
largely symbolic action aimed at people fleeing war in Central
America. It was rescinded when Gov. Garrey Carruthers took office
in January 1987.
   Demetria Martinez, a free-lance religion writer, and the Rev.
Glen Remer-Thamert, a Lutheran minister, were indicted by a federal
grand jury in December on charges of conspiring to smuggle two
pregnant Salvadoran women into the country in 1986.
   The minister contends he tried to help the women because of his
religious beliefs and because he considered them to be refugees
fleeing a war-torn country. He also maintains the women were to put
their babies up for adoption in the United States because they
feared conditions in their homeland.
   The U.S. attorney's office has said Remer-Thamert was motivated
by a so-called adoption-for-profit scheme.
   Martinez has maintained she accompanied Remer-Thamert in her
role as a journalist and should never have been indicted.
   Prosecutors have tried to prevent the minister from using his
religious beliefs as a defense. They also have tried to prevent
both defendants from using the sanctuary declaration.
   U.S. District Judge John Conway ruled Thursday the pair should
not be prohibited from offering evidence ``which could arguably
show that the defendants reasonably relied upon the proclamation.''
   ``The proclamation, while interesting, never mentions the fact
that it is symbolic only,'' Conway wrote.
   Trial is scheduled July 13.
</TEXT>
