<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PorchWoman     07-01 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Porch Woman,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crippled Woman Sits On Porch, Waiting To Die</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILTON, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Annie Jeffrey is unable to walk and spends
most of her time on her front porch, praying, reading the Bible and
waiting to die among the squalor of her rundown home.
   A health official said Friday he does not want to do anything to
take away her right to do what she wants. Mrs. Jeffrey, 88, said
she does not want or need anything else.
   ``When you get as old as I am you have to be satisfied,'' she
said. ``There's a time to put down all the stuff you picked up in
your young life and get ready to meet Jesus.''
   She said she doesn't want to leave her porch, where she's been
for three weeks, because that's where she wants to die. Neighbors
and friends take food to her.
   ``I feel satisfied,'' Mrs. Jeffrey said. ``That's why I stay
here.''
   Jim Hollis, environmental supervisor for the Shelby County
Health Department, said there is nothing the department can do
except accuse Mrs. Jeffrey of violating disposal laws, and it does
not want to do that.
   After Mrs. Jeffrey's living conditions were publicized,
neighbors arrived Thursday and picked up junk from her yard.
   The Rev. A.L. Jones has tried to persuade Mrs. Jeffrey to allow
someone to help her. He wants to get her to a hospital to find out
why she can't walk.
   Jones called the wood frame house a death trap. It has no
electricity, gas or running water. ``If she was a dog, the humane
society would have been over there to do something for her,'' he
said.
   Jones said some of her five stepchildren in California and
Chicago are to arrive this weekend, and he hopes they will take her
with them.
   But Mrs. Jeffreys said she barely knows her stepchildren and
would rather stay at the house where she has lived since 1935. Her
husband died in 1940.
   Delores Smitherman of Montevallo said she took Mrs. Jeffrey into
her home for three months after learning in January that the
woman's feet were badly swollen. Mrs. Smitherman said a doctor
``gave her two prescriptions, but she said that if she could go
home she could use a home remedy.''
   After the swelling went down Mrs. Jeffrey insisted on going home.
</TEXT>
