<HEAD>Death Sentence Sought For Smugglers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has proposed the death
penalty for people who smuggle women out of the country and sell
them into prostitution.
   Prime Minister Moudud Ahmed introduced the bill Thursday in
Parliament, saying capital punishment was needed to halt ``this
gruesome crime against our mothers and sisters.'' The measure is
expected to pass.
   The smugglers recruit their victims with promises of finding
jobs for them as servants in India, Pakistan and the Middle East.
Dhaka newspapers said other women and children were kidnapped.
   Border police last week said they foiled an attempt to smuggle
135 women and children across the border to India. Authorities say
they have rescued more than 400 women from smugglers this year.
   More than 50 alleged smugglers have been jailed. Under the law,
the maximum penalty they face if convicted is life imprisonment.
