<HEAD>Five Workers Killed by Scalding, Chemical-Filled Water</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scalding, chemical-filled
water from a broken pipeline sprayed technicians at a
government-owned steel factory, killing five people, officials said
Friday.
   Officials of the Iron and Steel Corp. plant at Newcastle in
Natal province said a sixth man was in critical condition with
severe burns covering most of his body.
   The head of the maintenance department, and four technicians and
engineers died Thursday following the morning accident. They had
been testing a new valve in a hot water pipeline at the plant's
coke ovens when a two-foot-thick pipe fractured and 176-degree
water sprayed over the men.
   A spokesman for Newcastle hospital said they suffered third
degree burns over 80 to 100 percent of their bodies, and that a
chemical in the water had worsened the effects.
