<HEAD>U.S. Welcomes Chinese Support for Cambodian Settlement</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 2nd graf, The Chinese, to fix quote to read `free and
fair' sted `fear and fair'; ADDS 1 graf with comment on Khmer
Rouge; ADDS byline</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Friday it welcomes
China's statement of support for a negotiated political settlement
in Cambodia, and Secretary of State George Shultz will discuss the
issue with Chinese leaders during his visit to Beijing later this
month.
   The Chinese statement ``mirrors our own views that a Vietnamese
withdrawal and free and fair elections and a secure atmosphere are
essential conditions for a lasting solution to the Cambodian
conflict,'' department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley told reporters.
   Mrs. Oakley also said the current announced withdrawal from
Cambodia of 50,000 Vietnamese occupation soldiers, including senior
command elements, ``if fully implemented would represent a positive
step toward stability in the region.''
   She added, however, that ``the announced withdrawal would still
leave in Cambodia at leaart 50,000 to 70,000 Vietnamese troops
whose presence would prevent any genuine expression of Cambodian
political self-determination.''
   ``We continue to maintain that the resolution of the Cambodian
problem would require a settlement agreement which provides for
complete withdrawal of Vietnamese troops from Cambodia.''
   Vietnamese forces invaded Cambodia in 1978, ending bloody rule
by the Khmer Rouge, blamed for the death of millions of Cambodians.
Mrs. Oakley said it is not known if the current withdrawal will
lead to a total Vietnamese pullout from Cambodia, and she did not
address concerns about a possible Khmer Rouge return to power in
Cambodia after the Vietnamese leave.
   However, Shultz's talks in Beijing later this month will be
preceded by extensive meetings in Bangkok with leaders of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations.
   The United States has been working closely with ASEAN countries
in seeking an end to the Vietnamese occupation of Cambodia as well
as a solution to the Khmer Rouge problem.
   A senior U.S. official said later the United States has made it
clear to China, the strongest supporter of the Khmer Rouge, that
return to power by the Khmer Rouge is out of the question. The
United States hopes that Cambodian Prince Norodom Sihanouk will be
able to find a solution to the future government structure, added
the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
