<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AmishTrade-in     07-01 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amish Trade-in,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amish Winner of New Pickup Truck to Trade It for Surrey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CENTREVILLE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Amish farmer who won a new pickup
truck in a grocery store contest will trade it in for a horse-drawn
buggy because the truck doesn't fit into his religion's simple
lifestyle.
   Leroy Hostetler won the fire-engine-red Ford Ranger, worth
$7,500, when his name was drawn from hundreds of thousands of
entries last month in a Village Market Food Centers drawing in
Huntington, Ind.
   The farmer, who operates 105 acres with his brother outside this
town of 1,000, learned that he had won Wednesday when the owner of
the local Village Market store, Allan Murk, drove out to his farm.
   Hostetler doesn't have a telephone, in keeping with Amish custom
of dressing simply and spurning modern conveniences like phones and
electrical appliances.
   Hostetler was surprised at winning, Murk said. But ``everybody
envisions what they'd do with something if they won. I think he had
in mind buying himself a new surrey, buggy, whatever you want to
call it.''
   Hostetler should have some money left over once he trades in the
pickup. Murk said a new carriage should cost $1,800 to $3,000.
</TEXT>
