<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Zaccaro 1stLd-Writethru a0626 07-01 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zaccaro, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0626,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zaccaro Jr. Begins Sentence</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Zaccaro arrival at jail,
superintendent's comment. picks up 4th graf pvs, `It's like
being...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Zaccaro Jr. began his
four-month sentence for selling a quarter-gram of cocaine to an
undercover officer by reporting to jail Friday before being put
under house arrest.
   Zaccaro, 24-year-old son of former vice presidential candidate
Geraldine Ferraro, was booked at Chittenden Community Correctional
Center and then left to begin a special house arrest program for
non-violent criminals.
   ``He's come and gone,'' said Philip Scripture, Chittenden
superintendent. ``He was processed, fingerprinted, photographed and
left at 2:30. We treated this as a routine booking.''
   After booking, Zaccaro was to be released to the field
supervision officer to participate in the state's house arrest
program.
   ``It's like being in jail, but without the walls,'' said
Scripture, adding that Zaccaro would be required to stay in his
residence.
   ``He would have a schedule whereby he could leave for work or
community service. He would not be allowed to consume alcohol or
drugs, and parole officers would stop by his place unannounced,
require him at times to blow into an alcohol sensor, or give a
urine sample,'' Scripture said.
   ``He must have a phone so that there can be telephone cheks to
make sure he is there and he would have to request the opportunity
to have visitors.''
   Under the program, Zaccaro could begin the 300 hours of
community service also part of his sentence. The judge ordered
Zaccaro to pay a $1,500 fine as well.
   To be eligible for house arrest, an offender must have committed
a non-violent crime and have been sentenced to fewer than 121 days
in jail, a limit Zaccaro meets by one day.
   Zaccaro was arrested two years ago after selling $25 worth of
cocaine to undercover Officer Laura Manning during Middlebury
College's annual Winter Carnival weekend.
   Zaccaro's conviction still will be appealed to the Supreme
Court. The defense claims Zaccaro was only prosecuted because of
his mother's fame and was treated much more harshly than others
charged with cocaine dealing.
</TEXT>
