<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 1933EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Teachers     07-01 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teachers,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pay For Teachers Reaches New High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Average beginning teacher salaries pushed
past $18,000 for the first time this past school year and average
pay for the entire profession reached a record high of $28,085, a
union survey revealed Friday.
   Teachers earned 17 percent more on average than all American
workers in 1987 and 10 percent more than all government workers,
the American Federation of Teachers said.
   ``The public is really supporting teachers. It's the seventh
straight year salaries have exceeded inflation,'' said F. Howard
Nelson, an assistant research director of the AFT, which released
the survey on the eve of its biennial convention.
   The AFT survey of state departments of education found starting
salaries for the school year that just ended were $18,557, up 5.4
percent from a year earlier and more than double the $9,085
beginners were paid in 1977.
   The average salary for all teachers was up 5.5 percent over
1987, and Jewell C. Gould, the AFT's director of research,
predicted a similar increase for the school year starting this fall.
   The AFT salary data shows Alaska at the top of the pay scale
with average salaries of $40,510 and South Dakota at the bottom
with $19,758.
   But the AFT also ranked the states by cost-of-living and by how
teachers' pay compared to salaries of other workers.
   The adjustment for differences in the cost of living ``shows
that Michigan, Alaska, California and Minnesota pay teachers the
most. Louisiana, Arkansas, Hawaii and South Dakota (are) on the
bottom.''
   Adjusted for inflation, the record $28,085 average salary is
just $665 more than teachers earned in 1972. The average 1972
salary of $9,705 is the equivalent of $27,420 in today's prices.
   Likewise, the beginning salary of $6,970 in 1972 is the
equivalent of $19,739 in today's dollars _ more than today's
starting salaries.
   Gould singled out Pittsburgh, Rochester, N.Y., and the state of
Connecticut as places that are ``setting a new standard for teacher
salaries.''
   The 665,000-member AFT represents nearly a half-million of the
nation's 2.4 million public school teachers, primarily in big
cities. The 1.9 million-member National Education Association,
which opens its convention Monday in New Orleans, has 1.5 million
members.
   ``Connecticut reported the highest salary increase _ 15.8
percent for 1987-88,'' pushing its average pay level to $33,776,
fifth in the nation, the AFT report said.
   Al Fondy, president of both the Pittsburgh and Pennsylvania
Federations of Teachers, said that under a new four-year contract,
average salaries in Pittsburgh will rise from $38,000 to $46,000 by
1991, with top-scale veterans earning $51,000.
   Rochester has a contract that will push its top scale past
$55,000, plus the possibility that lead teachers will earn nearly
$70,000.
   Although teaching pays more on average than other government
work and more than the average job in the private sector, the
report said the average male, year-round worker earned 14 percent
more in 1987 than the average teacher, who gets summers off.
   The average female, year-round worker made only 73 percent as
much as teachers, most of whom are women.
   The AFT said Alaska, California, Connecticut, Michigan, New York
and New Jersey all have starting salaries in excess of $20,000,
while only Vermont and Idaho start teachers off at less than
$15,000.
   Although they earn more on average in real dollars than they did
in 1972, today's teachers are also more experienced, with nearly 16
years in the classoom compared with less than 11 years then, the
AFT said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
