<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 2137EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-KuwaitAirways     07-01 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kuwait Airways,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six-Month Sentence for Man Who Said Kuwaiti Money Was for CIA-Iran
Ploy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge sentenced a former Kuwait
Airways sales manager to a six-month prison term Friday for
stealing $2.5 million from the airline in what the defendant
claimed was a plan with the CIA to woo moderates in Iran.
   The sentence was criticized immediately by a prosecutor as being
too lenient.
   Robert M. Sensi received a three-year sentence with all but six
months suspended for 21 counts of mail fraud, theft and interstate
transportation of stolen securities.
   A further order crediting Sensi with the four months he spent in
a British jail following his 1986 arrest means he will only serve
two months.
   U.S. District Judge George Revercomb acknowledged that the
sentence ``will strike some as extremely lenient.''
   But the judge said the Kuwait government had not produced ``all
knowledgeable witnesses'' who might have supported Sensi's claim
there has been ``some knowledge, some acquiesence, perhaps some
complicity on the part of others.''
   Sensi, 37, had contended that he was authorized by the Kuwaiti
royal family to spend the money, including $1 million to help
finance an initiative with the CIA to make contact with moderates
in Iran.
   During the trial, Sensi testified that he met with CIA Director
William J. Casey in 1986 before embarking on a trip to Iran where
he planned to meet with the Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   Sensi was arrested in London on the first leg of the trip to
Iran.
   Outside the courtroom, Assistant U.S. Attorney Theodore Shamanda
said: ``We accept the judge's sentence as one that is within his
power to impose.''
   But Shamanda added that ``as the trial prosecutor, I do believe
that to be too lenient. When you steal $2.5 million of your
employer's money and get a six-month sentence, what signal does
that send to the community?''
   Sensi could have received five-year prison terms for each of six
mail fraud counts and 10-year sentences for each of the 14 theft
and interstate transportation of stolen securities counts.
   Revercomb imposed the sentence after he rejected Sensi's motion
to set aside the verdict on the basis of newly discovered evidence
to support his claim that the royal family authorized his
expenditures.
   In May, Sensi's lawyers produced an affidavit from the airlines'
former New York manager who said he was aware of a special bank
account used by Sensi to funnel the money from the Kuwait Airways
accounts.
   Inder Sethi, who couldn't be located to testify at the trial,
said in the affidavit that ``it was clear to me that many people,
both in the United States and in Kuwait, were aware of Mr. Sensi's
activities.''
   ``To the best of my knowledge, no one questioned the propriety
of Mr. Sensi's actions during the entire time that I served as a
regional manager,'' the affidavit said.
   But Thomas J. Whalen, who represented Kuwait Airways in a
related civil suit, said in another affidavit that when he
interviewed Sethi last year, Sethi denied any knowledge of special
accounts kept by Sensi.
   ``Mr. Sethi said that he was shocked, or used some similar term,
when he learned about what Sensi had done,'' Whalen said.
   Before taking the bench, Revercomb met with Sethi in his
chambers. Based on his conversation, the judge said he determined
that Sethi's statements did not provide sufficient evidence to
warrant setting aside the verdict and ordering a new trial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
