<HEAD>What Happened To The Heat Wave?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A week after record high temperatures make people sweat from the
Plains to the East Coast, a cold front dropped temperatures to
autumn-like readings Friday from New England to North Carolina and
around the Great Lakes.
   Here is a list of record and record-tying low temperatures, as
reported by the National Weather Service, with the city followed by
Friday's low, and the previous record and year it was set:
   Akron, Ohio, 43, 46 in 1899.
   Atlantic City, N.J., 42, 52 in 1975.
   Beckley, W.Va., 41, 47 in 1982.
   Binghamton, N.Y., 44, 48 in 1986.
   Boston, 50, 51 in 1885, tied July record.
   Bridgeport, Conn., 49, 54 in 1978.
   Bristol, Tenn., 51, tied 1980.
   Cleveland, 45, 48 in 1965.
   Columbus, Ohio, 44, 47 in 1965.
   Dayton, Ohio, 46, 48 in 1899.
   Duluth, Minn., 35, 39 in 1969.
   Elkins, W.Va., 32, 40 in 1982.
   Greensboro, N.C., 55, tied 1938.
   Hartford, Conn., 46, 48 in 1912.
   Huntington, W.Va., 50, 51 in 1982.
   Lansing, Mich., 40, 43 in 1943.
   Parkersburg, W.Va., 45, 50 in 1930.
   Parkersburg airport, 44, 49 in 1982.
   Philadelphia, 52, tied 1943.
   Providence, R.I., 48, 51 in 1943, July record.
   Richmond, Va., 53, 54 in 1919.
   Roanoke, Va., 48, 55 in 1980, July record.
   Scranton, Pa., 44, 46 in 1943.
   Stratford, Conn., 49, 54 in 1978, July record.
   Toledo, Ohio, 40, 43 in 1965.
   Washington, 54, tied 1925.
   Wilmington, Del., 48, 50 in 1943, July record.
   Youngstown, Ohio, 43, 45 in 1965.
