<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Angola     07-01 0150</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Angola,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Department Agrees With Savimbi on Reconciliation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Friday it agrees
with Angolan guerrilla leader Jonas Savimbi that a national
reconciliation is needed to end the conflict in his country.
   Asked to comment on a program advanced in Washington by Savimbi
to end the civil war in his country, department spokeswoman Phyllis
Oakley told reporters, ``In general, we strongly support the
objectives of ending foreign troop presence in Angola, achieving
genuine independence for Namibia (South-West Africa) and obtaining
national reconciliation in Angola. That is the basic message of Dr.
Savimbi's proposals. ... We stand ready to assist in pursuit of
these goals.''
   Savimbi said during his Washington visit this week that he
supoprts the current negotiations involving the United States, the
Angolan communist government, Cuba and South Africa on the
withdrawal of Cuban forces from his counry and independence for
Namibia.
</TEXT>
