<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 1718EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Yeltsin     07-01 0926</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Yeltsin,0953</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ousted Moscow Party Boss Asks to Be Cleared</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Moscow-Party Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A simmering feud in the Soviet leadership
dominated the floor Friday and the first national Communist Party
conference since 1941 adjourned with a burst of candor not seen
since the Soviet Union's infancy.
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev encouraged both sides in the long-rumored
dispute over dismissed Moscow party boss Boris N. Yeltsin to have
their say.
   Yeltsin asked the conference to clear him of blame for an angry
outburst against party conservatives last fall that cost him his
job and a non-voting membership on the ruling Politburo.
   His most powerful opponent, Kremlin No. 2 man Yegor K. Ligachev,
took the floor to say Yeltsin committed many errors and had not yet
learned his lesson.
   More delegates also rose to criticize the wayward one-time
protege of Gorbachev. They accused Yeltsin of being tactless on a
trip abroad and giving interviews to foreign new agencies just to
boost his own prestige. One claimed Yeltsin drove an underling to
suicide.
   Others defended Yeltsin in an open debate, the highlights of
which were shown on television. The broadcast did not break away
even for live coverage of Gorbachev's speech closing the conference.
   Tass, the official news agency, said Yelstin told his 5,000
fellow delegates that his only mistake in criticizing the
bureaucracy last October was in speaking too soon.
   Extraordinary criticism of the Communist establishment was a
hallmark of the four-day meeting, including at least one call for
resignations of the old guard.
   Yeltsin, 57, is an outspoken reformer who became popular with
Muscovites by demanding that stores provide more food and better
consumer goods. Gorbachev brought him into the leadership, but
joined in denouncing him after Yeltsin's speech to an October
meeting of the policy-making Central Committee.
   Yeltsin's speech to the closed meeting has not been published,
but reports said he offered to resign out of frustration over his
inability to control the entrenched bureaucracy in Moscow's party
organization. His comments later were branded ``politically
erroneous,'' and he was fired.
   He rekindled the controversy during last month's U.S.-Soviet
summit in Moscow by calling for Ligachev's resignation during an
interview with Western television correspondents
   In an account carried by Tass, Yeltsin told the conference
Friday: ``I think my only mistake was that I spoke too early,
before the 70th anniversary of the October Revolution.
   ``Taking to heart what happened, I ask the conference to change
the decision of the plenum of the Central Committee. If you find it
possible to do this, you will rehabilitate me in the eyes of the
Communists.''
   Ligachev, widely viewed as a conservative counterweight to the
reform-minded Gorbachev, took the rostrum Friday evening as one of
the final conference speakers.
   Defending his own credentials as a supporter of perestroika, as
Gorbachev's ambitious modernization program is called, Ligachev
said Josef Stalin had executed some members of his family and
expelled others from the party.
   He helped his region become self-sufficient in food while
working as a party leader in Siberia, Ligachev said, whereas ``the
district where you, Boris, worked for nine years now has rationing
of food.''
   Ligachev also denounced Yeltsin for criticizing the old guard.
He credited veteran Politburo members Andrei A. Gromyko, Mikhail S.
Solomentsev and Viktor M. Chebrikov with helping Gorbachev gain
power at a crucial meeting of the Central Committee three years
ago. Without their efforts, Ligachev said, ``others might be
sitting here now'' on the dais.
   He said the leadership is united behind Gorbachev, and declared:
``There are neither conservatives nor reformers among the
leadership.''
   Yeltsin has ``not drawn the necessary conclusions from his
mistakes and the principled criticism of his party comrades,''
Ligachev said.
   Gorbachev, in his closing speech Friday, dealt Yeltsin the final
blow.
   He defended the decision to give Yeltsin the floor, saying ``We
must remove all the shrouds of secrecy,'' then reviewed events that
led to his dismissal, confirming many reports that have circulated
in Moscow for months but never appeared in the official media.
   Taking responsiblity for the decision to promote Yeltsin to the
key Moscow party post, Gorbachev said the Politburo saw his
excesses but did not act quickly enough.
   ``At a certain stage, we saw that something was wrong,'' he
said, and it became apparent Yeltsin ``was not up to the task'' of
running Moscow.
   According to Gorbachev's account, Yeltsin began losing his
temper, barking orders and ``being rude,'' and attacked his own
party organization.
   ``At first we thought he might be right,'' Gorbachev said. ``But
when he began changing one after another of the party functionaries
we became concerned and told him so. It was a time when practical
problems had to be solved, but he did not act accordingly.''
   He said the Politburo supported Yeltsin until, during
Gorbachev's vacation last summer, the Moscow party chief wrote him
asking to be relieved of his responsibilities.
   Gorbachev said he kept the letter confidential until they met
when he returned from vacation. ``We decided to wait'' after the
70th anniversary celebrations the first week in November, he said,
but then Yeltsin spoke out at the Central Committee meeting.
   As Gorbachev recounted the story, he referred to a record of the
secret proceeding. He said the Central Committee wanted to accept
the resignation but he decided to wait until after the anniversary.
   When the celebrations were over, Gorbachev went to the Moscow
party headquarters to participate in the meeting at which Yeltsin
was ousted. He said at the time that Yeltsin was overly ambitious.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
