<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FERCNomination     07-01 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FERC Nomination,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan To Nominate Stalon To Additional Time On FERC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan intends to nominate Charles
Stalon, a holdover member of the Federal Energy Regulatory
Commission, to serve additional time on the commission, the White
House announced Friday.
   Stalon, 58, filled an unexpired term when he came to the
commission in 1984. That term ran out last October. The law permits
him to stay on for a year as long as no successor has been sworn in.
   On Thursday, the president said he intends to nominate Elizabeth
Moler of the Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee staff to
Stalon's seat.
   Friday's announcement said Stalon, if confirmed, would fill the
remainder of the term of Michael Naeve, who resigned in March.
Naeve's term would have expired in October 1989.
   Stalon, who fills one of the two mandatory Democratic seats, has
been an intellectual force behind many of the commission's
deregulatory initiatives natural gas and wholesale electricity led
by the chairman, Martha O. Hesse.
   Fourteen Democratic senators wrote Reagan several months ago
asking him to renominate Stalon.
   Trade publications two weeks ago carried reports that Sens.
Bennett Johnston, D-La., chairman of the Energy Committee, and
James McClure, R-Idaho, the ranking Republican member, had asked
Reagan not to renominate Stalon because he could not be confirmed.
   Stalon said he did not know what was behind the opposition to
his renomination.
   The announcement still does not settle the commission's
membership uncertainties. Ms. Hesse has not been confirmed as
chairman a year after her nomination. Anthony Sousa has resigned
effective later this month and Charles Trabandt's term expires in
October.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
