<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FAATechCenter     07-01 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FAA Tech Center,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Technical Center Celebrates 30 Years Of Air Research</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POMONA, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration
Technical Center celebrated its 30th anniversary Friday, touting
its many research developments and contributions to passengers
safety.
   ``We have some of the finest scientists in the world who live
here. This is probably one of the finest research environments in
the world,'' said Edward T. Harris, the center's director, who
officiated at a small cake-cutting ceremony.
   The center is believed to be the largest research facility of
its kind in the world. More than 2,000 people work at the
5,059-acre complex and it has an annual payroll of $85 million for
employees and contractors.
   The center just outside Atlantic City has helped develop
fire-retardant seat cushions, emergency evacuation chutes that
won't melt in a fire, floor lights to guide passengers through
smoky aisles, computer programs for air traffic controllers and a
new warning device to help pilots avoid mid-air collisions well
before other planes are in sight.
   Researchers also are working on projects that include finding
ways of detecting bulk explosives and plastic weapons to avoid
terrorist hijackings, and using satellites to assist air
controllers with overseas flights, Harris said.
   The technical center is largely responsible for keeping the
aviation industry in line with projected air traffic growth, he
said.
   U.S. Rep. William Hughes, D-N.J., proposed a broadened role for
the center.
   ``There has to be a more direct link between our research
facilities and universities and colleges. We're losing
opportunities, and this is an ideal site to develop a National
Aviation Institute, which would provide undergraduate and graduate
training ...,'' Hughes said.
   Such an institute, although still in the planning stage, would
incorporate the expertise of specialists in the aviation industry,
government and universities, FAA officials said.
   Technical center employees do much of their work in
laboratories, such as a giant hangar where fires are set in a
hollowed-out aircraft fuselage or the airport security lab that is
surrounded by barbed wire. But research also takes place in the air
with test aircraft.
</TEXT>
