<2ND_LINE>AM-Stabbing Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0681,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Stabbed To Death, Recent Immigrant Held</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with details from police news conference,
relatives comments. CORRECT that victims were three females and one
male, sted two men and two women; fixes spelling of first name of
victim to Ric, sted Rick.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SNJ2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE CARPENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An amusement park worker was in
custody Friday after the stabbing deaths of four relatives and the
wounding of a fifth, a crime neither police nor the uncle who
summoned authorities can explain.
   Joselito C. Camangian, 23, who arrived in Santa Clara from the
Philippines about five months ago, was arrested late Thursday at a
gas station about a block from the duplex where the bodies of his
brother, two sisters and a niece were found.
   The slayings apparently occurred late Thursday, but authorities
had not established a motive, Sgt. Pat Kolstad said. A 13-inch
kitchen knife, believed to be the murder weapon, was found in a
yard three houses from the scene, he said.
   Elmer Gale, Camangian's uncle, said that after the rampage, his
nephew said calmly, ``Maybe I'm going crazy. ... I don't know what
I did,'' and told him to call police.
   Kolstad and relatives said Camangian had undergone drug
rehabilitation in the Philippines about five years ago, but
couldn't say what drug was involved or whether there had been a
relapse since he came to the U.S. He was listening to rock music on
the radio when he suddenly began attacking family members, Kolstad
said.
   Camagian, who had started work this week at a pizzeria at Great
America amusement park, was booked for investigation of four counts
of homicide and one count of attempted homicide, police said.
   Officers arrived in response to a call from Gale, who lives in
the other half of the duplex where the stabbings occurred.
   Gale ran for help after his niece, Candida C. Camangian, 26, and
her brother, Ric Camangian, 29, came to his home for help. Both
were wounded; the man later died.
   ``I heard a woman screaming, asking for help at my door,'' Gale,
48, said on Friday. ``It was my niece. She told me to call an
ambulance because her brother, `Lito,' was stabbing people.''
   Moments later, Ric Camangian arrived, clutching an abdominal
wound.
   ``I brought him inside, locked the door, and went for help,''
said Gale.
   Gale, who does not have a telephone, said he went to a shopping
center, where a gasoline station owner helped him call police. As
the two were talking, the suspect appeared.
   ``I was scared because I thought he was holding something,''
said Gale. ``But he wasn't. He approached me calmly and said,
`Maybe I'm going crazy. I stabbed somebody and I don't know what I
did. Call the police.'''
   In all, 11 relatives lived in the duplex, but they were not all
at home at the time of the attack, police said.
   Another sister, Cynthia Camangian, said, ``My sister said that
for some reason Joselito had a knife in his hand. Erlinda and
Candida tried to grab the knife. ... They thought he had an enemy
outside. And then just after that, he started stabbing.''
   Some victims had defensive wounds on their hands, and there were
signs of a ``substantial struggle'' in the house, Kolstad said.
Outside, blood was smeared around the doors of the duplex and the
pavement around it.
   Gale said he had seen Camangian that day and saw nothing strange
in his behavior.
   Candida Camangian was listed in serious condition at Santa Clara
Valley Medical Center with a chest wound, according to nursing
supervisor Carrie Wickwire.
   In addition to Ric Camangian, 29; police identified the victims
as his sisters Emerenciana Camangian, 26, and Erlinda Camangian,
30; and a niece of the siblings, Laraina Rodrigues, 15, who was
visiting from Atlanta.
</TEXT>
