<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bartok     07-01 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bartok,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Composer's Remains Arrive In France On Journey Home For Burial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHERBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A memorial concert for Bela Bartok was
held at the harbor terminal in this Normandy port city following
the arrival Friday of the composer's remains en route to reburial
in his native Hungary.
   The concert, attended by Bartok's sons, Bela Jr. and Peter, was
part of a ceremonial procession that will take the remains by train
in a sealed wooden box through France, West Germany and Austria to
Budapest, the Hungarian capital.
   The first stop on the journey from New York, where Bartok died
in 1945, was Southampton, England. The remains arrived in Cherbourg
aboard the liner Queen Elizabeth II.
   A memorial concert is planned Sunday in Munich, followed by a
lying-in-state Monday in Vienna and a ceremonial state burial in
Budapest on Thursday.
   Bartok, born in 1881, left Hungary in 1940 in disgust at the
Hungarian government's close ties with Nazi Germany, and lived his
last five years in self-imposed exile in the United States.
   ``We have no doubt that he belongs to Hungary,'' Peter Bartok,
64, of Homosassa, Fla., said in Southampton.
   ``It was difficult for a long time for us to accept that his
grave should be disturbed, but finally we knew if we did not, the
opportunity to go home with father won't always exist, and the
thought of not going with him we could not accept.''
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, in a program tribute
for a concert in Bartok's honor Thursday night at Southampton
University, described him as ``one of the great musical figures
this century.''
</TEXT>
