<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary     07-01 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tensions Heightened In Hungary-Romania Conflict</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament accused Romania on Friday of
violating human rights and urged its Eastern European neighbor to
reconsider a plan to resettle ethnic Hungarians.
   Newspapers reported that Romania began turning back Hungarian
tourists. It expelled a group of Hungarian diplomats Tuesday.
   A Parliament resolution adopted Friday said the fellow
Soviet-bloc nation had violated ``the funamental human, national
and nationalities-related rights.''
   It did not mention Romania's decision to close a Hungarian
consulate and expel its staff, or the Romanian order closing a
Hungarian cultural center in Bucharest.
   The resolution said a planned resettlement project that may
affect 7,000 Romanian villages, including many where ethnic
Hungarians live, would be ``contrary to the spirit of humanism as
well as to the concept of socialism.''
   Hungary says the plan to move residents of 7,000 villages to new
agricultural-industrial centers would destroy the culture and
traditions of Romania's ethnic Hungarian minority. Romania says it
will help villagers by providing services now found only in cities.
   Relations reached an unprecedented low this week and Hungarian
leaders appealed to Romania not to make the situation worse.
   ``We will always be cooperating partners,'' Parliament Speaker
Istvan Szueroes said when he presented the resolution on Romania.
``Unfortunately, (relations) are still further deteriorating.''
   He said Hungary was prepared to proceed with preparations for a
proposed meeting of premiers.
   Some newspapers said Hungarians trying to enter Romania were
being turned back, and at some border points only people in transit
through Romania were allowed to cross. the evening daily Esti
Hirlap, however, quoted a Hungarian border official as saying
``there is no ban'' on Hungarian travel.
   Romania's decision to close a consulate in Cluj in
Traynsylvania, where most of the 1.7 ethnic Hungarians live, came
after 50,000 people marched past the Romanian Embassy in Budapest
on Monday to protest the resettlement plan.
   In its resolution, Parliament said carrying out the program
``would ... impose new burdens on Hungarian-Romanian relations,''
the resolution said.
</TEXT>
