<DOCNO> AP880701-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 1945EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrugBust     07-01 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Bust,0607</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Largest Seizure Outside Of Florida</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HICKSVILLE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 6,000 pounds of pure
cocaine, sealed in blocks of chocolate, was seized at a Long Island
warehouse in what may be the nation's largest drug bust outside
Florida, officials announced Friday.
   The seizure, valued at $480 million, is likely to drive up the
price of coke in the New York City area this summer, some officials
said.
   Three Colombian nationals, thought to be members of a major
Colombian drug cartel, were arrested in a raid of the Toronto
Imports warehouse in Hicksville by 50 agents Thursday night, said
Robert Stutman, special agent in charge of the Drug Enforcement
Administration in New York.
   U.S. Customs inspectors stumbled on the cocaine shipment June 24
during a routine check aboard the Allison Lykes at a port in
Newark, N.J., according to Peter Baish, agent in charge of U.S.
Customs in New Jersey.
   The shipment was from Ecuador and the inspection was ``a cold
hit,'' he said, explaining that inspectors had no tip or advance
warning of the contraband.
   ``This was a picture perfect case,'' Baish said. ``The hit is
phenomenal for us.''
   He said the agents were attracted to the shipment, 1,200 cartons
marked ``industrialized cocoa powder,'' because Ecuador is a source
country for cocaine.
   They sunk a drill into one of the cardboard boxes and hit a
metal box hidden in the inner core of the hardened chocolate, said
Baish.
   Agents opened the carton and found the cocaine inside the metal
box, he said. They re-sealed it and kept a surveillance on the
shipment with the help of electronic monitoring devices, he said.
   When the shipment was picked up Thursday, narcotics agents
followed the trucks, said Art Stiffel of U.S. Customs in New York.
   The trucks were intercepted before reaching the warehouse and
undercover agents took the place of the drivers, according to
Stiffel.
   He said the drivers were not part of the scheme and were unaware
of the contents of their cargo.
   The agents and the three defendants unloaded the boxes into the
warehouse. A few hours later when the suspects began moving some
cartons out to their cars, agents made the arrests.
   Oscar Nunez, 28, of Jamaica, N.Y., Absalon Borrero, 42, of
Miami, and Jaime Caro, 48, of Anz, Colombia, were charged with
importation and distribution of cocaine and conspiracy to
distribute cocaine.
   They were ordered held without bail at their arraignment before
U.S. Magistrate A. Simon Chrein in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn.
   Stutman said the suspects are believed to be members of the
Ochoa family, of Medellin, Colombia, one of three leaders in
cocaine production and importation.
   Each box weighed about 66 pounds. Each package of cocaine within
weighed six to eight pounds and was marked with the initials of the
person who had ordered it, said Stiffel. Stutman said 779 of the
1,200 cartons contained cocaine.
   ``This is the largest seizure in the U.S. outside of Florida,''
said Stutman. ``And there are only two seizures in Florida that are
greater.''
   Stutman declined to comment on whether Toronto Imports was
connected to the scheme. He said more arrests are expected in the
case.
   Authorities believe that agents have been successful in plugging
up ports in Florida which is putting pressure on smugglers to seek
other areas, such as the Northeast, as ports of entry.
   Stiffel estimated that the cost of cocaine around New York City
will increase by $4,000 a kilogram because of the seizure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
