<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 1826EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-01 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>July Chill And Snow In Northeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Unseasonably cool air washed over the northeastern quarter of
the nation Friday and rain was widely scattered over the Plains,
New England and the South.
   Low temperature records were posted from New England into North
Carolina and around the Great Lakes. Elkins, W.Va., had a low of
just 32 degrees.
   Five inches of snow fell overnmight at the top of Mount
Washington in New Hampshire, and the noon temperature was in the
30s at the top of Mount Mansfield, N.H.
   Also about noon, there were thundershowers over southern New
Hampshire, at Nashua, Derry and Manchester.
   Afternoon showers and thunderstorms extended from southern Maine
across central New England and eastern New York state.
   Showers and thunderstorms also extended from Florida across
southern and western Alabama, northern and eastern Mississippi,
northern Arkansas, Missouri, southwestern Iowa, eastern Nebraska,
eastern South Dakota and southeastern North Dakota.
   Panama City, Fla., got 1.14 inches of rain in the six hours up
to 2 p.m. EDT.
   Showers with occasional thunder and lightning were scattered
over the Texas Panhandle into southeastern New Mexico.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 52
degrees at Montpelier, Vt., to 107 at Needles, Calif. The low for
the day was 31 degrees at West Yellowstone, Mont.
   For Saturday, scattered showers were forecast over northern
Maine. Showers and thunderstorms were forecast over Florida,
Alabama, northern Mississippi, Arkansas, southern Missouri,
Oklahoma and northwestern Texas.
   Highs in the 60s and 70s were predicted from New England across
the Virginia coast, over the northern half of the Appalachians and
the Great Lakes, and over the northern Pacific Coast; in the 90s
from the central Gulf of Mexico states across the lower Mississippi
Valley, much of Texas, the Rockies, and the Great Basin of Nevada
and western Utah; from 100 to 115 through the desert Southwest and
inland valleys of eastern California; and generally in the 80s over
the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
