<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Iran-Contra     07-01 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran-Contra Prosecution Says North Doesn't Need More Secret
Documents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran-Contra prosecutors on Friday urged a
judge to reject fired White House aide Oliver L. North's renewed
attempts to obtain secret documents concerning other covert
operations he participated in or that came to his attention.
   Independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh claimed in court papers
that North's latest request shows he wants ``to embark on a fishing
expedition into the nation's most sensitive classified materials.''
   He accused North of trying to ``convert the discovery rules into
a vehicle for rummaging through files that are irrelevant to the
charges in the indictment, thereby delaying the trial of this
matter.''
   North is awaiting trial on charges he conspired with President
Reagan's former national security adviser, John M. Poindexter, and
two arms dealers to divert U.S.-Iran arms sale profits to the
Nicaraguan rebels.
   His lawyers recently asked U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell
to reconsider his refusal to force the government to produce
classified documents about other covert operations that he knew
about or participated in while a National Security Council aide.
   North is requesting documents about covert operations that used
``commercial cutouts, foreign bank accounts, or other methods or
techniques similar to those allegedly used in connection with the
Iranian initiative or in connection with the support for the
Nicaraguan resistance.''
   Material sought includes documents about covert operations
undertaken ``without an express, written presidential finding''
authorizing the activity.
   Walsh contended that none of the materials is relevant to any
defense North might offer that he acted with authority of higher
government officials.
   No date has been set for North's trial.
   Gesell has also ordered separate trials for Poindexter and arms
dealers Albert Hakim and retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard V.
Secord.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
