<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iraq-Chemical     07-01 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iraq-Chemical,0580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Admits Using Chemical Weapons Against Iran</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iraqi official acknowleged Friday
that his country used deadly chemical weapons in its 7{-year-old
war with Iran but claimed the Iranians had used them first.
   The comments by Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz appeared to be the
first direct admission that Iraq has used chemical weapons, which
are outlawed by international agreement.
   But Aziz defended his country's use of chemical weapons, saying
Iran was a ``great threat'' to Iraq.
   ``When we want peace, we have to respect all conventions. But
you cannot say I'm going to respect all these conventions and give
the other side the liberty not to respect them,'' Aziz told
reporters in Bonn.
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley
declined to comment on the acknowlegment by Aziz, except to repeat
that the United States had condemned the use of chemical weapons in
the Iran-Iraq war, which began in September 1980.
   A U.N. team arrived Friday in Tehran to investigate accusations
that Iraq used chemical weapons in a recent attack on Iran,
according to Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency.
   The IRNA report said Iraqi chemical weapons killed 60 people and
injured 4,000 in a June attack on the western Iranian city of
Ahwaz. Only 100 of the injured were hospitalized and 10 of those
were in critical condition, said the report, monitored in Nicosia.
   On April 25, U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar said
there was evidence that both countries were using chemical weapons
in their war.
   The U.N. chief had sent a physician from Geneva to visit Iran
and Iraq and examine victims of alleged chemical attacks. On May 9,
the U.N. Security Council condemned the use of chemical weapons in
the Iran-Iraq war.
   ``The U.N. report says both sides have used them (chemical
weapons),'' Aziz said. ``Iran started its use. We were victims many
times, since the early beginning of the conflict.''
   Asked if it was true both sides had used such weapons during the
conflict, Aziz replied: ``Both sides.''
   Iran also claims Iraq killed 5,000 people, mostly Iraqi Kurds,
in a mustard gas and cyanide attack on the Iranian-held Halabja
territory of Iraq last March.
   Iraq did not deny the charge then and said it would use all
necessary means to repel Iranian forces. It also accused Iran of
using chemical weapons.
   Iran denies that its forces have used such weapons.
   Aziz also accused Iran of violating international accords on the
treatment of prisoners.
   ``Lately 7,000 Iraqi prisoners of war disappeared. We don't yet
know what their destiny is,'' said Aziz.
   Aziz repeated assertions that Iran started the war by invading
Iraq and that his country had the right to choose the means for its
defense.
   But the Tehran government blames Iraq for starting the war,
pointing out that Iraq bombed Iranian airfields in September 1980
and saying Iran's military responded to that attack.
   Aziz also said that Iraq's recent war successes do not mean that
his country has changed its position of wanting to find a peaceful
solution to the conflict.
   ``We hope they (Iran) will draw the correct conclusions from the
present situation _ that the path to war leads ... only to
continued killing and destruction,'' he said. ``But the question
still remains whether they will reach that reasonable conclusion.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
