<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HelsinkiConference     07-01 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Helsinki Conference,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Delegate Urges Approval of Compromise Draft</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union, West Germany and France
on Friday praised a compromise proposal at the stalled 35-nation
conference on European security.
   Speaking at a plenary meeting, Soviet chief delegate Yuri
Kashlev indirectly criticized Romania, an East-bloc ally.
   He said the question facing the conference is whether it can
overcome a ``game of extremist counter-amendments'' that could sink
the compromise package worked out by nine neutral and nonaligned
countries last month.
   The Conference on Security and Cooperation in Europe began in
November 1986. It is being attended by all signatories to the 1975
Helsinki conference including the United States, Canada and all
European states except Albania.
   Romanian delegate Dumitru Aninoiu reportedly rejected at an
earlier meeting most of the human rights provisions in the
compromise plan, saying the nations that drafted the proposal had
bowed to Western demands.
   Kashlev, referring to the Romanian position, said Friday the
question ``now is whether we will be able to adopt a final document
representing a new word in the (conference), particularly in the
military and humanitarian fields, or whether we will fail to do so
because some states are playing a game of extremist
counter-amendments in an attempt to ignore the legitimate,
reasonable and minimalistic positions of other delegations.''
   His unusual criticism of a Soviet-bloc member came as West
German and French foreign ministers Friday joined other delegates
in praising the compromise plan designed to end the deadlocked
conference.
   ``The overall draft ... is a forward looking document that
offers a basis for consensus and thus to our concluding efforts,''
West German Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher told the
conference. ``We must not lose any more time.''
   Foreign Minister Roland Dumas of France said the proposal, which
also calls for the convening of a human rights conference, ``is not
only the base the 35 nations can work on, but also the balancing
point'' that could lead to a final agreement.
   Neither Genscher nor Dumas indicated when they thought the
conference might end.
   Among the remaining obstacles are Romania's opposition to the
compromise and NATO and Soviet-bloc differences on whether to keep
tactical nuclear weapons off the agenda, as the West insists.
   A final document must receive the approval of all 35 nations.
   Genscher, referring to Romania, said the principle of consensus
``does not imply that a state can cling to proposals for which,
during the long negotiations, it has been unable to gain the
support of any other participating state.''
   Dumas told reporters he planned to confer with Romanian
delegates in search of a solution. ``I can't say that the Romanian
attitude will block the conference,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
