<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CaptiveWomen 1stLd-Writethru a0734 07-01 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Captive Women, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0734,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heidnik Found Guilty In Captive Women Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout; UPDATES with detail, quotes; no pickup; note
contents may be offensive to some readers.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury Friday convicted Gary Heidnik of
murdering two of six women he abducted and kept shackled in his
basement torture chamber.
   The case focused on whether Heidnik knew right from wrong when
he raped and killed women he lured to his North Philadelphia home.
The defense argued he is schizophrenic and not responsible for his
actions.
   Heidnik, 44, was convicted of first-degree murder, kidnapping,
rape, aggravated assault and involuntary deviate sexual
intercourse. He was acquitted of one count of the latter charge.
   Judge Lynne Abraham set Saturday morning for the start of a
penalty hearing. Prosecutors have said they would seek the death
penalty.
   Jurors, chosen in Pittsburgh because of pretrial publicity here,
began deliberating Wednesday afternoon, and issued their verdict at
3:30 p.m. Friday. ``Thank God it was guilty of first-degree,'' said
Teresa Lomax, sister of Sandra Lindsay, one of the women who died
in Heidnik's house and who according to testimony had been sawed
apart, some of her remains fed to other captives.
   ``Thank God that the jury listened to the case,'' she said. ``He
deserved, `Guilty, guilty, guilty.' Now I'm hoping for the death
penalty. That was a brutal way for my sister to die, tortured.
Nobody deserves to die like that.''
   Another victim's sister, Diane Dudley, whose sister Debbie was
electrocuted when Heidnik touched live wires to her chains while
she stood in a water-filled pit, said, ``I feel good. He got what
he deserved.''
   ``Now I hope he gets the chair and Debbie can rest in peace,''
Ms. Dudley said.
   Defense attorney A. Charles Peruto Jr. called the verdict ``a
big letdown.'' He said Heidnik spoke to him after the verdict but
declined to reveal the conversation.
   ``Whatever he said, he had no emotion,'' Peruto said.
   Assistant District Attorney Charles Gallagher said, ``The jury
did an excellent job.
   ``It is a difficult task for a jury to perform, that is, to sit
in judgment upon one's peer. This case presented very difficult and
complicated legal issues, all of which the jury pondered for quite
a bit of time and came to a just decision.''
   During the polling of the jury, the 44-year-old Heidnik stared
straight ahead, showing no emotion.
   The sole innocent verdict came in a charge involving Josefina
Rivera, a prostitute Heidnik seized in November 1986.
   It was Ms. Rivera who eventually escaped and brought police to
Heidnik's so-called ``House of Horrors,'' where he had imprisoned
the women.
   Peruto had argued Heidnik was insane, a ``fruitcake'' who
suffered from schizophrenia first diagnosed in 1963, for which he
was discharged from the Army.
   ``This man conducted repeated sadistic acts on six defenseless
persons,'' Gallagher argued. ``What he did was premeditated,
deliberate murder. He knew what he was doing and he knew it was
wrong.''
</TEXT>
