<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 2327EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Netherlands-Kidnap     07-01 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Netherlands-Kidnap,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Life Sentence Sought For Kidnap Suspect</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAARLEM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecution sought a life
sentence Friday for a man charged with kidnapping Dutch supermarket
tycoon Gerrit-Jan Heijn, killing him and collecting $4 million in
ransom.
   Prosecutor Onno van der Veen made the demand after a day of
testimony in the trial of Ferdi Elsas, a 45-year-old unemployed
business consultant.
   Elsas is charged with abducting and killing Heijn, vice
president of the Ahold concern, the Netherlands biggest supermarket
chain.
   Ahold also owns the Giant Food and Bi-Lo supermarkets in the
United States.
   Van der Veen said Elsas ``killed a man in cold blood ...
according to a well-devised plan.'' Elsas has said he picked his
victim at random and planned the kidnapping for months.
   Heijn's family paid $4 million in cash and diamonds for his
release, but Elsas told the court Friday he had shot and killed the
56-year-old kidnap victim with a 9mm pistol near Heijn's makeshift
grave the day he was abducted.
   ``It was money and diamonds that motivated Elsas, and everything
else was subordinated to that,'' van der Veen said.
   The court said it would rule July 13.
   Under the Dutch penal system, a life sentence means 20 years'
imprisonment. A prisoner may be released for good behavior after
serving two-thirds of his term.
   Heijn disappeared Sept. 9 after leaving his home to go to a
dental appointment. His body was exhumed April 4 in a forest near
Renkum in the eastern Netherlands.
   Elsas gave the court on Friday a description of Heijn's final
hours:
   ``The two of us sat in the sun for a while and drank some orange
juice. He (Heijn) had never suspected what was going to happen to
him,'' Elsas said.
   Hank Heijn, the victim's widow, and three of their children
attended the trial.
   In October, when Heijn's kin demanded some sign he was alive,
they received his little finger. Elsas told police he cut the
finger off after he killed the grocery baron.
   At the end of the eight-hour trial, Elsas, reading from a
prepared statement, said: ``Words cannot compensate the loathsome
crimes I have committed and the immeasurable grief I have caused to
the Heijn family.
   ``I want to say that I am sorry. I now live in a nightmare from
which I shall never awake.''
   A forensic psychiatrist told the court Elsas was not fully
responsible for his deeds at the time of the abduction.
   If the court accepts that finding, it could impose a limited
jail sentence followed by open-ended confinement to an institution
for the criminally insane.
   Police arrested Elsas in a raid on his home in a small Amsterdam
suburb after a huge search.
   Elsas' arrest followed discovery of a 250-guilder note from the
ransom payment in January by a bank employee in the Dutch capital.
   The note was traced back to a supermarket where the suspect did
his shopping. Police recovered nearly all the ransom.
</TEXT>
