<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ethiopia-CivilWar     07-01 0178</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethiopia-Civil War,0183</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethiopia Says it Captured Two More Towns from Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethiopia said Friday its forces
have recaptured two more towns from rebels in northern Tigre
province, leaving only one key center in guerrilla hands.
   State radio said the 3rd Revolutionary Army drove guerrillas of
the Tigrean People's Liberation Front from Axum and Adwa, about 70
miles northwest of the Tigrean capital of Mekelle, in an ongoing
counteroffensive this week.
   Rebels seized all the main towns in the province except Mekelle
in February and March.
   In the previous 10 days, the Marxist government led by Mengistu
Haile Mariam has reported recapturing all key centers except
Inda-Selassie, about 40 miles west of Axum.
   State radio reports suggested the guerrillas were driven into
the barren mountains of western Tigre.
   There was no way to verify independently government or rebel
communiques about insurgencies which have raged for 14 years in
Tigre and 27 years in neighboring Eritrea province.
   Eritrean guerrillas are fighting for control of the province.
Tigreans demand more autonomy for their area.
</TEXT>
