<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Angola-Bomb     07-01 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola-Bomb,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blast At Angolan Airline Office Injures 10</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded outside the Angolan
national airline in the capital city of Luanda, injuring 10 people,
the official Angolan news agency ANGOP said Friday.
   The blast on Thursday damaged the front of the building that
houses the airline TAAG, the agency said in a report monitored in
Lisbon.
   ANGOP blamed unidentified ``enemies of the Angolan people'' for
what it said what a terrorist action aimed at civilians. ANGOP said
10 people were hurt, but gave no particulars.
   Also Friday, the Angolan rebel movement UNITA said it killed 82
soldiers, including three Cubans, in five attacks in four provinces
Tuesday and Thursday.
   It listed rebel casualties as one killed and 24 wounded.
   UNITA, standing for the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola, said in a statement distributed in Lisbon
its actions included a commando raid Wednesday night on workshops
at the railroad station in the central city of Huambo.
   The rebels said they killed 22 soldiers and destroyed machinery,
warehouses and offices at the station on the Benguela Railroad, the
main route for transporting minerals from Zambia, Zaire, and
eastern Angola to the Atlantic port of Lobito.
   UNITA, supported by the United States and South Africa, has been
fighting since 1975 to force the Marxist government of Angola to
share power.
   The Soviet Union and Cuba support the government.
   The southern African nation is a former Portuguese colony.
</TEXT>
