<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Shultz 2ndLd-Writethru a0769 07-01 0744</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0769,0765</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Secretary of State Winds Up Central American Tour</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 13th pvs bgng, Shultz met with... to
insert Arias comment. PICK up 14th pvs, The idea of...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz
ended a visit to Central America Friday and leaders of Nicaraguan
guerrillas said they discussed with him ways to win congressional
approval for aid to the rebels.
   Alfredo Cesar, a leader of the rebels known as Contras, met with
Shultz on Thursday and later said the package discussed could
include direct U.S. aid to the leftist Sandinista government if it
fulfills promised democratic reforms.
   The United States cut all aid to the Nicaraguan government in
1981.
   Shultz spent six hours in San Jose after a flight from
Guatemala, where another rebel leader, Adolfo Calero, said there
was discussion on a $30 million aid package for the insurgents.
   Calero said there have been informal talks about the possibility
of setting aside $7 million and releasing it as military aid the
Sandinistas do not meet promises for greater democracy.
   All sides agreed that no decisions have been made on a Contra
aid package. The Reagan administration has said only that Congress
will be asked to approve an unspecified amount of additional
assistance.
   The rebels have received no military aid since Feb. 29. Congress
approved a $17 million humanitarian aid package in late March after
the rebels and the Sandinistas agreed on a temporary truce.
   Calero said Shultz responded positively to the idea of a new aid
package in which a portion would be earmarked for military
assistance and placed in an escrow account.
   ``There is no doubt in my mind that he's very enthusiastic about
it, very enthusiastic,'' Calero said.
   Reagan administration officials accompanying Shultz seemed
annoyed that the Contra aid issue was deflecting attention from
Shultz's principal message during his three-day tour of Costa Rica,
El Salvador, Honduras and Guatemala: that the region's democratic
countries are progressing while Nicaragua is lagging far behind.
   At an airport arrival ceremony in San Jose attended by hundreds
of flag-waving school children, Shultz said there has been a
two-thirds decline in living standards in Nicaragua over the past
four months.
   But Shultz did not mention a new aid package for the Contras.
   Shultz met with Costa Rican President Oscar Arias and then told
reporters at a news conference only that the administration is
``seeking obviously to support those who stand up and are ready to
struggle'' against the Sandinistas.
   Arias said Shultz had proposed a meeting with the foreign
ministers of the four countries he visited to be held before a
scheduled Central American summit that would include Nicaragua in
early August.
   Arias, who won last year's Nobel Peace Prize for his regional
peace plan, said the Shultz suggestion specifically excluded
Nicaragua from the proposed foreign ministers meeting.
   He also said he told Shultz that talks between the Sandinistas
and Contras have not failed yet and suggested neither side has put
its final bargaining position on the table. Arias said he hoped the
two sides would agree to meet this month.
   The idea of approving military aid and placing it in an escrow
account has been discussed in recent weeks by pro-Contra lawmakers
in Washington.
   Calero said he expects legislation to be introduced soon in the
Senate, with the campaign spearheaded by Democratic Sens. David
Boren of Oklahoma and Ernest Hollings of South Carolina.
   Joining them is Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., Calero said.
   According to Calero, the aid package would be for the six-month
period between October 1988 and March 1989.
   The most innovative aspect of the aid proposal is the pledge to
provide economic aid to the Sandinistas if they meet Contra demands
for democratization.
   Cesar, meeting with reporters Thursday, called the package a
``carrot and stick'' approach, noting that Sandinista
non-compliance with promised reformed would trigger military aid
for the Contras.
   The Carter administration sought to woo the Sandinistas with
economic aid after the triumph of the revolution in July 1979.
About $120 million was spent, but the Reagan administration
suspended the program in April 1981, citing alleged Sandinista
efforts to export their revolution.
   Shultz said Friday that the Sandinistas are continuing to
subvert their neighbors.
   ``I want to make it absolutely clear that the United States will
not tolerate the subversion or destabilization of the democratic
governments of Central America,'' Shultz said.
</TEXT>
