<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ToxicTanker     07-01 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Toxic Tanker,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salvagers Work on Sunken Tanker With Poisonous Cargo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salvage workers on Friday sawed in
two the wreck of a sunken tanker loaded with a deadly chemical as a
preliminary to raising the hulk, Dutch television reported.
   None of the Dutch-flagged Anna Broere's cargo of 1,600 tons of
highly toxic acrylonitrile leaked from its tanks during the
hourlong operation, the TV report said.
   Salvage crews fled on Thursday when an acrylonitrile tank sprang
a leak during efforts to lift the ship, but no injuries were
reported.
   The chemical, a highly carcinogenic and inflammable agent, is
used by the plastics industry.
   Workers on Friday used a 16-ton chain to separate the ship's aft
section, which contains the engine room, from the fore part, where
the tanks are, the report said. It said this was done to facilitate
hoisting the wreck to the surface later.
   The sawing operation marked the latest episode in efforts to
salvage the ship and its hazardous cargo after the Anna Broere
collided with a freighter 40 miles off the Netherlands on May 27.
   The 180-foot fore section and the 60-foot aft section are
expected to be raised over the weekend, the report said.
   A first attempt to salvage the Anna Broere failed last month
when two of the four steel cables holding the vessel broke.
   A coast guard official said water samples taken Thursday showed
a sudden increase in the levels of acrylonitrile in the water at
the site, and divers quickly boarded small boats kept nearby for
emergencies.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said that at
about 9.30 p.m. Thursday, the levels rose to more than seven times
the amount considered safe by the Dutch Environment Ministry.
</TEXT>
