<1ST_LINE>u i AM-BerlinShowdown 1stLd-Writethru a0787 07-01 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Berlin Showdown, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0787,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Move On Squatters, Communist Guards Help Them Over Wall</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede to UPDATE number of protesters to 220. PICK up 2nd
graf pvs bgng, Most of ...; SUBS 7th pvs, One smiling ... with 1
graf to add color. PICK up 8th pvs, the protesters. ADDS 4 grafs at
bottom with details.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 220 West German environmentalists scampered
over a 13-foot-high section of the Berlin Wall into Communist
territory Friday to dodge police trying to clear them away from a
disputed spot near the wall.
   Most of them returned to West Berlin later in the day. Police
said nine protesters were arrested, but eight were released later.
   Authorities issued a removal order Friday after a 5-week
struggle that pitted environmentalists against city developers. The
demonstrators were protesting plans to build a highway through a
nearby park.
   When more than 900 West Berlin police moved in to chase away the
squatters, the protesters were already perched on the wall.
   They had earlier declared they would seek ``political asylum''
in East Berlin if West German police tried to remove them.
   East German border guards helped the protesters over the
communist-built barrier, which splits Berlin into Allied and
communist sectors. Some guards backed trucks up to the eastern side
of the wall to make it easier for the environmentalists to jump
down and escape West Berlin police.
   One smiling East German guard helped one protester by pulling
his bicycle over the wall. Others greeted cheering protesters with
coffee, warm sausages and cigarettes.
   The protesters were occupying a 10-acre piece of land which
formally came under West Berlin's control at one minute after
Thursday midnight. Before then, police could not legally enter the
area.
   The property was handed over under a deal worked out with East
Berlin this year.
   The protesters began occupying the land May 26. They set up a
shantytown and put up barriers to protect themselves from police.
   The area became the scene of frequent violent skirmishes between
police and demonstrators. Protesters often attacked police with
bottles, stones and gasoline bombs. Officers responded with tear
gas and water cannons.
   West Berlin officials have repeatedly asked protesters to leave
the area, saying it could contain live ammunition from World War
II. The area, not far from where Nazi leader Adolf Hitler's bunker
was located, was the scene of fierce battles in the final days of
World War II.
   Officials have said plans for the proposed highway are not yet
finalized and have charged that many of the protesters are intent
only on provoking violence with authorities.
   East Germany's state-run newspaper Neues Deutschland last week
reported West Berlin police were using ``terror tactics'' against
the protesters, indicating offical Communist approval of the
environmentalists' actions.
</TEXT>
