<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 2052EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CriminalLibel     07-01 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Criminal Libel,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Criminal Libel Charges Against Editor Dropped</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor dropped criminal libel
charges against a weekly newspaper editor Friday at the request of
two legislators who said the case was causing the poor, rural area
too much adverse publicity.
   State Rep. B.J. Gordon and state Sen. Frank McGill, whom editor
Jim Fitts accused of unspecified corruption and stealing, delivered
letters to Solicitor Wade Kolb on Friday asking him to drop the
charges.
   ``I see no useful purpose in furthering the prosecution of Jim
Fitts,'' McGill said in his letter. ``I realize that vengeance is
not mine but God's,''
   Gordon, a Baptist minister, wrote, ``God in his own time will
rectify all situations.''
   Kolb, who agreed to drop the rarely used counts of criminal
libel, said of Gordon and McGill: ``Even though both felt seriously
harmed, they didn't want to harm (Williamsburg) County. ... They
were distressed by the negative publicity that has made the county
look bad.''
   Fitts, the 62-year-old editor of a small weekly newspaper, The
Voice, was indicted by a grand jury Monday and faced a possible
sentence of a year in jail if he was convicted. He was not
immediately available for comment on Friday's action, a newspaper
employee said.
   Wallace Connor, the attorney for the lawmakers, said: ``Nobody
ever thought this would reach the proportions that it did. I've
never in my 40 years of practice here seen anything that got such
national attention.''
   The case set off a legal battle involving First Amendment rights
that caught the attention of journalists across the United States.
It was only the fourth criminal libel suit involving journalists in
South Carolina in 40 years and the first in the nation since 1984.
   In his column of May 17, Fitts, who is black, wrote, in part:
``I will say to you, without fear of contradiction, if every black
in Williamsburg County would start stealing today and steal every
day for the rest of their lives, they could not steal as much as
those two have stolen during their time in power.'' He did not
elaborate.
   Gordon, who is black, and McGill, who is white, signed warrants
against Fitts shortly after reading the column.
   The two politicians have denied Fitts' charges.
   But The State newspaper reported Friday that an investigation
completed in February by the State Law Enforcement Division
concluded that Gordon, while chairman of a center for mentally
retarded adults that he founded in 1976, diverted state grant money
and used it for personal benefit.
   A prosecutor concluded there was not enough evidence of criminal
activity to present to a grand jury, the law enforcement division
said.
   Connor said the State story had nothing to do with Gordon's
decision to drop the libel charge. ``I didn't see that there's
anything there (in the State story) that would have justified him
(Fitts) saying what he did in the newspaper,'' Connor said.
   Kolb said Gordon and McGill told him last week that they were
going to ask him to drop the charges after the grand jury
indictment was unsealed Monday.
   Although McGill said, ``I trust that the matter will be laid to
rest,'' the American Civil Liberties Union is considering asking
permission from Fitts to ask a judge to declare the state's
criminal libel law unconstitional, state ACLU director Steve Bates
said Friday.
   ``In any event this whole affair points out the need to abolish
the criminal libel statute, because it is an invitation to
politicians to intimidate and silence their opponents in an attempt
to hide the truth,'' Bates said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
