<DOCNO> AP880701-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 2201EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Portugal-US     07-01 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Portugal-US,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Military Attache Transferred After Seized By Customs Agents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diplomatic sources said Friday that a
U.S. military attache left Portugal after customs agents detained
him and claimed he was illegally taking photographs of an Iranian
ship in the port of Setubal.
   A newspaper had reported the attache, Navy Capt. William Barney,
was expelled but that account was denied by both the U.S. Embassy
and the diplomatic sources, who spoke with condition they not be
identified.
   The sources said the Portuguese government expressed its
displeasure to the United States over the incident earlier this
year and Barney was transferred in May at the end of a three-year
tour of duty.
   A report in the weekly Independent newspaper had said Barney was
expelled and left Lisbon Wednesday. It later acknowleged it might
have erred about the date of the attache's departure.
   U.S. Embassy spokeswoman My Chau Bui-Griffin said Barney left
Portugal in early May following routine transfer orders from
Washington. She said Barney had served as naval attache in Lisbon
since March 1985. She declined comment on the Independent's story.
   According to the diplomatic sources, Barney was detained by
customs agents while photographing an Iranian ship loading arms in
Setubal, 25 miles south of Lisbon.
   Setubal is the port where arms sold by Portuguese state-owned
companies to both Iran and Iraq are loaded for shipment. Iran and
Iraq have been at war since September 1980.
   Photographing some state-owned installations is prohibited by
Portuguese law.
   The diplomatic sources did not specify when Barney allegedly was
detained, but the state-run television network RTP said the
incident occurred in the first week of April. It said the
government advised Washington not to renew Barney's posting in
Lisbon.
   The Portuguese Foreign Ministry declined comment on the reports.
   Portugal and the United States are allies in the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
