<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 2250EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sweden-Palme     07-01 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sweden-Palme,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Publisher Says Private Probe Showed Iran Ordered Premier Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CECILIA LONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A publisher who ran a private
investigation into the unsolved 1986 assassination of Prime
Minister Olof Palme said Friday he believed Palme was killed on
orders from Iran.
   Ebbe Carlsson said Iran wanted Palme eliminated because he was
ending illegal deliveries of Swedish arms to the Tehran government
and because he was appointed by the United Nations to mediate an
end to the Iran-Iraq war.
   A gunman shot and killed Palme on a Stockholm street on Feb. 28,
1986. Police have failed to establish a motive and have offered a
$8.3 million reward for the killer.
   Carlsson is employed at Bonniers, one of Sweden's main
publishing houses which publishes everything from books to weekly
magazines.
   The disclosure of Carlsson's unofficial probe created a
political storm and led to the resignation June 7 of Justice
Minister Anna Greta Lejion, who approved his secret mission and
wrote a letter of introduction to foreign intelligence agencies.
   Carlsson said he was pursuing a possible Middle East connection
to the assassination, a link that police investigated but failed to
prove.
   Critics said Carlsson's maverick operation bordered on the
illegal _ his bodyguard was caught smuggling outlawed surveillance
equipment into Sweden _ and added nothing to the official probe.
   Breaking his silence over the episode, Carlsson said on Swedish
radio: ``Iran is conducting a holy war, where they put everything
into the survival of their nation, and they did not want any
mediation or meddling.''
   He also said, ``I think that Olof Palme was murdered because
Iran felt it was more difficult to buy war material since he had
become premier (in 1982).''
   Iran and Iraq have been at war since September 1980.
   Carlsson indicated he believed Iran contracted the murder to
Kurdish extremists living in Sweden who also had a grudge against
Palme.
   Several reports during the police investigation mentioned a
small group of leftist Kurdish exiles known as the Kurdish Workers
Party as perhaps organizing the killing. The Kurds are an ethnic
group seeking a separate state in part of Iran and Iraq.
   The Palme government had classified the group as a terrorist
organization and sentenced two of its alleged members to life in
prison for the killing of two defectors from the group.
   Carlsson said police received ``a lot of tips about the behavior
of the Kurds in connection with the murder,'' and that ``my simple
contribution'' was drawing a possible link between the two theories.
   Attorney General Hans Stark said Friday he would open a
preliminary investigation against two Security Police officers who
gave Carlsson classified information on the Palme case.
   But Stark, releasing a 42-page report on the Carlsson incident,
cleared the heads of the Security Police and the national police of
irregular behavior.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880701-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 2117EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Circus 1stLd-Writethru a0702 07-01 0627</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Circus, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0702,0646</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Big Top a Big Hit in Japan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-6 UPDATE with evening performance. Picks up 5th
graf pvs, The first ... </NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES W. HATTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAPPORO, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The grownups paid $40 a ticket without a
murmur and the children proved that kids are kids the world over
when the Greatest Show on Earth made its debut in this very
unfamiliar part of the world on Friday.
   The Ringling Bros. and Barnum and Bailey Circus roused some
familiar reactions even though it was performing 5,000 miles from
home. The cavorting clowns and the dancing elephants still helped
make the Big Top a big hit.
   Ringmaster Dinny McGuire was ecstatic about the reception here
following the afternoon performance and Susannah Smith, vice
president for public relations, said the evening performance ``went
even better.''
   ``Some of the kids were dancing in the aisles,'' she said.
   ``We have been prepared for a reserved, quiet crowd. This is not
Texas,'' McGuire said after the first performance.
   ``But they clapped fervently ... I did not expect them to be as
overwhelmingly demonstrative in their response.''
   The first Ringling show ever to play in Japan opened in a huge
tent in this northern city, its first time under canvas in 32
years, won the hearts of a reserved but less-than-capacity audience
of about 4,000 people.
   After slow start, the audience warmed to the troupe and
applauded enthusiastically.
   ``I told you this during the dress rehersal, but today was the
real test because we had real people _ and they loved it,'' circus
owner Kenneth Feld told the 200 members of his troupe after the
show.
   ``You really are `the greatest show on Earth,''' Feld said.
   Feld has brought an all new version of the 118-year-old show to
Japan as an experiment.
   It will give 44 performances in Sapporo, then 96 shows in Tokyo
in August and September. Feld said the circus will go on to play in
Osaka in southern Japan in October before returning home.
   The testing of the Japanese entertainment waters comes at a time
when the Bolshoi Circus from the Soviet Union, already well-known
here, also is touring Japan.
   But Feld says the Soviets ``don't compare with us. They're very
plodding. They can't match our rhythm and tempo. That's the secret.
Tempo.''
   The Ringling tour of Japan is being promoted locally by the
Japan Educational Association, which asked Feld to bring a show as
big as the two Ringling troupes touring the United States, said
show publicist Joe Gold.
   Feld also liked the idea because Japan is a wealthy nation that
can afford hefty admission prices, Gold said. Adult tickets went
for $40, about four times the average price in the United States.
   Feld created a new ``gold unit'' with the best of the acts from
the ``blue'' and ``red'' units touring America, and world-class
acts from other countries.
   To help audiences here understand the acts, ringmaster McGuire
had to learn his introductions and explanations in Japanese. Also,
Japanese characters were put on many of the clown costumes to
identify them to the children.
   Finally, ``we brought in 120 kids last week'' for a dry run,
Gold said. ``We ... went through the clown routines to find out
what worked and what didn't.''
   Feld said the production cost $10 million, including $8 million
for the tent.
   After Friday's matinee, a smiling Mrs. Sachiko Okawara, asked
about performance, said she liked ``The performers, the animals,
the costumes, the lights _ and the band. The band was beautiful.''
   For 5-year-old Miku Kusakabo, the list of favorite items was
much shorter: ``The elephants,'' she said through an interpreter,
and nodded vigorously when asked if she wanted to come back again.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
