<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-PartyBirthday     07-01 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Party Birthday,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China's Communist Party Marks 67th Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China marked the 67th anniversary Friday of the
founding of its Communist Party by issuing a new party theoretical
journal and by cautioning the 47 million party members that their
mission is a serious one.
   ``Each member from the day he joins the party is constantly
tested,'' the party newspaper People's Daily said in a front-page
editorial. ``As times change, so do the tasks and the tests.''
   It said members' main tasks now are to uphold China's
market-style economic reforms and fight growing corruption that has
accompanied the new prosperity.
   ``There are a handful of members, including some officials ...
who instead of using their power to benefit the people and the
country abuse it for personal gains,'' the paper said. ``We must
resolutely expel (them).''
   China's Communist Party convened its first congress on July 1,
1921, at a girls' school in Shanghai's foreign quarter. When police
got word of the session, delegates fled to nearby Hangzhou and
finished their meeting in a boat on a scenic lake, posing as
holiday-makers.
   Fewer and fewer members today are interested in Marxist
ideology, as evidenced by the creation of the new, livelier party
journal.
   The old party bi-monthly, Red Flag (Hong Qi), which put out its
last issue in June, carried lengthy, jargon-laden essays on such
topics as the relationship between art and the masses and ``Basing
Planning Work On the Foundation of the Law of Value.''
   The new journal, called Seek Truth (Qiu Shi), takes its name
from senior leader Deng Xiaoping's pragmatic slogan, ``Seek truth
from facts.'' He advanced the slogan in the 1970s as a counterpoint
to Mao Tse-tung's emphasis on theory and the ideology of class
struggle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
