<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama-Invasion     07-01 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Invasion,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panama Official Says U.S. Military Intervention Is imminent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high Panamanian official accused the
United States on Friday of preparing for a military intervention of
Panama, probably over the Fourth of July holiday weekend.
   Jose Maria Cabrera, Panama's vice minister of foreign affairs,
told a news conference that evidence of ``imminent military
action'' included troop mobilization in the Canal Zone. He said his
government was convinced that President Reagan ``has decided to
pass from a policy of destabilization and economic aggression to
one of armed aggression.''
   ``We consider the threat is very serious and we feel it is
necessary to denounce it before the governments of Latin America
and the world,'' Cabrera said following a meeting of Latin American
diplomats here.
   He said ``armed action'' could take place within days, probably
over the weekend as the United States celebrates its Declaration of
Independence.
   Cabrera claimed that U.S. Secretary of State George Shultz's
mission to Central America was to gain regional support for U.S.
policy in Panama.
   The United States has tried to force out Panama's de facto
ruler, Defense Forces chief Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, since
Noriega was indicted last February on U.S. drug trafficking charges.
</TEXT>
