<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 2309EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-World-AIDS     07-01 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-World-AIDS,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Global AIDS Cases Top 100,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100,000 cases of AIDS have been reported
worldwide, with more than half of them in the United States, the
World Health Organization said Friday.
   The Geneva-based group said the United States listed 65,099 AIDS
cases, the highest national total and a 5.7 percent increase in 2{
months. The U.S. rate of 8.9 cases per 100,000 is the highest in
the industrialized world.
   WHO said 138 countries reported a total of 100,410 cases by June
30. The May 30 total stood at 96,433 cases worldwide.
   Organization officials, however, estimate there are more than
150,000 cases and that 5 million to 10 million people may carry the
HIV virus, which causes acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
   According to the WHO figures, AIDS cases were registered for the
first time in Sierra Leone, which had three cases, and the islands
of Comoros, which had one case.
   A special survey of 30 European nations said that male
homosexuals made up 56 percent of AIDS victims, followed by
intravenous drug abusers at 21 percent and heterosexuals at 7
percent.
   The breakdown varied among individual nations.
   Among AIDS victims in Britain, the share of drug abusers was
only 2 percent, while that of homosexuals was 84 percent. In Spain,
54 percent were drug abusers and 23 percent were homosexuals.
   AIDS is caused by a virus that wrecks the body's immune system,
leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer.
   It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or
syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products,
and from pregnant women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
