<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Karpov-Kasparov     07-01 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Karpov-Kasparov,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Karpov Defeats Kasparov; Kasparov's Lead Reduced To One Point</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELFORT, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anatoly Karpov defeated Garri Kasparov in
the 14th round Friday, cutting the world champion's lead in World
Chess Cup competition to one game. Kasparov resigned on his 38th
move.
   With only one round remaining, Kasparov leads with 10.5, one
point ahead of his fellow Soviet. Kasparov is assured at least a
tie for first place even if he loses his final game Sunday and
Karpov wins, since a win counts one point and a draw one-half.
   Experts said Karpov's victory demonstrated that he remains
remains a threat to Kasparov's domination of international chess.
   With Karpov playing white, the players followed a variation of
the Gruenfeld defense that occurred several times during their 1987
world title match in Seville, Spain.
   Afterward, Karpov told reporters: ``I stood better throughout
the game.'' Asked about the two games he lost to Kasparov during an
Amsterdam tournament in May, he said, ``I think this result was
more important.''
   The two Soviet players' bitter personal and professional rivalry
has stretched over a record series of matches totaling 129 games _
19 victories for Kasparov, 17 for Karpov and the rest draws.
Kasparov, 25, took the championship from Karpov, who is 12 years
older.
   The tournament at Belfort, in eastern France, is the second of
six making up the World Chess Cup, in which the world's top 24
players are competing for total prizes of $1.2 million. It is
widely regarded as the most important chess event after the world
championship.
   In the final round Sunday, Kasparov will play Andrei Sokolov of
the Soviet Union and Karpov is pitted against Boris Spassky, a
former world champion who is a native of the Soviet Union but lives
in France.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
