<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BabyHeart     07-01 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baby Heart,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World's Youngest Transplant Recipient Goes Home To Canada</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Holc is CQ</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 8-month-old boy who became the world's
youngest transplant recipient by receiving a heart three hours
after his birth headed back to his Canadian home Friday.
   Paul Holc made such good progress since the Oct. 16 transplant
that doctors at Loma Linda University Medical Center let him go
home sooner than the usual one-year wait for baby transplant
recipients, a hospital spokeswoman said.
   The blond, blue-eye child slept in his mother's arms at Los
Angeles International Airport as they waited for a 2:10 p.m. plane
to Vancouver, British Columbia.
   Nine weeks before Paul was born, doctors discovered through a
prenatal procedure that he had a hypoplastic left heart syndrome, a
fatal heart defect that made a transplant a necessity.
   Paul received a donor heart from a brain-dead Canadian girl.
   The procedure was done by Dr. Leonard Bailey, the Loma Linda
surgeon known for placing the heart of a baboon in Baby Fae in
October 1984. The girl lived 20{ days after the implant.
   Paul and his parents Gordon and Alice Holc live in a Vancouver
suburb. Once home, Paul will continue to take medication. He must
return to Loma Linda once a month until he is one year old.
</TEXT>
