<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     07-01 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Says Five Killed in Separate Attacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military and news reports said
Friday that attacks throughout the country killed a physician, two
government officials, a former political candidate and a
12-year-old bystander.
   In Angeles, 50 miles north of Manila, two men barged into the
clinic of Dr. Patricio Santiago Thursday night and shot him in
front of his wife, military reports said.
   Also Thursday in Angeles, two gunmen killed district council
member Almario Quiambao as he walked with his wife on a street, the
reports said.
   The shootings brought to 35 the number of people killed in the
past two months in the town, home to the sprawling U.S. Clark Air
Base. Most of the killings have been attributed to leftist and
right-wing extremists.
   In Mexico town, 10 miles from Angeles, communist guerrillas
aboard a truck overtook a government patrol jeep and fired on the
troops, military reports said. The soldiers fired back and killed
one rebel, the reports said, adding that a 12-year-old boy on a
bicycle nearby died in the cross fire.
   Four militiamen and a soldier were wounded, the military reports
said.
   Thursday's other slayings were in the village of Pandanon on the
central Philippine island of Negros, the Philippine News Agency
reported.
   The agency quoted a police report as saying six men shot Alfredo
Magdato, a defeated vice mayoralty candidate in nearby Murcia town.
The gunmen then turned their fire on village council member
Reynaldo Conlu and killed him, PNA said. Conlu had been nearby and
was rushing to investigate, the agency added.
   On Friday, gunmen fired on a barrack of army musicians at a
military camp, breaking windows but causing no casualties,
officials said.
   Officers at Camp Crame, headquarters of the Philippine
Constabulary in the Manila suburb of Quezon City, said the
attackers and their car vanished.
   Renegade soldiers loyal to deposed President Ferdinand Marcos
raided the band's armory June 12 and stole 24 rifles, but failed in
their bid to free comrades jailed for taking part in coup attempts
against President Corazon Aquino.
   Col. Douglas Tansiongco of the constabulary's operations center
said in a telephone interview he did not think renegades from that
incident were involved Friday.
</TEXT>
