<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Uganda-Budget     07-01 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Uganda-Budget,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Uganda Devalues Currency, Increases Domestic Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Uganda on Friday announced a devaluation
of its currency, raised prices of fuel and other consumer goods and
increased taxes in a budget designed to curb inflation.
   Finance Minister Crispus Kiyonga told the governing National
Resistance Council that the exchange rate of Ugandan shillings
would be halved from 60 to a dollar to 120.
   He said prices of petroleum products would be more than doubled
and similar increases would be imposed for other items ranging from
cigarettes and soft drinks to beer and sugar.
   But in a bid to boost agriculture, the mainstay of this East
African nation's economy, the minister announced producer-price
increases of more than 100 percent for coffee, cocoa, tea and
soybeans.
   Uganda, with a population estimated in 1985 of 15.3 million, has
a foreign debt of $1.2 billion.
   President Yoweri Museveni told the council, ``If you have a
father who dies you have to pay for the debts and loans that he had
acquired.''
   Museveni, who came to power in a coup in January 1986, has
frequently said his government inherited huge foreign debts but it
would honor them.
</TEXT>
