<DOCNO> AP880701-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 2317EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSSuit     07-01 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Suit,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS Suit Against Blood Center Settled Out of Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAFAYETTE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawsuit against a blood bank filed by
an AIDS victim who became a spokeswoman for others with the disease
has been settled out of court 1{ years after her death, an attorney
said.
   A condition of the settlement between the family of Amy Sloan
and the Central Indiana Regional Blood Center was that the amount
would not be disclosed, said attorney Charles Vaughan Sr.
   Mrs. Sloan died in January 1987 at age 25. Her husband, Steve
Sloan, said he was satisfied with the settlement, which was
announced Thursday.
   ``There have been so many emotions, ups and downs. There were
times Amy and I wondered if justice would be served,'' he said. ``I
am pleased and hope I have the opportunity to say more later on.''
   Mrs. Sloan learned she had AIDS in 1984, the same week she
realized she was pregnant. She gave birth to a healthy son in 1985.
   The lawsuit claimed she contracted acquired immune deficiency
syndrome from a blood transfusion she received in 1982 while being
treated at Home Hospital for ulcerative colitis.
   She sued the hospital, the blood center and two doctors with the
blood center in Indianapolis.
   Mrs. Sloan had discussed her disease on national television,
before state officials and in other forums, saying her goal was
``to get some help for those people who are sick. ... This is a
terrible disease, and we all need to work together to get some kind
of cure.''
   Skip Whaley, a lawyer representing the blood center, said he
could not comment on the case. Larry R. Fisher, the hospital's
lawyer, said only that the suit against the hospital was dismissed.
   Under Indiana law, plaintiffs in a malpractice suit cannot sue
for a specific amount of damages, only for just and reasonable
damages limited to $500,000, said Vaughan. He declined to elaborate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
