<DOCNO> AP880701-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 2325EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Mileage     07-01 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Mileage,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Vehicle Sets Fuel Consumption Record</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A three-wheeled, superlightweight car built by a
team of Japanese auto workers set a new world record for fuel
consumption Friday, consuming fuel at the rate of 6,409 miles per
gallon to win the annual Shell Mileage Marathon.
   The tiny car, driven by Masaki Oka, consumed fuel more
efficiently than 60 other vehicles to win the competition at the
Silverstone race track in Northamptonshire, southern England. It
was the first non-British entry to win the contest since it began
in 1978.
   The four auto workers who built the car, employees of the Honda
motorcycle firm in Suzuka, Japan, beat the previous record of 5,691
mpg set in Canada in 1986 by a team from the University of
Saskatchewan.
   A French team finished second in Friday's contest, and Britain's
Shell Research Team came in third.
   The defending Silverstone champion, a team from the mechanical
engineering department of King's College, London, was out of the
contest Friday with technical problems.
   The mostly three-wheeled vehicles drive six laps around a
2{-mile course at about 15 mph. Their fuel consumption is carefully
measured.
   The cars weigh from 300 to 400 pounds and have very thin tires
to reduce road friction. Children as young as 11 have been selected
as drivers to minimize weight.
   The Honda team, which has won three similar contests in Japan,
received a trophy and $1,810 for their victory.
</TEXT>
