tactical duties of firefighters, reflects that the firemen's deaths
are the city's first in-action.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NR3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHALE MORAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The burning roof of a car dealership
collapsed onto firefighters Friday, killing five of them in a
shower of fiery debris, authorities said.
   The fire, which destroyed the building and contents of
Hackensack Ford, apparently started shortly after 3 p.m. in the
ceiling space above the rear service section of the building, said
Fire Chief Anthony Aiellos.
   Aiellos said the roof collapsed as the firefighters inside the
building were cutting a hole in the false ceiling in order to
attack flames between the ceiling and the roof.
   ``All of a sudden the entire 60 foot square inside ceiling fell
on them,'' he said, adding that four other firefighters inside at
the time escaped injury.
   Aiellos said the men were spraying the space between the ceiling
and the roof trying to create a ``fog'' to decrease the heat of the
fire. ``They did what they were supposed to do,'' he said.
   Killed were Capt. Richard Williams, Capt. Richard Reinhogen,
firefighters William Krejsa, Leonard Radumski and Stephen Ennis,
officials said. They were the city's first firefighters killed in
the line of duty, Aiellos said.
   The fire apparently started in the ceiling above the
dealership's service area. All the dealership's employees were
evacuated without injuries, a Hackensack police spokesman said.
   The fire was under control by 6:30 p.m. All of Hackensack's 100
firefighters answered the alarm, as well as units from surrounding
towns.
   Fire investigtors were picking through the debris to try and
determine the cause of the fire, but Aiellos said the roof collapse
may make it impossible to find the exact cause.
   Witnesses said a series of explosions rocked the building
shortly after the fire began.
</TEXT>
