<2ND_LINE>AM-Mysterious Boy,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Children's Shelter Workers Bid Farewell to `Sabath'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ELP1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CIUDAD JUAREZ, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Youngsters and workers at a
children's shelter bade farewell Friday to the partially deaf boy
who was reunited with his mother this week after an eight-month
separation.
   Jose de Jesus Garcia Aguilera _ known to the world as Sabath
before Tuesday's reunion with his mother _ passed out pieces of
angel food cake to children, social workers and reporters gathered
at the going-away party at the shelter where he had been staying
since last November.
   A handwritten sign on a wall read: ``Adios Jesus (Sabath).''
   The boy, nicknamed Chuy, had started packing early for the bus
ride Friday night with his mother and aunt to his hometown of
Tampico, on the Gulf Coast about 300 miles south of Brownsville,
Texas.
   Chuy caused a stir after he was picked up Nov. 7 near downtown
Juarez because he could not convey his identity or his hometown. He
speaks only a few words and communicates mostly through gestures
and drawings.
   Because he seemed to like American food, Mexican child welfare
authorities contacted their U.S. counterparts, thinking the child
might be an American. The FBI even got involved in the effort to
identify him.
   But his family was eventually traced, and he was reunited
Tuesday with his mother, Micaela Aguilera de Garcia of Tampico. She
said the boy, one of five children, had run away while on a trip to
visit his father in Monterrey.
   Before he left Friday, Chuy ran around the playroom at the
children's shelter, eagerly handing pieces of cake to social
workers, reporters and about 20 playmates. Then he walked shyly to
his mother and thrust out a piece of cake at arm's length.
   Social worker Leticia Cota stood in a doorway, watching Chuy hug
his friends and pose for pictures. ``I'm glad to see him back with
his family, but it's sad to see him go,'' she said.
   Juan Ramon Hernandez, director general of the Juarez office of
Integrated Family Development, said welfare authorities were
considering putting Chuy into a shelter in Tampico because of the
conditions the family lived in.
   Ms. Aguilera had previously told people that she worked as a
maid. But when officials in Tampico visited the family's home this
week and interviewed neighbors, they discovered the family's living
quarters were cramped and that Ms. Aguilera worked late hours as a
waitress in a bar, Hernandez said.
   ``It's better this way,'' Hernandez said, adding that Ms.
Aguilar would be allowed to see her children if they are put in a
shelter. ``We're here to protect children, not to protect the
parents.''
</TEXT>
