<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 1157EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APArts:Mahabharata Adv08   07-01 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Mahabharata, Adv 08,0689</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, July 8 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Indian Epic Sells Out In Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONIKA JAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Silence has greeted Peter Brook's lavish nine-hour
odyssey based on the rambling Indian epic ``The Mahabharata,'' but
for the cast, the silence is golden.
   Playing to nearly packed houses in Tokyo, the last stop of a
year-long worldwide tour, Brook's adaptation of good's triumph over
evil pits two warring clans in ferocious battle to gain control of
a vast ancient Indian kingdom.
   The epic, which comprises the world's longest poem, narrates a
way of life in its dealings with feelings of hatred, love and
jealousy _ basic human emotions often hidden under a polite facade.
Audiences in New York, Copenhagen, Paris and Glasgow have responded
with awkward, embarrassed laughter.
   ``That has been true with many audiences all over the world,''
said Malika Sarabhai, the only Indian national in the performance.
``We used to get very upset in the beginning.
   ``In America, they laughed at everything,'' said Sarabhai, an
accomplished dancer-actress in India. ``Anytime when there was
something tense going on stage, they would laugh ... because they
are embarrassed. They don't like ... to be confronted with very
deep, very basic emotions.''
   In Tokyo, the silence has been louder; the Japanese audience has
laughed the least. Many Japanese, Brook said, have discovered that
``India is really the root of their culture.''
   Kenichiro Shirahama, a theater critic and author of several
books on plays, said ``The Mahabharata'' has allowed the Japanese
``to re-evaluate the meaning of life.''
   ``Japan has drawn its culture from the centuries-old traditions
of Korea, China and especially India,'' he said, ``but in their
pursuit of money, the Japanese have forgotten how to live.
   ``By watching the play, the people are reminded of the richness
of life and human nature.''
   In Tokyo for an eight-week engagement as part of the six-month
Festival of India, ``The Mahabharata'' has earned rave reviews from
the local media, and Saison Theater personnel say tickets for the
nine-hour marathon sessions were sold out well in advance before
the opening last month.
   Originally written in the ancient Indian language of Sanskrit,
the epic under Brook's direction is staged in English and lines up
a multinational cast of 50 people from over 15 different countries.
   The cast of the Centre International de Creations Theatreales
company, based in France, has already toured in Europe, the United
States and Australia.
   Ironically, India has not been part of its itinerary.
   Marie-Helene Estienne, Brook's assistant, blamed the logistics
of transporting a company of 50 plus into a nation notorious for
its red tape, but said a movie on the play, next on the director's
agenda, will open in New Delhi by September 1989.
   Doordarshan, India's government-run TV network, will sponsor the
play's move to celluloid and will also cast the same group of
actors, with one notable difference: The play will be cut to six
hours, ``the shortest length of time in which the story can be
told,'' Brook said. Doordarshan, he added, initially wanted only
two hours.
   The epic is played out an a stage packed with dry earth,
complete with a pond in the front and a rippling stream in the
back. Outdoor and indoor scenes within acts are signaled by
changing floor mats, brought out by the actors themselves doubling
as stagehands.
   The story is about two groups of cousins, the Kauravas and the
Pandavas, who fight over control of an ancient Indian kingdom. The
climax of the story is an 18-day battle, in which the Pandavas,
representing good, are victorious.
   Around this core are woven thousands of subplots, which nearly
fill an entire encyclopedia of 18 books.
   ``The play is very true to `The Mahabharata,' very true to the
spirit,'' Sarabhai said. ``Had I not been proud of the production
both as an Indian and as a woman, I don't think I would have stayed
party to it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, July 8</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880701-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 1147EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Brazil-Forest Adv07   07-01 0785</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brazil-Forest, Adv 07,0805</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thu PMs, July 7, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Efforts Under Way to Save Brazil's Coastal Forest</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY BRUCE HANDLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmentalists are mobilizing
to save what's left of Brazil's once-vast Atlantic forest, the
nation's picture-postcard front door.
   One of the species of trees near extinction is the brazilwood,
or pau-Brazil, which gave the country its name.
   When Portuguese explorers discovered Brazil in 1500, the
Atlantic forest covered some 170,000 square miles along a
3,000-mile coastal strip.
   Today, with 80 million of the country's 143 million people and
most of its heavy industry crowded into the coastal zone, only
about 3 percent of the original primary forest remains _ in
scattered patches.
   Some of the forest's rare monkeys, birds and trees, many found
nowhere else in the world, face extinction.
   ``We are in the process of destroying an entire ecosystem. But
there's still time to save what's left and prevent total tragedy,''
said Rodrigo Lara Mesquita, the chairman of a group called the
S.O.S. Atlantic Forest Foundation.
   The foundation has strong economic and political influence.
   Mesquita is an heir of the family that for a century has
controlled the influential O Estado de S. Paulo newspaper and media
group. Others running S.O.S. include two multimillionaire
industrialists, the president of the country's largest university
and a retired admiral.
   Since 1986, the foundation has raised the equivalent of more
than $4 million for nationwide newspaper and television publicity.
It intends to collect more, for the satellite mapping of the forest
zone and for actual conservation programs where the remaining
forest is thickest.
   ``This group is powerful and well organized,'' said Russell A.
Mittermeier, international vice chairman of the Washington-based
World Wildlife Fund and a consultant to the Atlantic Forest
organization. ``It's not radical, as unfortunately was the case
with many well meaning but ineffective environmental groups that
sprang up in the United States in the 1960s. I'm very optimistic.''
   Mittermeier has been coming to Brazil since 1971, principally to
work with Atlantic forest's endangered monkey species.
   He said in an interview in Rio de Janeiro that Brazil probably
has the best chance for success of the ``three highest-priority
ecological problems in the world'' _ the tropical South American
Andes in Colombia, Ecuador and Peru; the African island of
Madagascar, and the Atlantic forest.
   ``Here in the Atlantic forest it really is possible to save the
remnants,'' Mittermeier said. He mentioned specifically the
muriqui, South America's largest primate, of which fewer than 100
remain; the Golden Lion Tamarin, another endangered monkey, with
about 400 left; the increasingly scarce red-tailed parrot; the rare
and valuable jacaranda tree, and the almost extinct pau-Brazil.
   ``Today, with few exceptions, the only place you can still see
pau-Brasil is in a botanical garden,'' lamented Mesquita.
   Early Portuguese pioneers chopped down all the brazilwood they
could find to extract dye. Later settlers hacked away the coastal
forest to make way for sugar-cane and coffee plantations and for
settlements.
   The S.O.S. Atlantic Forest Foundation's logotype is a stylized
green-yellow-and-blue Brazilian flag, but with part of the green
ripped away.
   A foundation poster shows a map of Brazil with an outline of the
Atlantic Forest as it existed in 1500, with the words, in
Portuguese, ``I Used to be Like This.'' Then there is a map showing
the scattered forest pockets left today and the words, ``I Wound Up
Like This.''
   The foundation's first specific project is to be in a
still-relatively untouched forest zone covering 3,500 square miles
along the coasts of the southeastern states of Sao Paulo and
Parana. It intends to set up two ecological bases and buy a
patrol-type boat to sound the alarm against illegal tree cutting
and the banned netting of coastal fish, shrimp and oysters.
   ``Invasion of that region has long gone unpunished,'' S.O.S.
Chairman Mesquita said. ``But we think we can stop it. We're
organized, we've got money, and we have access to the authorities
and the media.''
   The foundation also supported lobby efforts in Brazil's Congress
to place in the draft of a new constitution the legal concept of
``ecological crime.''
   ``We're also attempting a process of environmental education,''
said Ibsen de Gusmao Camara, the former admiral who now is a member
of the S.O.S board. ``A lot of Brazilians think development
automatically means physical occupation. It's not that they
purposely want to destroy the environment. They just don't know any
better.''
   ``We'll never see the Atlantic forest again as it once was,'' he
added. ``That's impossible. But we will put a stop to the
destruction and preserve and build up the forest's `genetic
library'.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu PMs, July 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880701-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 1124EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-Elderly Adv04   07-01 0856</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Elderly, Adv 04,0881</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs, July 4, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>PBS Documentaries Reveal Non-Stereotypical Elderly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two public television documentaries this week
give names and faces and unique stories to a part of the population
that is often faceless, especially on TV _ the elderly.
   One of the films is an uplifting fairytale romance, the Academy
Award-winning short documentary ``Young at Heart,'' airing
Wednesday.
   The other is a realistic profile of six elderly women. ``Acting
Our Age'' is half of the two-hour premiere installment Tuesday
night of ``P.O.V.,'' standing for ``point of view,'' a new
documentary series on PBS.
   The film is by Michal Aviad, an Israeli filmmaker who decided to
examine the effects of aging, both physically and psychologically,
on a half-dozen thoughtful and intelligent women coping with
different lifestyles _ married, divorced and widowed, some lonely,
some not.
   ``There's nobody that's young that's not going to get old,
unless they die,'' says Enola Maxwell, 66, one of the women Ms.
Aviad profiles.
   Ms. Aviad allows her subjects to speak for themselves; as a
result they are portrayed sympathetically but realistically.
   Mrs. Maxwell is surrounded by an extended family, but Irja
Friend, 74, is struggling with loneliness. ``The older I get, the
fewer chances I have, and the ones that I had I rejected. It's
painful not to be wanted, and I found that you just simply have to
do without. No one wants you for a spouse or a mate or a lover.''
   Not the case for the adoring couple profiled in ``Young at
Heart,'' Wednesday on PBS, which won this year's Academy Award as
best short-subject documentary.
   It is a bald-faced love story with a happy ending. Louis
Gothelf, 85, and Reva Shwayder, 84, two artists _ he paints
portraits, she paints flowers she grows in her garden _ found that
being old doesn't mean an end to romance.
   The film was made by Sue Marx, Gothelf's daughter, and Pamela
Conn.
   Gothelf and Mrs. Shwayder met when they went on a painting tour
of England and were seated next to each other on the plane. They
talked all the way. Once they arrived, it sounded like something of
a twist on ``A Room with a View.''
   Louis had a large room with lovely scenery out the window. Mrs.
Shwayder was stuck with closet-like accommodations. She showed up
at his door with her luggage, and the rest was history.
   They decided to live together, because as Mrs. Shwayder says,
``When you're young you should get married. But when you're old,
what difference does it make?''
   The film is captivating in its simplicity. Gothelf and Mrs.
Shwayder are two wise, funny people whose bodies might be old, but
whose minds are young and open.
   Mrs. Shwayder has an especially good line that will likely end
up tacked on a lot of walls _ ``Housework is the worst enemy of an
artist.''
   The camera follows the couple to an art gallery where they both
coo over a John Singer Sargent portrait, but later argue the
relative merits of various examples of modern art.
   Mrs. Shwayder points out that Gothelf learned to paint in the
'20 and '30s, but she didn't begin until the 1950s, so she has a
more modern view.
   Later in the film, we learn that Gothelf's wife had Alzheimer's
disease, a progressive disorder that affects the mind. He cared for
her through 10 years of sickness before she died.
   Mrs. Shwayder had lost her entire family. Her son died of cancer
in his 40s. Then her husband passed away. Her other son later
drowned while scuba diving.
   Gothelf shows a portrait he painted of Mrs. Shwayder a few weeks
after the tragedy. He couldn't get her to smile.
   In one of the film's loveliest scenes, he paints a new portrait,
this time with Mrs. Shwayder where she's happiest, at her easel.
   Sitting together in the evening, cocktails in hand, Mrs.
Shwayder sums up the sentiment that leads the two to a marriage,
documented in the film: ``We're both getting older,'' she says. ``I
hope if anything happens to him, I'll be able to take care of him,
and if anything happens to me, he'll take care of me. That's what I
call love.''
   This is what viewers will call a very nice program.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   NEWS FROM GERALDO _ Gerald Rivera will put Lee Harvey Oswald on
trial this fall on Nov. 22, the 25th anniversary of the
assassination of President Kennedy, and Nov. 23, says the Tribune
Entertainment Co. which announced three more specials by Rivera.
The first, in October, will air on NBC, no subject matter yet.
Likewise another in April. Both it and the Oswald trial will be
syndicated. ...
   `TRACEY' AND `DUET' SWITCH _ Fox is flip-flopping the time
periods of two of its most critically praised shows. As of July 10,
``The Tracey Ullman Show'' will be seen at 9:30 p.m. EDT, changing
time periods with ``Duet,'' which will be seen at 10 p.m.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, July 4</NOTE>
