<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   07-01 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0525</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices have risen ose sharply,
abruptly ending a two-day decline as rain tapered off in the Farm
Belt and drought fears regained the upper hand on the Chicago Board
of Trade.
   Wheat futures turned in the strongest performance Thursday, in a
rally driven by concern about further drought damage to the spring
wheat crop in the northern Great Plains and worries that
Wednesday's heavy rains in the central and southern Plains would
hamper progress on the winter wheat harvest.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new age in environmental monitoring is set
to begin.
   Today was the deadline under a 1986 law for 30,000 industrial
installations to file with federal and state authorities an
estimated 1.5 million pages reporting all their releases of 328
hazardous chemicals to the environment in 1987.
   The Environmental Protection Agency is supposed to put the
information into a data base for access via personal computers by
sometime next year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A consumer group is urging Agriculture
Secretary Richard E. Lyng to rewrite regulations that it contends
allow millions of chickens contaminated with bacteria to reach U.S.
homes.
   Community Nutrition Institute officials said Thursday they asked
Lyng in a letter to rescind current regulations that allow
processors to wash poultry.
   ``No amount of washing can help poultry once bacteria become
firmly attached,'' an executive of the group said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists have determined the atomic
structure of Earth's most common protein, a feat experts say
eventually may help them increase food production and design new
drugs.
   Biochemist David Eisenberg, whose study was published in today's
issue of the journal Science, spent 18 years determining the
three-dimensional arrangement of RuBisCO, a protein that sustains
life by making plants grow.
   Such knowledge eventually may help researchers design proteins
to kill cancers, treat diabetes, destroy blood clots and even make
better laundry detergents.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greece assumes the presidency of the
European Economic Community midway into a year that has produced
some of the biggest successes in the trade bloc's 31-year history
but still faces friction with the United States over farm trade.
   The socialist government of Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou,
which often is out of step with the priorities of its 11 EEC
partners, takes over the rotating presidency from West Germany
today. He is likely to emphasize improving the economic prospects
of Europe's poorer and less industrialized regions.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rose broadly Thursday, with the Dow Jones average
of 30 industrials closing up 19.73 points at 2,141.71.
   Bond prices moved higher. The Treasury's long bond was up about
$6 per $1,000 in face amount; its yield fell to 8.85 percent from
8.92 percent late Wednesday.
   The dollar finished narrowly mixed. Gold prices were mixed.
   Crude oil futures prices fell to their lowest level this year in
active trading, while soybean futures shot higher on renewed fears
of drought damage.
</TEXT>
