<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 0148EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ForeignTourists Bjt   07-01 0910</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Foreign Tourists, Bjt,0936</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>From Tucson To Manhattan, Foreigners Visiting In Record Numbers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Italians are riding the range in Arizona. West Germans are
inspecting plantations in South Carolina. And Japanese are teeing
up wherever they find a nice golf course.
   Heading into the Independence Day weekend, tourism officials
were predicting the lure of the cheaper dollar would help bring a
record 30.2 million foreign visitors to the United States this year.
   The expected increase is modest, up less than 2 percent from
29.7 million last year. And not all of the visitors are tourists.
Many come for business, as students, or to visit friends and
relatives.
   But the financial power of foreign visitors _ they are expected
to spend a record $22.1 billion here this year _ is reshaping the
hospitality business.
   ``The U.S. is on sale,'' William D. Toohey, president of the
Travel Industry Association of America, told foreign tour operators
last month in a gathering held in Dallas in May.
   Americans are learning to provide the amenities they get when
they travel abroad. Multilingual signs are popping up. Some
big-city hotels now have same-day delivery of Japanese newspapers.
   Tourism professionals also say they have to cater to the
particular tastes of specific nationalities.
   It turns out many West Germans have a fascination with the
pre-Civil War South, while Europeans of all kinds feel they haven't
seen America without a pony ride way out West.
   ``I have 82 Italians here right now,'' Bob Cote, the owner and
camp cook of the Tanque Verde Ranch outside Tucson, Ariz., said
Thursday. ``Cowboys and Indians are typically American, so that's a
strong image for them.''
   Although for some foreigners the United States has not become a
major travel bargain _ it is not much cheaper for Canadians than it
used to be and has become more expensive for Mexicans _ shifting
exchange rates have doubled the power of currencies such as the
Japanese yen and West German mark since early 1985.
   The 11.8 million Canadians who are expected to arrive this year
vastly outnumber visitors from other countries, while Mexicans are
second at 6.4 million, according to projections of the U.S. Travel
& Tourism Administration.
   But the border nations are getting less notice lately than the
free-spending Japanese, who are in third place and rising rapidly.
   About 2.8 million Japanese are expected this year, up 30 percent
from 1987, the fastest growth rate of any major country. The growth
should continue under Japan's Ten Million Program, which seeks to
double the annual number of Japanese tourists going abroad to 10
million by 1991.
   Hawaii has been a popular Japanese tourist spot, drawing about
1.2 million Japanese visitors. Tourism officials have tried to help
by putting up many signs in Japanese _ perhaps too many.
   ``Some of them have come to me and said, `We're going to visit
in a foreign land; we ought to be able to fend for ourselves,'''
said Gene Cotter, senior vice president for marketing at the Hawaii
Visitors Bureau. ``You're damned if you do and damned if you
don't.''
   A step at a time, cautious Japanese tourists have ventured from
Hawaii, to the West Coast, to New York City, where shopping at
Tiffany's and bus tours through Harlem are popular.
   Around 1986, the Japanese began to discover Washington. All
Nippon Airways, which began direct flights between Tokyo and
Washington that year, says an expansion to daily service has been
held back only by a lack of pilots and planes.
   The United States is a paradise of fairways and greens to the
Japanese, some of whom do most of their golfing back home on
multi-tiered driving ranges because it is so hard to get a tee time
on crowded courses.
   Japanese visitors tend to stick to well-traveled routes, while
Europeans are more willing to rent a car and discover America. But
even the Europeans don't spend a lot of vacation time in heartland
states such as Iowa.
   Farmers from more than 25 countries are expected to compete in
the plowing match during the World Ag Expo at the Amana Colonies in
September, but sightseers from abroad are fairly scarce in Iowa,
said Skip Strittmatter, marketing manager for the state Bureau of
Visitors and Tourism.
   South Carolina capitalized on the popularity of the ``North and
South'' television series about the Civil War, which was shown
twice in West Germany, by offering a free trip to the Palmetto
State in a joint promotion with a German women's magazine, Das Neue
Blatt.
   The states, locales and tourist attractions that are most
successful in attracting foreign visitors are the ones who began
their efforts before the dollar's big decline, said Hawaii's
Cotter. Hawaii, for example, has representatives spread from
Vancouver, British Columbia, to Thailand and Brunei.
   Disney World in Florida is famed for its marketing to Latin
America.
   In Washington, D.C., Hogate's restaurant expects 60 percent of
its customers will come from abroad this year, the culmination of
marketing efforts that Harriet Epstein has pushed for seven years.
   The French want window seats, the Japanese like ice cream and
the Germans would rather have a Budweiser than a German beer,
Hogate's discovered. The homework, and the sales calls to tour
operators, paid off.
   ``When the tidal wave started to turn in our direction, we were
on the receiving end,'' said Ms. Epstein, the sales director. ``Our
name was on the tip of their tongues.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
