<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 0153EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ContinentalPleas Bjt   07-01 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Continental Pleas, Bjt,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Bank Officers Enter Guilty Pleas In Continental Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former officer of Continental Illinois National
Bank & Trust Co. and a former Oklahoma banker will seek probation
after pleading guilty to charges related to Continental's historic
near-collapse, a lawyer says.
   But prosecutors plan to seek prison terms for John R. Lytle, who
admitted misapplying bank funds, and William G. Patterson, who
admitted helping Lytle with the scheme.
   Both entered into a plea agreement Thursday before U.S. District
Judge Milton I. Shadur, nearly two months after a trial of the pair
ended in a mistrial.
   ``It definitely closes the chapter on the Continental Bank-Penn
Square relationship,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney Joseph Duffy
after Shadur accepted the defendants' guilty pleas and set
sentencing for Aug. 30.
   Each man could get 5 years in prison and a $5,000 fine, but
Lytle's attorney said the defendants would seek probation.
   ``We are looking forward to getting all this behind Mr. Lytle
after a long, long road,'' said attorney James Streicker.
   Penn Square failed in 1982, and Continental came close to
collapse two years later after the largest run on deposits in
banking history, following disclosure that it held millions in poor
energy-related loans. The government kept Continental's doors open
with a record $4.5 billion bailout.
   Lytle, 53, a former vice president who once headed Continental's
oil and gas lending operation in Oklahoma, said: ``I feel we've
come to an agreement that's fair to everyone.''
   Patterson's attorney, Warren Bickford had no comment. His
client, who once had assets valued at $2 million, left the
courtroom in tears.
   Lytle and Patterson were indicted on charges of wire fraud and
misapplication of bank funds, and went to trial in March. But after
seven weeks, the proceeding ended May 3 when the jury became
deadlocked and Shadur declared a mistrial.
   A new trial on eight counts each of wire fraud and three counts
each of misapplication of bank funds was scheduled to begin in
September.
   Lytle was accused of buying millions of dollars in poor-quality
loans from Penn Square Bank in return for kickbacks from Patterson.
   Patterson, 38, former head of energy lending at Penn Square in
Oklahoma City, was accused of arranging the kickbacks in the form
of $585,000 worth of unsecured personal loans to Lytle between 1980
and 1982.
   The jury in the first trial cleared a third defendant, Oklahoma
drilling contractor Jere Sturgis, of wire fraud charges for his
alleged role in a scheme to defraud Continental.
   Patterson was accused of manipulating Lytle and Sturgis in
schemes to save his own failing bank.
   The government said Lytle was caught in spiraling personal debt
to finance a luxurious lifestyle and accepted kickbacks from
Patterson in exchange for taking risky energy loans off Penn
Square's hands at Continental's expense.
   The indictment cited Lytle's involvement in $44 million in loans
made by Continental to 12 Penn Square customers. It did not say how
much was recovered by the Chicago bank.
   In Thursday's guilty plea, Lytle and Patterson admitted
arranging for Continental to buy a $2.25 million loan made by Penn
Square to one of its customers to cover a bad business deal of his
partner, who was already millions of dollars in debt to Penn
Square, Duffy said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
