<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 0754EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Drought-At-A-Glance     07-01 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-At-A-Glance,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought At A Glance</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here is summary of recent developments in the drought gripping
most of the Midwest and Southeast.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>RAIN
   Heavy rain muddied parts of the Plains Thursday and today,
bringing relief to farmers but causing some flooding in Kansas.
   Some fields in northeastern Kansas, plus roads and bridges, were
under up to 5 feet of water Thursday. The heaviest rain reported
was 12 inches in Douglas County, Okla.
   </HEAD>
<HEAD>BEEF PRICES
   Dean Kleckner, president of the American Farm Bureau, said beef
prices should be dropping as a result of the drought. He made the
comments to about 300 representatives of farm organizations, food
processors and retailers attended a three-day conference in St.
Louis on agricultural competitiveness and quality sponsored by the
Department of Agriculture.
   Cattle are being sold in droves because of poor pasture
conditions, he said.
   </HEAD>
<HEAD>WHEAT RESERVES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A federal analyst told the National Association of Wheat Growers
that drought will cut the nation's wheat reserves by as much as
half by next June 1.
   Bruce Weber of the U.S. Agricultural Stabilization and
Conservation Service told the growers meeting at Steamboat Springs,
Colo., on Wednesday that the drought could drop the current
inventory of 1.2 billion bushels down to 600 million or 700 million
bushels by next June. That would be the lowest wheat inventory
since three years of sales to the Soviet Union in the early 1970s
diminished the stockpile to 350 million bushels, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
