<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 0959EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-Supercomputers     07-01 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Supercomputers,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Manufacturers ``Disappointed'' At Continued Lack Of Sales</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. supercomputer manufacturers said Friday they
were disappointed with the Japanese government's failure to
purchase U.S.-made supercomputers despite Japan's commitment last
year to encourage such procurements.
   A bilateral agreement to promote, though not guarantee, Japanese
public-sector purchases of U.S. supercomputers went into effect
last August after the United States complained that the Japanese
government was favoring Japanese supercomputers over their American
counterparts.
   ``I think disappointed is the word'' to describe U.S. computer
makers' feeling toward Japanese government procurement of American
supercomputers, John McPhee, director of the U.S. Commerce
Department's Office of Computers and Business Equipment, told
reporters at the Foreign Correspondents Club of Japan.
   Supercomputers are advanced-technology computers that perform
complex calculations at rapid speed and are used in such fields as
science, engineering and the military.
   McPhee said the first three government procurements in Japan
since the agreement went into effect, by the state-run Tohoku and
Hokkaido universities and the High Energy Physics Laboratory, went
to NEC and Hitachi, which along with Fujitsu are Japan's leading
computer makers.
   ``It's curious to us as we look at the data to see that (U.S.
firms) have 80-85 percent of the supercomputer market in the rest
of the world, but a relatively small share of the private sector in
Japan, and until recently had no installations in the Japanese
government,'' McPhee said.
   McPhee headed a delegation of six U.S. supercomputer
manufacturers which conducted a trade seminar and exhibition in
Tokyo this week. The delegation consisted of Cray Research Inc.,
ETA Systems Inc., Evans & Sutherland Computer Corp., Myrias
Computer Corp., Prime Computer Inc., and Scientific Computer
Systems Corp.
   ``The solutions (to performance problems) that these firms bring
to the market are an attractive package for Japanese users,''
McPhee said.
   The delegation came to Japan to familiarize potential Japanese
clients with their technology and to study possible joint marketing
of their products with Japanese partners, said Lee Adamson, Prime
Computer's senior manager for engineering and scientific sales
support.
   ``We're having tremendous interest with prospects for
accounts,'' Adamson said. ``My experience on this mission with
prospects we've talked to and the excitement and interest of our
subsidiary in Japan for the mini-supercomputer market has been very
good, and we expect some major sales in the Japanese market.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880701-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 1014EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Japan-Trade     07-01 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Trade,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan's Current Account Surplus Continues To Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong economic growth cut the broadest measure of
Japan's trade surplus by 19 percent in May from a year earlier and
pushed down the jobless rate to a three-year low of 2.5 percent,
the government said Friday.
   The surplus in the current account, the broadest measure of a
nation's commerce, including trade in goods and services as well as
capital transfers, fell to $5.79 billion from $7.12 billion in
April and $7.11 billion in May 1987, the ministry said.
   May was the second month in a row that the surplus declined from
both previous-month and year-earlier levels.
   During the first three months of the year, Japan's economy grew
at an annual rate of 11.3 percent, its highest level in 11 years.
   The expansion of the economy fueled heavy demand for imports,
including steel, lumber and non-ferrous metals, the Finance
Ministry said. Exports were led by such products as computers and
semiconductors.
   Unemployment in May fell 0.1 percentage point from the previous
month to a seasonally adjusted 2.5 percent, the Management and
Coordination Agency said. The May rate represented a sharp
turnaround from the record high of 3.2 percent registered in the
same month a year earlier.
   The number of job holders hit a record 61 million, up 2.2
percent from 59.8 million a year earlier.
   The official said the number of jobs increased in virtually all
industrial sectors, with companies becoming increasingly eager to
hire new workers to meet growing demand.
   The chief exception was agriculture, which registered a drop of
50,000 jobs during the month, the agency said.
   A 2.5 percent unemployment rate was last registered in April
1985.
   Japan's unemployment rate would be higher if calculated by U.S.
and European methods.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
