<1ST_LINE>u f PM-ElectricBoat 1stLd-Writethru f0023 07-01 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Electric Boat, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0023,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Submarine Yard Employees Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf with 2 grafs to update with arrests, number of
workers on day shift; Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GROTON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 10,000 submarine builders at the
Electric Boat shipyard went on strike today after refusing to
accept the company's offer of lump-sum bonuses instead of wage
increases over the next three years.
   The Metal Trades Council, representing more than half of the
shipyard's 18,000 workers, negotiated with the company until a half
hour before the midnight deadline before announcing an impasse.
   No new talks were planned, union and company officials said
early today.
   About 300 chanting pickets marched outside the gates of the
giant yard under sunny skies this morning. City police reported two
arrests, one of a man setting off fireworks and another of a man
who allegedly drove his car through police barricades in front of
the plant, nearly hitting some pickets.
   Company officials didn't know how many people stayed off the job
today. Union officials said 5,000 blue-collar workers normally
report for the first shift.
   The submarine workers voted 4,921-3,140 Thursday to reject the
latest contract offer from Electric Boat, a division of General
Dynamics Corp.
   Electric Boat is one of only two shipyards making nuclear
submarines for the Navy, and the only manufacturer of giant subs
capable of carrying the Trident ballistic missile.
   Electric Boat General Manager Fritz Tovar said a strike will not
stop submarine construction. The company made arrangements to
reassign 3,000 of its 8,000 salaried employees to new jobs within
the yard, he said.
   Electric Boat offered employees bonuses worth 5 percent of a
worker's wages during the first contract year and 4 percent during
the second and third years of the pact. The union demanded wage
increases of 5 percent, 4 percent and 4 percent.
   The shipyard said it could not afford to raise base pay if it
was to remain competitive in its pursuit of Navy contracts.
   ``We have maintained steadfastly that not increasing the base
(pay) is what is going to close the competitive disadvantage we
have with Newport News Shipbuilding,'' said Electric Boat spokesman
Neil Ruenzel.
   Pickets went up one minute past midnight outside the shipyard's
main gate, located along the Thames River that flows into eastern
Long Island Sound.
   ``No one likes to see a strike,'' said Metal Trades Council
President Joseph Messier. ``The company doesn't like to see it, the
union doesn't like to see it, the community doesn't like to see it,
but it just comes down to you've just got to do what you've got to
do.''
   The last strike at the shipyard was in 1975, when the union
walked out for five months and the region's economy sagged.
   Electric Boat's final offer, presented Monday, called for
bonuses totaling $4,250 over three years for a first-class mechanic
making $12.02 an hour, said Thomas Sotir, vice president of human
resources.
   Earlier Thursday, the Navy awarded this year's third and final
SSN-688 attack submarine contract to Electric Boat. The $347.4
million contract will go to Electric Boat's main shipyard here and
its other plant, in North Kingstown, R.I., which is unaffected by
the strike.
   Newport News, which pays its workers 60 cents an hour less than
Electric Boat, recently won two contracts for nuclear attack
submarines after it underbid Electric Boat.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880701-0266 </DOCNO>
