<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans opened
sharply higher today on the Chicago Board of Trade amid forecasts
for a long, dry Independence Day weekend in the Midwest, analysts
said.
   Corn prices got an additional boost from indications that the
Soviet Union was in the market for U.S. and Argentinian corn. Talk
of Soviet purchases helped drive corn futures up their daily
trading limit of 10 cents a bushel at the opening bell, said Dale
Gustafson, an analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago.
   Early advances in the other trading pits were limited by
profit-taking ahead of the long holiday weekend, he said.
   ``This is a nervous trading market and it will stay that way
today unless someone changes their weather forecast at midday,''
Gustafson said.
   Thursday's monthly grain stocks report from the Agriculture
Department, which showed larger-than-expected stocks of corn, wheat
and soybeans, also offset some of the bullish enthusiusm,, he said.
   In early trading, wheat was 9 cents to 14 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.98{ a bushel; corn was 1{ cents
to 15 cents higher with July, on which the daily price limit has
been removed, at $3.42 a bushel; oats were 2 cents to 13 cents
higher with July at $3.55 a bushel; soybeans were 10{ cents to 22{
cents higher with July at $10.02 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were sharply lower, with pork futures
down their daily limits, in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   The sharp declines in pork futures were linked to Wednesday's
USDA hogs and pigs report, which showed an unexpectedly large U.S.
hog herd, analysts said.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .90 cent lower with August at
63.70 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to .87 cent lower
with August at 73.10 cents a pound; hogs were 1.50 cents lower
across the board with July at 44.82 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were 2 cents lower across the board with July at 35.25
cents a pound.
</TEXT>
