<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru   07-01 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Construction Spending Up, US Debt Widens, Drought Speculators Bid
Up Prices</HEAD>
<HEAD>Grafs 1-7 new with construction spending report, early stock and
bond action, picks up 7th graf pvs, ``As long as...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Big jumps in factory and office building boosted construction
spending 1.1 percent in May, offsetting declines elsewhere, the
government said today in a report that suggested U.S. manufacturers
are actively investing for the future.
   The Commerce Department said that building activity rose to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of $407.1 billion in May following
a 0.2 percent dip in April. In March, construction shot up 2.8
percent.
   The department's report put factory construction at 22.8 percent
above the same level last year, a reflection of strong growth in
America's manufacturing industries because of increased demand,
primarily higher exports.
   But the report also showed a 1 percent decline in residential
construction in May, another indication that higher interest rates
have hurt the housing industry by making mortgage loans
unaffordable to many potential homebuyers.
   In other economic news early today, stocks retreated in
pre-weekend profit taking after a broad gain Thursday but the bond
market rose on the strength of the dollar.
   The U.S. currency's resilience came despite moves Thursday by
West Germany, the Netherlands, Switzerland, Austria and Belgium to
raise their interest rates, which would tend to weaken the dollar.
   The markets also ignored a $99 billion rise in the U.S. foreign
debt for 1987, reported Tursday by the Commerce Department. The
increase to $368.2 billion underscored fears by many critics that
the country is living beyond its means and is losing its worldwide
political and economic might.
   ``As long as the United States has to rely on foreign financing
of such magnitudes, events could at literally any moment trigger a
sharp turndown in our economy,'' said C. Fred Bergsten, director of
the Institute for International Economics in Washington.
   But the Reagan administration contends that the leap in the
nation's debt during its tenure largely reflects the investment
attractions in this country, with foreigners pouring in money to
buy real estate, factories and securities.
   The other big market news Thursday was in Chicago's commodity
pits, where soybean and grain speculators drove prices up sharply,
ending a two-day decline caused by rainfall on the water-starved
farm belt.
   The buying rush came after the National Weather Service issued
its latest 30-day outlook late Wednesday, calling for almost no
rainfall in the critical areas.
   Elsewhere Thursday, the Commerce Department said orders to U.S.
factories for manufactured goods fell 0.6 percent in May,
reflecting a sharp drop in demand for aircraft that was offset by
strength in other areas.
   It was the largest one-month decline since a 1.4 percent drop in
August, but economists weren't concerned because orders had been up
sharply in March and April. They said the May decline actually
could be good for the economy by giving overworked factories an
opportunity to catch up with unfilled orders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880701-0268 </DOCNO>
