<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Canada-Dollar     07-01 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Canada-Dollar,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Coin Will Replace Paper Bill By Mid-1990</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canada's one-dollar coin, nicknamed the Loonie
because one side depicts a swimming loon, will entirely replace the
paper dollar bill within two years, the government has announced.
   The Loonie was introduced last year under a plan to save
taxpayers 175 million Canadian dollars, or about $145 million, over
20 years because coins have a longer circulation life than paper
bills.
   But public acceptance of the gold-colored, 11-sided coin has
been limited and most banks and stores still provide customers with
dollar bills.
   Many Canadians have hoarded Loonies, believing the coin will
share the demise of the Susan B. Anthony dollar coin introduced in
the United States in 1979 and overwhelmingly rejected.
   But the federal government, acting upon recommendations of the
Royal Canadian Mint and House of Commons, says production of dollar
bills will cease on June 30, 1989, and the bills will cease to be
legal tender about one year later, the normal life span of a paper
dollar.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
