<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AsiaPopulation     07-01 0647</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Asia Population,0669</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Asia's Growing Concern: 3 Billion's A Crowd</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven babies are born every second in Asia and the
continent may be only days away from reaching 3 billion
inhabitants, an occasion causing some concern in the world's most
crowded corner, experts said Friday.
   China, faced with a motherlode of maternity, marked the occasion
with a ceremony and speeches that urged its citizens to keep
practicing birth control. In Tokyo, a group of experts gathered to
debate the significance of the approaching milestone, its effects
on the family and the growing problem of feeding all those people.
   Takashi Sato, Japan's minister of agriculture, said ``excessive
population growth will result in shortages of food, resources and
energy ... and environmental destruction beyond national boundaries.
   ``Without global-level responses to the issues of population,
food, environment and development, it would be difficult for the
world to welcome a peaceful 21st century,'' said Sato, chairman of
the Asian Forum of Parliamentarians on Population and Development,
which sponsored the conference.
   In July 1987, the world's population passed 5 billion, double
the population in 1950.
   According to United Nations estimates, Asia's population will
reach 3 billion at 47 minutes after midnight Greenwich Mean Time on
Aug. 10 (8:47 p.m. EDT Aug. 9). Asian experts, however, predict the
milestone will be reached within days.
   Professor Gayl D. Ness of the University of Michigan estimated
that Asia's population would grow to 3.5 billion by the end of the
century and to 4.5 billion by 2025, while the world population
reaches 8.2 billion.
   Rice production will have to increase 50 percent by 2025 to feed
the continent, Ness said, but great gains already have been
registered by farmers in China, Japan and Southeast Asia.
   The 21st century targets ``are well within the realm of
possibility if the agricultural transformation continues. This, of
course, requires sensitive government policies,'' said the
sociologist and researcher on Asian population.
   Asia has made ``substantial progress'' in lowering fertility
rates, and Asian countries were the first to adopt policies to
limit population growth, he said.
   But Ness noted disparities in different regions of Asia. East
Asian countries such as China and Japan, which has 122 million
people, have rapidly declining fertility rates.
   But in South Asia, India is still experiencing 2.08 percent
annual growth in its population of 818 million; Pakistan has 3.45
percent growth with 115 million people; and Bangladesh has 2.67
percent growth rate from a current base of 110 million, according
to U.N. figures.
   ``The challenge lies ahead in completing the demographic
transition and bringing birth rates down to match the fall in the
death rates,'' Ness said.
   He and other panelists were critical of the United States for
withdrawing money from the U.N. Fund for Population Activities
because of the fund's support for abortion.
   The population growth also has caused some social changes.
   Professor Toshio Kuroda, director emeritus of Tokyo's Institute
of Population at Nihon University, noted that China ``expects the
family to care for the aged ... but the family is undergoing
tremendous change in China with the one-child family.''
   China, the world's most populous country with 1.08 billion
people, has since the early 1980s limited most families to one
child. But the limit has been widely flouted in the past two years.
   In Beijing, Chinese officials marked the Day of 3 Billion In
Asia with a ceremony in the Great Hall of the People.
   They handed out cassette players to 18 family planning workers,
doctors and others for ``outstanding performance in implementing
our population policy.''
   Speakers warned that rapid population growth poses a threat to
economic development.
   ``We cannot think that we can have more children because of
economic development ... nor can we relax our efforts because of
progress in family planning,'' said Hu Keshi, forum vice chairman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880701-0272 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 1336EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Soviet-Environment     07-01 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Environment,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Environmental Chief Demands Polluters Be Punished</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polluters should be punished for allowing rampant
industrial waste to push the Soviet Union to the brink of an
ecological disaster, the head of the country's new environmental
protection committee said Friday.
   Fyodor Morgun, chief of the committee that was created in
January, told a Communist Party conference that ``the grave
ecological situation has emerged because of the ill-considered
drive to build gigantic plants.''
   Morgun said the natural fertility of soils is declining, topsoil
is decreasing and forests are ``in an unsatisfactory condition.''
   The air in all industrial centers is polluted ``above the
hygienic standards'' and ``the quality of water in the rivers
worsens nearly everywhere,'' he said.
   He said the Caspian and Baltic seas are polluted and called the
Aral Sea ``a disaster zone.''
   ``Behind the facts of outrages upon nature and damage done to
human health are certain people in science, design institutions and
builders, members of state commissions, with whose blessing
facilities were put into operation which destroy nature,'' Morgun
said.
   ``Those who are responsible for the problems should be mentioned
by name and be punished according to their deserts,'' he added.
   Morgun addressed the 5,000 delegates at the conference a day
after a steelworker from the Urals city of Nizhny Tagil criticized
government leaders for their failure to tackle problems he said had
reached the proportions of ``a Chernobyl-like catastrophe.''
   Steelworker Veniamin Yarin lent force to his appeal by depicting
the situation in his city, where 10,000 people demonstrated earlier
this year against failure to close two 45-year-old coke-fired
furnaces at the city's steel mill.
   One Soviet media report said 54 children were stillborn in the
city last year. Nizhny Tagil has a population of 403,000.
   Yarin said the government should devise an emergency program for
up to 60 Soviet cities he said were polluted beyond all norms.
   The environment has become an issue of great concern to many
Soviets as Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of ``glasnost,'' or
openness, has revealed the extent of ecological damage in candid
media articles.
   The Ural Mountain region is in particularly bad shape. The area
was heavily industrialized during World War II as the Soviets moved
their factories eastward, away from the invading Nazis.
   The Communist Party daily newspaper Pravda said in December that
another Urals industrial city, Ufa, was unfit for human habitation.
   Environmental damage is also a sensitive issue in the Baltic
republics, whose delegations each mentioned the need to tackle what
the Estonians term an ecological ``catastrophe'' in written
platforms submitted to delegates.
   The Communist Party chief of Uzbekistan referred Thursday to the
catastrophic drop in the level of the Aral Sea, a vast inland sea
seriously depleted by schemes to irrigate the arid republics of
Central Asia.
   A newspaper account in 1983 said excessive tapping of the sea
for irrigation had halved its depth in a decade and caused the
shoreline to recede 40 miles in a few years.
   Morgun is head of a committee established in January to deal
with the mounting environmental problems. He said measures have
been outlined to improve the situation, but did not immediately
give any details.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880701-0273 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 1337EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ZIPAnniversary     07-01 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ZIP Anniversary,0639</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ZIP Code Turns 25</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a quarter century on the job, the ZIP
code _ like most of us _ has gained a little weight. But it still
helps smooth the flow of nearly half the world's mail.
   Friday marked the 25th anniversary of that string of numbers
bringing up the rear of every American address, a system ordered
into use by by then-Postmaster General J. Edward Day, who says he
simply got tired of waiting for bureaucrats to finish studying the
idea.
   Day's original five-digit system held sway for 20 years and is
still the most commonly seen.
   An expanded version was introduced in 1983, though, adding four
more numbers to bring the total to nine _ a voluntary addition
officially called ``ZIP Plus 4'' but referred to in postal circles
as ``Son of ZIP.''
   The basic system, says senior assistant postmaster general John
G. Mulligan, has been a ``roaring success.''
   The United States, with only about 6 percent of the world's
population, has 50 percent of the world's mail volume, Mulligan
points out.
   By way of comparison, the New York metropolitan area handles
about the same volume of mail as all of Great Britain, and the
Chicago area's mail is about equal to Japan's, said Day, who now is
retired from government service and is living in a Maryland suburb
of Washington.
   In the 25 years since the introduction of ZIP _ which stands for
Zone Improvement Program _ U.S. mail volume has more than doubled,
but the Postal Service employs only about 15 percent more people,
Mulligan said. And the ZIP system is a big factor in that labor
saving.
   ``No direct calculation of the exact savings has been made,''
Mulligan said in an interview. ``It's hard to separate the effect
of the ZIP code from other things. But believe me, I think it's up
there in the several billions of dollars.''
   In 1963 the United States Post Office carried 67.9 billion
pieces of mail, sorted by human beings at a maximum rate of 800
items an hour. Now reconstituted as the U.S. Postal Service, the
agency handled 153.9 billion pieces last year. With ZIP codes the
mail can be sorted by machines at a rate of 27,000 to 35,000 pieces
an hour.
   Public acceptance has been ``amazing,'' said Mulligan, with ZIP
codes on about 97 percent of the items mailed. Even better, he
added, 95 percent of mail comes in with correct ZIP codes.
   A variety of coding systems had been under study when Day lost
patience. What he did was simply to announce, during a speech in
December 1962, that a new coding system would take effect the
following July 1.
   It worked. Years of study ended and within six months the agency
decided on a five-digit system, divided the nation into regions and
assigned a code to each of the more than 30,000 post offices in the
country.
   The system took effect July 1, 1963, accompanied by promotional
hoopla organized by the Post Office and grumbling by people afraid
they would lose their identities to some anonymous numbers.
   The ZIP code divided the nation into 10 slices, each starting
with a different number, from ``0'' in New England to ``9'' on the
Pacific Coast.
   The next two numbers designate a major city in the area, for
example 606 is Chicago. Finally, the last two numbers localize the
address to a neighborhood post office. And the four newly added
digits in the code narrow the delivery down to one side of a city
block or even one floor of a large office building in a major city.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
