<1ST_LINE>u f BC-EasternShuttle     07-01 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Eastern Shuttle,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eastern Shuttle Sale Canceled</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: An AMs version planned.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines and its parent, Texas Air Corp.,
on Friday canceled a contract calling for Eastern to sell its
popular Northeast shuttle service to another Texas Air subsidiary.
   Eastern gave no explanation for the ``mutual'' cancellation in a
terse news release and said no other details would be forthcoming.
   ``This is one of those releases where we can't make any comment
beyond the text. The release will have to speak for itself,'' said
Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak.
   Spokesmen for Eastern's Machinists union, which battled the
proposed sale in court, and for Houston-based Texas Air did not
immediately return telephone calls.
   The sale of the profitable Washington-New York-Boston shuttle
routes to the newly created Texas Air subsidiary would have brought
the financially ailing Eastern $225 million, company officials have
said.
   In March, U.S. District Judge John H. Pratt in Washington,
ruling on a suit filed by the Machinists, said Eastern, by taking
steps to sell the shuttle, had flouted a July 1987 order that
barred it from transferring 6,000 ground crew members to the other
Texas Air subsidiary.
   But on June 7, the U.S. Court of Appeals in Washington lifted
that injunction. The appeals court said Pratt had erred in holding
Eastern in contempt for taking the steps.
   The International Association of Machinists, which represents
about 13,000 Eastern workers, has long contended that Texas Air
aims to break up the carrier it bought in 1986.
   The Machinists union and Eastern are holding secret contract
talks guided by federal mediators. The union has rejected deep pay
and benefit cuts the company calls necessary to return to
profitability.
   Eastern has lost a total of nearly $1 billion in the past 10
years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
