<DOCNO> AP880701-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 2034EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-China-Airline     07-01 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-China-Airline,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Sets Up Largest Airline in Reorganization of Flag Carrier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's largest airline, Air China, was
established Friday under a plan to revamp the Civil Aviation
Administration of China, the state-run flag carrier that has been
criticized for mismanagement and inefficiency.
   The government announced more than a year ago plans to bring
competition into civil aviation and separate CAAC's government
functions from its business management by creating six airline
companies.
   ``The establishment of Air China is an important achievement for
CAAC in implementing the civil aviation system reform plan,'' Hu
Yizhou, director general of CAAC told a reception at Beijing's
Great Hall of the People.
   Vice Premier Tian Jiyun and representatives of major
international airlines that fly to China attended the reception.
   A large red-and-white banner across the stage bore the words
``Air China'' and the airline's logo, a red phoenix.
   Attendents were dressed in the airline's new uniforms, designed
by Pierre Cardin. The sophisticated two-piece wool outfits and
peaked cap, all in vibrant blue, contrast sharply with the
ill-fitting, blue-gray pantsuits worn by CAAC stewardesses.
   Air China will be the nation's major international carrier,
operating 32 overseas routes to 31 cities in 24 countries. It also
will operate 44 domestic routes to 30 cities.
   The airline, with a fleet of 46 planes and a staff of nearly
1,000, is the third and largest to be established under CAAC's
decentralization plans.
   China Eastern Airlines, based in Shanghai, and the Chengdu-based
Southwest China Airlines were formed earlier this year under the
decentralization plan. CAAC now has a strictly administrative role
and will no longer manage airline business. The airlines operate as
enterprises responsible for their own profits and losses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880701-0279 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 2053EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BusCrash-Settlements     07-01 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Crash-Settlements,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Offers to Settle Out of Court</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Late-afternoon lead planned, following news conference; Also
moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. has offered settlements of
less than $1 million to each of the families of 24 children killed
in a fiery church bus crash, The Courier-Journal reported Friday.
   Citing unidentified lawyers close to the case, the newspaper
also reported that Ford, which manufactured the chassis of the bus
involved in the accident, offered payments to the estates of the
three adults who died and to the 40 survivors of the May 14 crash,
based on the severity of their injuries.
   Lawyer Don Skeeters, a spokesman for the firm that represents
many of the families, would neither confirm nor deny the report.
   Michael Hance, who represents the families of two of the dead
children, said the settlement was being offered by Ford and all
manufacturers responsible for producing the bus, including Sheller
Globe Corp. of Toledo, Ohio, which assembled it.
   Hance declined to disclose the size of the offers, but described
them as ``attractive financially'' to the families and also a good
deal for Ford.
   Robert Waite, a spokesman for the Dearborn, Mich.-based Ford,
said ``delicate'' negotiations were under way but declined comment
on whether a settlement had been offered. Sheller Globe's spokesman
did not return phone calls.
   The wreck occurred as the converted school bus, owned by the
Radcliff First Assembly of God Church, was returning 67 people to
the church after a day at an amusement park. Police say the
accident was caused by a drunken driver traveling the wrong way on
Interstate 71.
   But investigators have said other factors combined to increase
the loss of life, including the bus' lone rear exit door and
crowded conditions inside. Authorities have also pointed to the
bus' gas tank, which ruptured in the crash and burst into flames,
with the smoke from the resulting fire blamed for all 27 deaths.
   The bus was apparently one of the last manufactured in 1977
before a new federal rule required bus fuel tanks be sheathed in
protective cages.
   Prominent mass-disaster lawyers said it would be highly unusual
for such a major case to be settled even before lawsuits were filed.
   Washington, D.C., lawyer John Coale, who represents one family
and has been active in several air-disaster cases, said it would be
``unconscionable'' to settle so quickly without exploring whether
Ford might be liable for punitive damages.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880701-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 1601EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-ForeignTourists 1stLd-Writethru   07-01 0807</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Foreign Tourists, 1st Ld-Writethru,0839</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Tourists Bring Dreams, Dollars To U.S.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 7th graf, Nigel and ..., to CLARIFY with
actual value of dollar vs. pound; picks up 8th graf pvs,
``Everything is ....</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marie Lemoin came to the United States with a
bag full of dreams and a fist full of dollars.
   The French woman is part of the wave of foreigners taking
advantage of the weak dollar to visit America and splurge on goods
that have become bargains in terms of their own currencies.
   Ms. Lemoin, 21, arrived in New York this year carrying a
suitcase, a satchel stuffed with guidebooks and slick tourist
brochures and a wad of travelers' checks and assorted U.S. currency.
   She said she never expected her money to go so far.
   But Yvonne Gomez and her husband, Ramiro, of Sao Paulo, Brazil,
stopped in New York en route to a European vacation, expecting to
pick up a lot of bargains.
   ``We're taking his wallet to my favorite places _ Saks and
Bloomingdale's,'' said Mrs. Gomez, anticipating her shopping spree
at two of New York's most stylish department stores.
   Nigel and Rosy Collins of London took their vacation in the
United States for the same reason. They estimated their week-long
trip would cost about half what they would have paid two years ago.
   They may have been carried away in their enthusiasm, since the
dollar is only 10 percent cheaper against the pound than it was at
the end of June 1986.
   ``Everything is so warm, so new, so cheap,'' he said.
   ``And you have Don Johnson,'' his wife added, referring to the
star of popular television detective series ``Miami Vice.''
   Foreigners have been lining up to get into the Empire State
Building, to catch a ride on the Staten Island ferry past the
Statue of Liberty, and to buy half-price tickets for Broadway
shows. They have been packing restaurants in Chinatown and Little
Italy.
   Elsewhere, record crowds are converging on the beaches, popular
tourist attractions in southern Florida and California.
   And the numbers are expected to swell during the summer.
   The rise in foreign tourism is due largely to the weak dollar,
which has doubled the buying power of the Japanese yen and West
German mark since early 1985. Most other nations' currencies also
buy more here.
   By the end of the year, the U.S. Travel and Tourism
Administration predicts a record 30.2 million foreigners will have
visited the United States as tourists, on business, or on visits to
friends and relatives.
   ``I'm hearing French, German and Japanese everywhere. It's like
a language school outside my office,'' said Michael Finley,
superintendent of Florida's 1.4 million-acre Everglades National
Park, where attendance is up more than 40 percent over last year.
   Nearly half of the foreign visitors will come from neighboring
Canada and Mexico, the tourism administration said. But more
Japanese and Europeans are expected to visit than ever before.
   ``Projections are that British, German, and French travel to the
U.S. will hit a new record, and Japan will hit a new record
again,'' said Ron Erdmann of the agency's research office.
   The number of visiting Brazilians also is expected to increase,
in part due to that government's decision to rescind the 25 percent
surtax on overseas plane tickets and on U.S. dollars purchased for
foreign travel.
   Executives at the Resort Hotel Association of Miami Beach, said
they thought they were overly optimistic when they sent their
London tourism office 20,000 brochures touting package deals to the
Florida beach resort.
   ``We were gambling. But in 10 days, we ran out,'' said Murray
Gold, executive director of the association. ``The requests coming
in are phenomenal. We never expected it.''
   Ms. Lemoin, who left France a year ago to study languages in
Sheffield, England, said at first she did not think she could
afford a trip to America. Her home is in Toulouse.
   ``My aunt always told me the first place I should visit was `the
States,''' she said. ``But I thought it would be too expensive.''
   It only took an outing in New York's Greenwich Village and Soho
areas to dispel that notion.
   ``I've been able to buy whatever I want,'' she said, looking out
into New York Harbor from the top of the 110-story World Trade
Center.
   ``I hope to have a lot more of these before I go home,'' she
said, pointing to a huge bag stuffed with a variety of souvenirs,
including T-shirts, postcards, coffee mugs and an apple-shaped key
ring emblazoned with ``I Love New York.''
   And that was just the beginning, she said.
   She pulled out a color pamphlet from the Arizona tourist ageny
and said: ``I'm disappointed the only place I won't get to see is
the Grand Canyon.''
</TEXT>
