<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Corn Closes Limit-Up On Drought Fears, Export Rumors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn futures prices closed sharply higher Friday
on the Chicago Board of Trade, with most contracts up the limit for
daily trading on a combination of drought fears and rumors of
Soviet purchases.
   Forecasts for a warm, dry Independence Day weekend in the
Midwest also supported wheat and soybean futures, but oat prices
dropped sharply on indications that U.S. millers were importing
oats from Argentina, analysts said.
   ``Corn was very strong and rumors of Russian buying were
rampant,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader for Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc. He said the Soviets were believed to have purchased
500,000 to 1 million metric tons of U.S. corn and an unknown amount
of Argentine corn.
   Most corn contracts advanced the 10-cents-a-bushel limit and the
limitless contract for July delivery soared even higher.
   Gains in the wheat and soybean trading pits, while substantial,
were held down by Thursday's monthly grain stocks report from the
Agriculture Department, which showed larger-than-expected stocks of
corn, wheat and soybeans, Lespinasse said.
   At the close, wheat was 10 cents to 17 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $4.01 a bushel; corn was 9{ cents
to 14 cents higher with July at $3.41 a bushel; oats were 21 cents
lower to 3 cents higher with July at $3.32 a bushel; soybeans were
1{ cents to 28 cents higher with July at $9.90 a bushel.
</TEXT>
