<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Autos-FactoryVacations     07-01 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Autos-Factory Vacations,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>All U.S. Ford Plants Shut for Two Weeks Vacation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. is shutting all its U.S. factories
for a two-week summer vacation beginning Saturday, allowing the No.
2 automaker to set up the plants to build 1989 models, the company
said Friday.
   Meanwhile, General Motors Corp., the nation's largest automaker,
was still organizing its summer vacation and model changeover
schedules, which will be scattered through July and August.
   Ford has used a nationwide July vacation shutdown for model
changeovers for the past several years, eliminating the need for
temporary layoffs, spokeswoman Judith Muhlberg said.
   ``It's very efficient. Europe shuts down a month in August,''
she said.
   In the United States, however, workers will have to make up the
lost production time with overtime later in the year because of
surging car and truck sales, which have left Ford with low
inventories.
   During the shutdown, some skilled workers at every plant will
have to stay in the factories, installing new tooling and equipment
for next year's models, Ford spokesman Pete Olsen said.
   GM has scheduled a temporary shutdown of its Fiero plant in
Pontiac next week and a two-week model changeover at its Lake Orion
assembly plant beginning July 15.
   The Fiero plant will end production of the sporty,
plastic-bodied two-seater later this summer at the end of the 1988
model run.
   GM's heavy-duty truck assembly line in Pontiac also will close
temporarily starting July 15 and its medium-duty truck assembly
line closes from Aug. 5-8.
   But demand for light-duty trucks is so high that GM's Pontiac
East assembly plant will continue production through the Aug. 4
changeover to 1989 models, as will the Pontiac West plant during an
Aug. 12 changeover.
   Chrysler Corp. reports its model changeover shutdowns a week
ahead of time. The only plant closed is Newark, Del., which shut
for 16 weeks beginning June 17 for modernization and retooling. The
plant, which built the Dodge Aries and Plymouth Reliant K-cars,
will build the new Dodge Spirit and Plymouth Acclaim sedans.
</TEXT>
