<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 1732EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     07-01 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0543</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Strengthens, Gold Up Slightly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose further Friday, strengthened by
pre-holiday buying and the lack of central bank intervention to
dampen the momentum of the U.S. currency's recent advances.
   Gold prices rose slightly in late U.S. trading after steadying
in Europe. Republic National Bank of New York quoted gold at
$437.25 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from $435.10 at the same
time Thursday.
   Money brokers said there was a widespread view in
foreign-exchange markets that the dollar is heading higher for now
because the key industrialized democracies will tolerate the move.
But they said the advance will be slow and orderly, orchestrated
through occasional dollar-selling by central banks.
   Traders at a major Japanese bank in New York, who spoke on the
condition they not be identified, said they saw some significant
orders for dollars Friday from large security companies, further
bolstering the dollar's value.
   Some expressed short-term concern about possible intervention on
Monday by the Bank of Japan in the Tokyo market if the dollar rises
too sharply. But others disagreed.
   ``I don't think there's that much fear of intervention,'' said
James Chorek, currency analyst at Money Market Services in Chicago.
``If there was, you'd have seen it today.''
   In Tokyo, the dollar jumped 2.30 yen to close the week at 134.50
yen, its highest level since Nov. 27 when it closed at 134.75 yen.
Later in London, it was quoted at 134.05 yen. By the time trading
ended in New York, the dollar was worth 134.43 yen, higher than its
133.04 yen-level late Thursday.
   In London, the British pound slid to its lowest point against
the dollar this year, trading as low as $1.69. Late in the
afternoon it was quoted at $1.7023, the lowest level since Oct. 27,
and cheaper than $1.7085 Thursday. In New York, the pound fetched
$1.6960, cheaper than its $1.7115 level Thursday.
   Other late-dollar rates in New York, compared with late Thursday
included: 1.8203 West German marks, up from 1.8155; 1.5135 Swiss
francs, up from 1.5040; 1.2202 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2131;
6.1425 French francs, up from 6.1163; and 1,352.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,344.75.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday:
1.8213 West German marks, up from 1.8170; 1.5130 Swiss francs, up
from 1.5060; 6.1375 French francs, up from 6.1250; 2.0530 Dutch
guilders, unchanged; 1,352.50 Italian lire, up from 1,350.38;
1.2190 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2126.
   Gold prices drifted in a narrow range Friday in Europe but rose
mildly in New York after a big midweek decline. On the Commodity
Exchange, gold for current delivery rose $1.90 a troy ounce to
$437.20.
   Earlier in London, gold closed at $437.50 a troy ounce,
unchanged from Thursday. In Zurich it rose, closing at $437.50 vs.
$436.50 late Thursday. In Hong Kong, gold rose 82 cents an ounce to
close at $440.
   Silver bullion prices rose on the London market, where the metal
was trading at $6.74 a troy ounce, compared with $6.66 Thursday. On
the New York Comex, silver for current delivery rose 2.5 cents an
ounce to $6.703.
</TEXT>
