<FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 2319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Allis-Chalmers     07-01 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Allis-Chalmers,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Allis-Chalmers Files Reorganization Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financially troubled Allis-Chalmers Corp., once
a giant farm equipment manufacturer, on Friday filed a formal
reorganization plan that would formalize the sale its principal
businesses.
   The plan, the final step required to emerge from Chapter 11
bankruptcy protection, must be approved by U.S. Bankruptcy Court
for the Southern District of New York.
   The company, which sought protection from its creditors last
year, said in a statement that the sales of major assets would
raise between $400 million and $425 million, which would be
distributed to creditors.
   Allis-Chalmers already arranged for the sales of its assets.
Last week the company announced an agreement to sell its pump
business to International Telephone and Telegraph Corp. for $71
million.
   Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Wendell F. Bueche called
the agreement ``the final final agreement necessary to complete our
reorganization plan strategy for the sale or merger of our
principal businesses as going concerns.''
   In April Allis-Chalmers said it has agreed to sell its air
quality control business for $245 million to Snyder General Corp.
of Texas.
   The company estimated that, after the payment of priority claims
and secured debt, unsecured creditors will recover approximately 16
to 21 percent of their claims.
   The reorganized Allis-Chalmers would, under the plan, include an
office in West Allis, Wis., and two wholly-owned operating
subsidiaries. They are Houston Dynamic Service Inc., which operates
a machinery repair facility in Houston, Texas, and KILnGAS R&D,
Inc., which has four employees in its current development phase and
manages a coal gasification project at East Alton, Ill.
   Allis-Chalmers said that the plan was conditional, among other
things, on the closing of previously announced sales of the
company's air filter, pump and power generation services businesses.
   The company's existing common stock holders would receive no
cash distributions and approximately 20.6 percent of the
reorganized company's common stock.
   ``The company's goal is to have the plan consummated by year-end
1988,'' Bueche said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
