<HEAD>Corn Futures Post Limit Gains; Oat Rally Called Over</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn prices soared the limit for daily trading Friday but oat
futures dropped sharply in what analysts said might be a signal of
the end of a record-breaking rally.
   Wheat and soybeans advanced strongly in other action on the
Chicago Board of Trade.
   On other markets, pork futures plunged the daily trading limit
while cattle futures were mixed; crude oil prices dropped below $15
a barrel; precious metals were slightly higher; and stock-index
futures retreated.
   Forecasts for a warm, dry July 4 weekend in the drought-stricken
Midwest underpinned gains in most grain and soybean markets.
   ``Corn was very strong and rumors of Russian buying were
rampant,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader for the investment firm
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. He said the Soviets were believed to have
purchased 500,000 to 1 million metric tons of U.S. corn and an
unknown amount of Argentine corn.
   Most corn contracts advanced the 10-cents-a-bushel limit and the
limitless contract for July delivery rose even higher.
   Gains in the wheat and soybean pits, while substantial, were
slowed by Thursday's monthly grain stocks report from the
Agriculture Department, which showed larger-than-expected stocks of
corn, wheat and soybeans, Lespinasse said.
   But it was another story in the oat pit, where prices dropped
sharply on ideas that the drought-driven rally in that market was
over.
   Lespinasse cited rumors of oat imports from Argentina. Other
experts said the reality of yield losses had finally caught up with
the futures market.
   The U.S. oat crop, grown primarily in the northern Great Plains,
``is basically at maturity or close enough to maturity that very
little more damage is going to be done to it now than is already
known,'' said Walter Spilka, grain analyst with Smith Barney,
Harris Upham & Co. in New York.
   Oat futures prices, which hit a record $3.94 a bushel Thursday,
likely will slip as supply-and-demand factors replace
drought-damage fears, Spilka said.
   ``I think we've seen our highs for the year,'' said independent
oat trader Jay Homan.
   The full extent of damage to the corn crop probably will become
apparent next week as stunted plants pass through the critical
pollination stage and speculation will continue to drive the
soybean market for another month, he said.
   ``You've got reality (in the oat market), then you're a week
away from reality (for corn) and a month away from reality (for
soybeans) and that's how the market traded today,'' Homan said.
   The National Weather Service issued a 6-to-10-day forecast after
the close calling for hot, dry weather in most major growing areas
for the period July 7-11.
   Wheat settled 10{ cents to 15{ cents higher with the contract
for delivery in July at $4.00{ a bushel; corn was 9} cents to 15
cents higher with July at $3.42 a bushel; oats were 21 cents lower
to 3 cents higher with July at $3.32 a bushel; soybeans were 2
cents to 17{ cents higher with July at $9.88{ a bushel.
   As expected, pork futures plummeted their daily limits at the
opening on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange and remained locked
limit-down all day in reaction to Thursday's surprising USDA report
showing larger-than-expected increases in both the U.S. hog herd
and the breeding intentions of hog producers.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .95 cent higher with August at
64.60 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .60 cent lower to .42 cent
higher with August at 73.67 cents a pound; hogs were 1.50 cents
lower across the board with July at 44.82 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were 2 cents lower across the board with July at 35.25
cents a pound.
   Crude oil prices slumped below $15 a barrel to their lowest
levels in almost two years after fluctuating wildly on the New York
Mercantile Exchange.
   Analysts were divided on the reasons for the drop. Some cited
technical factors while others pegged the drop to Saudi Arabia's
desire to see lower oil prices.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 18 cents to 22 cents
lower with August at $14.94 a barrel; heating oil was .03 cent to
.10 cent lower with August at 41.02 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .39 cent lower to .29 cent higher with August at 48.35
cents a gallon.
   Precious metals futures advanced slightly in light, choppy
trading on the Commodity Exchange in New York.
   Gold was $1.90 to $2 higher with August at $439.60 a troy ounce;
silver was .40 cent lower to 2.5 cents higher with July at $6.703 a
troy ounce.
   Stock-index futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for September delivery of the Standard
& Poor's 500 index finished 2.5 points lower at 272.90.
</TEXT>
