<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-CSX,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CSX Loses $160 Million In 2nd Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CSX Corp. on Friday reported a
second-quarter loss of $160 million mainly because of a $778
million special charge that will in part cover severance payments
to laid-off employees.
   Excluding the charge, second quarter earnings would have been
$332 million, or $2.12 per share. In the year-ago quarter, the
transportation, energy and technology conglomerate earned $114
million, or 74 cents a share.
   Of the special charge, $592 million will be used for costs
related to reducing the rail labor force to about 30,000 employees.
   About 8,200 employees will receive payments ranging from $30,000
to $50,000, except for locomotive enginemen who are covered under
an existing program that calls for payments of $75,000.
   The remaining $186 million of the special charge covers various
costs and claims pending against CSX and certain subsidiaries.
Those costs are expected to result from litigation and negotiated
settlements.
   CSX President and Chief Operating Officer John W. Snow said the
employee reduction program is part of CSX Transportation's effort
to match the number of rail employees with the operating
requirements of the rail system. CSX Transportation is a subsidiary
of CSX Corp.
   Snow said CSX Corp., since its formation in 1980, has reduced
the physical base of CSX Transportation from 26,748 route miles,
3,343 locomotives and 175,281 freight cars at year-end 1981 to
21,494 route miles, 2,633 locomotives and 116,063 freight cars at
year-end 1987.
   For the first six months of 1988, CSX lost $95 million, compared
with earnings of $199 million, or $1.29 per share for the first
half of 1987.
   Without the special charge, first half earnings would have been
$397 million, or $2.52 per share.
</TEXT>
