<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Fall; Construction Spending Rises</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil prices have fallen to their lowest levels in almost
two years, a development that helped cool inflation concerns and
lift bond prices.
   The contract for August delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the
benchmark U.S. crude oil, plunged 22 cents per 42-gallon barrel
Friday, piercing the $15 level to settle at $14.94 on the New York
Mercantile Exchange.
   Along with the fall in oil, bond prices were boosted modestly by
a stronger dollar and fresh foreign demand. The yield of the
Treasury's key 30-year bond, which falls when prices rise, dipped
to 8.83 percent from 8.85 percent late Thursday.
   In other economic news, construction of offices and factories
increased strongly in May, the government said Friday in a report
that indicated healthy economic growth.
   On Wall Street, stock prices fell and the Dow Jones average of
30 industrials dropped 10.13 points to 2,131.58, closing out the
week with a net loss of 11.38 points.
   Overall construction spending advanced 1.1 percent in May, the
Commerce Department said. The increase was led by a 7.8 percent
advance in office construction and a 7.7 percent advance in factory
construction.
   In contrast, residential construction fell 1 percent.
   The big jump in factory construction reflected the capital
spending boom occurring as manufacturers rush to expand capacity to
meet sharply higher demand for U.S. exports.
   Analysts said the rise in office construction, after a sustained
period of weakness, reflected strong activity in certain sections
of the country such as the Northeast and a halt to the giant plunge
in building which had occurred in the Southwest, hard hit because
of troubles in the oil patch.
   ``Cities such as Chicago, New York, Boston and Washington, D.C.,
are enjoying good economic growth and a fair amount of offfice
construction,'' said Richard Peach, senior economist for the
Mortgage Bankers Association. ``This is happening while the sharp
declines in other areas have at least bottomed out.''
</TEXT>
