<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Incentives, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0262,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chevy, Buick, Oldsmobile Extend Incentives through Sept. 28</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead and adds one graf on Pontiac rebates; SUBS
penultimate graf pvs to restore dropped figure in Skylark rebate;
$400 sted $00.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp.'s Chevrolet, Buick, Pontiac
and Oldsmobile divisions Friday extended through Sept. 28 buyer
incentive campaigns that were to expire on Tuesday.
   Many of the Chevrolet rebates will be leaner, but Buick rebates
will continue unchanged except for the LeSabre, which was dropped
from the program, a spokeswoman said.
   Chevrolet also dropped its double rebate on the Nova and
Spectrum subcompacts, said spokeswoman Mary McElyea. As intended,
the program increased the number of import owners who shopped at
Chevrolet dealerships, but irritated some domestic-car owners.
   Chevrolet trimmed rebates by $100 to $400 on Beretta and $300 on
Corsica and the Cavalier two-door model and by $250 on Camaro, to
$500. Rebates increased by $100 to $500 on Cavalier four-door and
wagon and $60 on Nova and Spectrum.
   Chevrolet also added the Sprint to the program, with a $300
rebate, McElyea said.
   Rebates on Chevrolet trucks remain unchanged and range from $300
on the S-10 pickup EL model to $750 on the four-wheel-drive S-10
Blazer.
   Buick rebates range from $1,000 on Electra-Park Avenue to $400
on Skylark. Buick also added a range of option-package discounts.
   Meanwhile, Oldsmobile's rebates included $1,000 on the
Oldsmobile Ninety-Eight; $500 on Cutlass Ciera; $400 on Cutlass
Calais, and free air conditioning on the Cutlass Supreme and
Supreme SL.
   Pontiac said its rebates range from $600 on the Fiero to $250 on
the Sunbird.
</TEXT>
